<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Bank Bills </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japanese upper house approves bank failure measures
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's upper house of Parliament on Monday voted
into law a plan to use at least 10 trillion yen (dlrs 86 billion)
in taxpayer money to clean up the nation's massive bad debt problem
and deal with failed banks.
	   The package, which was passed by the more powerful lower house
on Oct. 2, marks a major step in Japan's battle against its deepest
recession since the end of World War II.
	   With Japan under pressure to turn around its economy and help
Asian neighbors, the bills also are a major victory for Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi and end a fierce dispute between his ruling
party and the opposition.
	   The so-called financial stabilization plan creates a special
committee to oversee the clean up of the nearly dlrs 1 trillion in
bad debts weighing on the nation's financial system.
	   With new loans hard to get, business has been suffering,
especially small and medium-size companies. Unemployment is at a
record high, bankruptcies are soaring and consumer spending is
falling.
	   Under the new law, the government would set up an organization
similar to the U.S. Resolution Trust Corp. in the 1980s U.S.
savings and loan crisis to buy bad debt from banks.
	   The committee created by the new package has the authority to
pursue three courses of action when dealing with a failed bank: to
nationalize the bank temporarily through the government's purchase
of its shares; to order the liquidation of the institution; or to
transfer the bank's operations to a public bridge bank.
	   It was unclear, however, what standards would be used to decide
which banks would fall under each method. But the pool of public
money to help will total more than 10 trillion yen (dlrs 86
billion).
	   The bills also abolish a 13 trillion yen (dlrs 113 billion) fund
that previously was used to pump public money into the banking
system to recapitalize banks.
	   (jc-apdj)
</TEXT>
