w2735 &Cx1f; wstm-
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Cricket-Johnso     10-12 0267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Johnson-Obit </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former Australian captain dies
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) _ Former Australian cricket captain
Ian Johnson has died aged 80, Australian Cricket Board chairman
Denis Rogers said Monday.
	   Rogers said Johnson died in hospital on Friday after a long
period of poor health.
	   Johnson, a member of the Invincibles side that was unbeaten on
the 1948 tour of England, played 45 tests between 1945 and 1957,
scoring 1,000 runs at 18.52 and taking 109 wickets at 29.19.
	   He captained Australia from 1954-57, leading the team in the
1954-55 Ashes series against England in Australia and on tours to
the West Indies (1954-55), England (1956) and Pakistan and India
(1956-57).
	   ``Ian was the off-spinner for the great Australian teams
immediately after the Second World War and a wonderful ambassador
for our country as captain,'' Rogers said. ``The sides he led to
the West Indies and Pakistan and India were the first official
tours to each of those regions and he built the foundations for the
relationships that exist today between Australia and our fellow
test nations.''
	   Johnson was a fighter pilot for the Royal Australian Air Force
during World War II and became a cricket administrator after
retiring from play. He was secretary of the Melbourne Cricket Club
for 25 years.
	   In 17 Tests under Johnson's captaincy, Australia won seven
matches, lost five and drew five.
	   At the time of his retirement, he was only the fifth Australian
to complete the ``double'' of 1,000 runs and 100 wickets in Test
cricket.
 &UR; (tjh)
</TEXT>
