<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Stocks surge on passage of banking reform bills, dollar falls
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS to UPDATE with early afternoon Nikkei moving higher on
upper house passage of bank bills, latest dollar and bond &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japanese stocks surged in Monday afternoon trading,
lifted by the passage in Parliament of bills designed to address
the nation's ailing banks. The U.S. dollar fell against the yen.
	   The benchmark Nikkei Stock Average rose 612.82 points, or 4.76
percent, moving to 13,492.79 by early afternoon. On Friday, the
index had tumbled 146.09 points, or 1.12 percent, closing at
12,879.97 _ its lowest finish since December 1985.
	   Also in early afternoon trading, the dollar bought 115.90 yen,
down 1.30 yen from late Friday in Tokyo and also below its late
Friday level in New York of 116.95 yen.
	   Share prices continued to rally after Japan's upper house of
Parliament voted into law a plan to use public funds to clean up
the country's massive bad debt problem and deal with failed banks,
traders said.
	   The package, which was passed by the more powerful lower house
on Oct. 2, marks a major step in Japan's determination to bail the
nation out of its deepest recession since the end of World War II.
	   The market started higher on expectations that the government
would soon expand a pool of public funds to assist ailing Japanese
banks, traders said.
	   Also supporting the market was Friday's rally in blue chips on
Wall Street.
	   ``The impact from the rise in New York stocks is more than
expected,'' said Setsuo Nagao, a manager at the equity division of
Tokyo Securities.
	   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 167.61, or 2.17 percent,
to 7,899.52 points, a gain of 114.83 for the week and just shy of
7,908.25 where it began the year.
	   Japanese media reported over the weekend that the ruling and
opposition parties have agreed to expand to 67 trillion yen (dlrs
577 billion) the pool of public funds to boost the capitalization
of weak banks
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 38.05 points, or 3.87 percent, to 1,020.55. On
Friday, the TOPIX fell 19.00 points, or 1.93 percent.
	   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar moved lower on
selling from Japanese institutional investors and possibly by hedge
funds in a thin local market, traders said.
	   Last week, the dollar dropped nearly 14 percent, falling as low
as 111.45 on Thursday before recovering somewhat.
	   The selling was fueled largely by hedge funds moving to dump
dollars in uncertain markets amid hopes for greater efforts by
Japan to mend its weak economy and the gloomier outlook for the
U.S. economy.
	   Haruhiko Kuroda, the head of the Japanese Finance Ministry's
international bureau, said Monday that volatility like that which
took place last week was undesirable.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese
government bond rose to 0.860 percent from Friday's finish of 0.790
percent, driving its price down to 108.39 yen from 109.08. 	   
</TEXT>
