w2764 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HongKong-Economy     10-12 0453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hong Kong poll shows half of business leaders expect economy to
</HEADLINE>
weaken

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Hong Kong's economic decline is expected to
continue in the next six months, half of 150 leading firms in the
territory said in a poll released Monday.
	   Jointly conducted by brokerage Nomura International and the
South China Morning Post, the polls is the first in a series to be
carried out quarterly to gauge business and economic sentiment.
	   ``The results are negative. More than 50 percent of firms say
the economic outlook will deteriorate in the next six months,''
Nomura's Greater China economist Kevin Chan said.
	   Hong Kong fell into a recession in the second quarter, with the
economy shrinking by 5 percent. It is expected to contract by at
least 4 percent this year, while unemployment is at a 15-year high
of 5 percent.
	   But most respondents expected the growth in unemployment to
ease. More than two-thirds said they would not lay off workers in
the next six months, and only 19 percent expected more layoffs in
their companies.
	   About 33 percent said they did not expect economic conditions to
change in the period, while 11.9 percent said the economy would
pick up.
	   ``Overall, it's bearish, but responses from China-related
companies were least bearish, followed by property, banks, and
private listed companies,'' Chan said.
	   Hong Kong could be facing negative inflation next year, pushing
real interest rates higher, he said, noting that 60 percent of the
firms said property prices would fall.
	   Of the 50 listed companies polled, half said their net profit
margins would decline, indicating that earnings forecasts for 1999
are ``overly optimistic,'' Chan said.
	   Despite high interest rates, firms are still willing to invest
and are optimistic in the long term, he said.
	   ``A lot of firms would like to diversify away from properties,''
he said.
	   All the banks surveyed said interest rates would remain constant
over the next six months, the Post reported.
	   More than two-thirds of those polled said they agreed with the
government's highly criticized efforts to ward off financial
turmoil by intervening in the stock and futures markets. But many
said that the move should have been better planned and implemented.
	   During two weeks in late August, the government spent an
estimated U.S. dlrs 15 billion buying up stocks and futures to
stabilize the markets in an effort to drive out what it called
``market manipulators,'' or speculators.
	   Questionnaires were sent to 300 leading companies, and the 150
respondents included 50 listed companies, including a majority of
the 33 members of the blue-chip Hang Seng stock index. 	   
</TEXT>
