w2766 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Taiwan-China     10-12 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-China </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwan calls for new thinking ahead of meetings with China
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER BODEEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ Premier Vincent Siew urged China to sweep
away obstacles to a restoration of dialogue during crucial meetings
this week, and said Taiwan would not rule out discussing any issue.
	   Those contacts mark the start of a ``new stage'' in relations
frozen for three years by China's suspension of dialogue, Siew said
in an address Monday to a 12-member delegation led by senior envoy
Koo Chen-fu.
	   Koo's delegation departs for China on Wednesday.
	   ``We hope that the two sides will use new thinking and a new
approach to face the issues (and) rebuild a framework for relations
suited to the conditions of separation between the two sides,''
Siew said.
	   The premier's comments appeared to be a final appeal for China
to seize the opportunity of Koo's visit to pave the way for
restoring formal talks.
	   China has made negotiations conditional on Taiwan agreeing to
discuss political issues relating to their reunification, but the
island has urged agreement be first reached on practical matters to
build trust.
	   Siew reiterated comments he made in February that Taiwan would
be willing to discuss any matter that aided peaceful relations and
eventual reunification. But he added that Taiwan would not be
dictated to by Beijing, and said the sides should regard each other
as equals.
	   Though careful not to promise results, Taiwan has expressed
cautious optimism over Koo's visit. At the least, contacts should
``nurture a pleasant atmosphere (and) advance constructive
relations,'' Siew said.
	   Receiving a letter of authorization to represent Taiwan in the
informal meetings, Koo told reporters he felt the mission was a
``great responsibility.''
	   Koo's first top will be in Shanghai, where he will meet Wang
Daohan, his Chinese counterpart. Jan Jyh-horng, a deputy secretary
general of Koo's semi-official Straits Exchange Foundation,
departed for China's commercial capital Monday morning to make
final preparations for the visit.
	   The Shanghai meeting will be the first between the elder
statesmen since 1993 talks in Singapore that marked the first
formal contact between the sides since they split politically amid
civil war in 1949.
	   Based on the agreement they reached, the sides held talks on
practical issues such as recognition of legal documents, until
China backed out in June 1995 in anger over Taiwan's efforts to
raise its international profile.
	   China regards Taiwan as a breakaway province with no right to
foreign relations and refuses to recognize the government in
Taipei. 	   
</TEXT>
