<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Stocks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Share prices surge on interest rate cut hopes
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Shares prices in Hong Kong opened the week
sharply higher Monday, fueled by increasing hopes for both local
and U.S. interest rate cuts.
	   The blue-chip Hang Seng Index was up 660.15 points, or 7.8
percent, to 9,166.94 at midday, its highest intraday level since
May 27. It pushed through the psychological resistance level of
9,000 during a frenetic morning session.
	   Turnover hit 7.46 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs 954
million), compared with 4.09 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs
524 million) in Friday's morning session.
	   Dealers say investors are piling into the market on expectation
that the territory's banks will cut interest rates as early as this
week. Such hopes have fueled a 12-percent rally in the index for
the past three sessions, including Friday's 7.15 percent gain.
	   Hopes of yet another rate cut in the United States at the next
meeting of the Federal Open Market Committee in mid-November are
also bringing institutional investors back to the local market,
traders add.
	   ``There's more fear of being left out than buying high,'' said
Kent Rossiter, head of institutional sales at Nikko Securities Co.
(Asia) Ltd.
	   Property shares rose sharply on hopes of interest rate cuts,
with the sub-index tracking property shares rising 9.9 percent.
	   The gains in Japan's stock market early Monday and on Wall
Street Friday also buoyed sentiment, traders said.
	   Tokyo's benchmark Nikkei Stock Average jumped 570.54 points, or
4.43 percent, to 13,450.51 at the end of the morning session. The
Dow Jones Industrial Average gained 2.17 percent Friday.
	   George Chan, an analyst with Celestial Asia Securities Holdings
Ltd., said many institutions have been caught out by the sudden
change in sentiment locally and are short-covering their positions,
pushing the market higher. 	   
</TEXT>
