<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Norway-Plane Crash </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Charter airplane crashes in Norway; eight killed
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   OSLO, Norway (AP) - A nine-passenger charter airplane crashed
short of a runway in western Norway Monday, killing all eight of
those believed to be aboard, police said.
	   The plane, a Cessna 402, was on its way from Aalborg, Denmark to
Stord, Norway when it crashed and caught fire at about 12:30 a.m.
(2230 GMT), some 200 meters (yards) short of the runway. The cause
of the crash was not known, even though it was seen from the
airport tower.
	   ``Everything seemed normal, and we had visual contact with the
plane,'' said Jan Morten Myklebust, head of the Stord local
airport. ``It was dark and raining, but there as a high cloud
ceiling and little wind. The plane just suddenly went down.''
	   According to Berit Johansen Sangholt, of the Hordaland district
police, seven passengers and a pilot were known to be aboard. The
Norwegian state radio network NRK said eight bodies had been
recovered from the wreckage, but that it was not clear whether one
more person could have been aboard.
	   The plane had been chartered to fly Danish workers to the Aker
Stord shipyard, about 500 kilometers (300 miles) west of Oslo,
after a weekend off. The identities and nationalities of the
victims were not immediately released.
	   (dm)
</TEXT>
