w2786 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NewZealand-Antarctic-     10-12 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-New Zealand-Antarctic-Drilling </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Stronger ice platform allows early start to Antarctic seabed
</HEADLINE>
drilling &QL; 
 &UR; By RAY LILLEY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) _ Solid sea ice more than 6-feet (2
meters) thick off the Antarctic coast is allowing an early restart
to a seabed drilling project at the ice continent's Cape Roberts,
where scientists are studying past climatic change.
	   ``The ice is thicker this year, Antarctica is letting us have
another go,'' chief scientist for the project Prof. Peter Barrett
told The Associated Press Monday.
	   This year's program could see the team drill a 2,300-ft (700
meter) hole into the Antarctic seabed.
	   ``We would like to get back 65 million years to the end of the
Cretaceous period, the end of the age of the dinosaurs,'' Barrett
said.
	   Last year the team extracted 500 feet (150 meters) of core
material from the first hole, before a severe Antarctic storm broke
a huge chunk from the ice-sheet and forced an urgent evacuation of
the 50-ton drill rig back to solid ice 15 miles (24 kilometers)
closer to the shoreline.
	   A thin ice sheet prevented any drilling in 1996.
	   The drilling project off Cape Roberts is 85 miles (140
kilometers) northwest of New Zealand's Scott Base and the U.S.
McMurdo Station on McMurdo Sound.
	   The six-nation project is drilling the Antarctic coastal seabed
to study past climatic change.
	   Scientists believe the rock cores from 1,500 feet (500 meters)
below the sea bed could unlock the history of the Antarctic's
climate and offer clues to global warming.
	   They also believe that studying earlier Antarctic warm spells
may help them predict what global warming may do to the world's ice
and sea levels.
	   The New Zealand dollars 10.2 million (U.S. dlrs 5 million)
drilling program is being jointly conducted by the United States,
Australia, Germany, Italy, New Zealand, and Britain.
	   Barrett said the team expected to reach back at least 40 million
years in the second hole, with the drill team currently cementing
the casing to the seafloor, 560-ft (172 meters) below the ice,
ready to start drilling later this week.
	   Last year's hole yielded material going back 22 million years,
including 32 different shellfish fossils and 15 previously unknown
species of algae.
	   The discovery of the shells indicates the Ross Sea off
Antarctica was several degrees warmer some 1.2 to 1.8 million years
ago, said Marco Taviani of the Institute of Marine Geology in
Bologna, Italy.
	   Fifty scientists from 28 institutions around the world are
analyzing and describing the seabed core as it is recovered by the
drilling team.
	   Barrett, professor of geology at Victoria University of
Wellington, said the weather at Cape Roberts was reasonable, but
50-knot winds at McMurdo had prevented any flights to the ice from
Christchurch for nearly a week. Only the drilling and logistics
teams had reached the Antarctic so far. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
