<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Stocks,0343 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pakistan stocks plunge as government scraps contract with Hub
</HEADLINE>
Power &QL; 
 &UR; By AMIR ZIA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Pakistan's stock market plunged 67
points in early morning trading Monday as the Karachi Stock
Exchange reacted violently to the cancellation of a contract with
the country's largest private power company, dealers said.
	   The government also initiated criminal investigations against
senior officials of the Hub Power company.
	   The premier Karachi Stock Exchange 100-share index slumped 7.12
percent or 67 points, to 874 points in the first 30 minutes of
trade.
	   ``The Karachi index could hit an all time low owing to this
news,'' said Shakil Anwar, a dealer at Prudential Securities.
	   Hub Power shares fell 4.95 rupees to 9.10.
	   ``We should now forget about new fresh foreign investment in the
market for a long time to come. The individual investors and
institutions all have taken a severe beating,'' Anwar said.
	   Hub Power _ the second largest company listed on the exchange _
is considered a sentiment leader.
	   Meanwhile, the Karachi Stock Exchange board of directors was
holding an emergency meeting Monday to try to gauge the impact of
the government's decision to cancel Hub's contract. The government
also has warned that it is looking at rates being charged by other
power companies with an eye to cancellation or renegotiation.
	   ``The market was already under a bearish spell ... this news has
come as another blow,'' said Sajjad Mankani, a dealer at the BMA
Capital Management.
	   The cancellation of the contract follows months of wrangling
between the government and Hub in which Sharif accused the largely
British-owned company of charging inflated tariffs for electricity.
	   The contract was signed by former prime minister Benazir
Bhutto's government.
	   The government lodged two criminal cases of fraud and theft
against senior company officials. Several key officials from Ms.
Bhutto's former government also have been charged, he said. 	   
</TEXT>
