w2792 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-China-Trade     10-12 0255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Trade </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China's trade surplus rises 15 percent in first nine months of year
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ China's trade surplus for the first three
quarters of 1998 swelled 15 percent from a year earlier to dlrs
35.3 billion, as import growth slowed due to Asia's economic
troubles, state-run television reported Monday.
	   The General Administration of Customs said China's exports rose
3.9 percent on the year to dlrs 134.13 billion in the nine-month
period. Imports inched up just 0.4 percent to dlrs 98.82 billion,
according to the report.
	   China's January-September trade surplus was about dlrs 3.92
billion more than the surplus reported for the first eight months
of the year. The report blamed a deepening of the Asian financial
crisis for sluggish trade.
	   Facing slack demand from its Asian neighbors, China has been
hard-pressed to boost exports. This year's growth in exports is
well off the 21 percent pace the country recorded in 1997.
	   The region's widespread banking and corporate problems have also
meant fewer companies are willing to expand operations in China, so
they're spending less money to import equipment.
	   Some foreign officials have also complained that China is
erecting protectionist barriers to keep out some imports and
protect its own struggling companies from foreign competition.
	   The government has recently applied new anti-dumping laws more
vigorously and has established a cartel pricing system for both
autos and steel to prop up falling prices in these sectors. 	   
</TEXT>
