<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asian Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Asian markets rally on growing optimism that worst is over
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PRISCILLA CHEUNG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Asian stock markets opened the week sharply
higher Monday as the stronger yen and and Japan's action to address
its ailing banks generate hopes that the worst in Asia's protracted
financial chaos is finally over.
	   Asian bourses were also boosted by Wall Street's 2.17 percent
gain Friday, stabilizing regional currencies, and hopes of a fresh
round of global interest rate cuts.
	   The benchmark Nikkei Stock Average rose 675.04 points, or 5.24
percent, to close at 13,555.01. On Friday, the index had tumbled
146.09 points, or 1.12 percent, closing at 12,879.97 _ its lowest
finish since December 1985.
	   Hong Kong's Hang Seng index _ after gaining 12 percent in the
past three sessions _ rallied another 7.8 percent in the morning
session to 9,166.94 points, the highest intraday level since May
27.
	   Property shares led the Hang Seng's advance as local investors
expect a local interest rate cut as early as next week.
	   Singapore shares rallied on Wall Street's strong performance
Friday and continued expectations of further interest rate cuts.
	   The Straits Times Index surged about 6.3 percent, or 61.18
points, to 1037.83 in mid-afternoon trading. The last time the
index was around these levels was about two months ago.
	   In Japan, share prices rallied as the upper house of Parliament
voted into law Monday a plan to use public funds to clean up the
country's massive bad debt problem and deal with failed banks,
traders said.
	   The package, which was passed by the more powerful lower house
on Oct. 2, marks a major step in Japan's determination to bail the
nation out of its deepest recession since the end of World War II.
	   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar bought 115.90 yen in
early afternoon trading, down 1.30 yen from late Friday in Tokyo
and also below its late Friday level in New York of 116.95 yen.
	   Last week, the dollar dropped nearly 14 percent, falling as low
as 111.45 on Thursday.
	   Other Asian markets were buoyed by the Nikkei's jump and hints
that the United States and Europe are ready to coordinate efforts
to help Asia, said Richard Verin, director of Asia equity trading
at Credit Suisse First Boston in Hong Kong.
	   Some investors believe ``Asia may have past the worst, with the
yen having traded very strongly. That would take a lot of pressure
off the currencies, and they would take interest rates down,'' he
said.
	   In other markets, the key index was up 2.1 percent in South
Korea; 2.8 percent in the Philippines; 2.9 percent in Thailand; 1.3
percent in Malaysia; and 1.9 percent in Indonesia. 	   
</TEXT>
