<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Stocks finish sharply higher on passage of banking reform bills,
</HEADLINE>
dollar down
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with closing Nikkei, mid-afternoon dollar and bond

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japanese stocks finished sharply higher Monday,
lifted by the passage in Parliament of bills designed to address
problems at the nation's ailing banks. The U.S. dollar fell against
the yen.
	   The benchmark Nikkei Stock Average rose 675.04 points, or 5.24
percent, closing at 13,555.01. On Friday, the index had tumbled
146.09 points, or 1.12 percent, finishing at 12,879.97 _ its lowest
finish since December 1985.
	   The dollar bought 115.76 yen by mid-afternoon, down 1.44 yen
from late Friday in Tokyo and also below its late Friday level in
New York of 116.95 yen.
	   Share prices rallied in the afternoon after Japan's upper house
of Parliament voted into law a plan to use public funds to clean up
the country's massive bad debt problem and deal with failed banks,
traders said.
	   The package, which was passed by the more powerful lower house
on Oct. 2, marks a major step in Japan's determination to bail the
nation out of its deepest recession in decades.
	   The market opened higher on expectations that the government
would soon expand a pool of public funds to assist ailing Japanese
banks, traders said.
	   Also supporting the market was Friday's rally in blue chips on
Wall Street, where the Dow Jones industrial average rose 167.61, or
2.17 percent, to 7,899.52 points, a gain of 114.83 for the week and
just shy of 7,908.25 where it began the year.
	   Japanese media reported over the weekend that the ruling and
opposition parties have agreed to expand to 67 trillion yen (dlrs
577 billion) the pool of public funds to boost the capitalization
of weak banks.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 40.84 points, or 4.16 percent, to 1,023.34. On
Friday, the TOPIX fell 19.00 points, or 1.93 percent.
	   In currency dealings, traders said the dollar moved lower on
selling from Japanese institutional investors and possibly by hedge
funds in a thin local market.
	   Anxiety over the economic health of hedge funds _ known for
betting large sums on global currency movements _ and their impact
on U.S. markets are among factors contributing to the uncertainty
over the dollar's direction.
	   The dollar's weakness also derived from the prospect of lower
German interest rates, which nudged the German mark down against
the yen, leading to the Japanese currency's relative strength
against the dollar, traders said.
	   Last week, the dollar plunged nearly 14 percent, falling as low
as 111.45 on Thursday.
	   That selling was fueled largely by hedge funds moving to dump
dollars in uncertain markets amid hopes for greater efforts by
Japan to mend its weak economy and the gloomier outlook for the
U.S. economy.
	   Haruhiko Kuroda, the head of the Japanese Finance Ministry's
international bureau, said Monday that volatility like that which
took place last week was undesirable.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese
government bond rose to 0.895 percent from Friday's finish of 0.790
percent, driving its price down to 108.06 yen from 109.08.
 &UR; (km-dj)
</TEXT>
