<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 10/12/1998 02:49:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2810 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-US     10-12 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cambodian government unruffled by U.S. condemnation of Hun Sen
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ The Cambodian government said Monday
it was unconcerned by a U.S. congressional resolution calling for
an investigation into violations of international humanitarian law
allegedly committed by strongman Hun Sen.
	   The resolution, passed last week in the House of
Representatives, is non-binding and not supported by the U.S. State
Department, a Cambodian government spokesman said.
	   It is, therefore, not seen as a threat to Cambodia's leader, he
added.
	   ``We expected this resolution. It won't affect the relationship
between the American government and the Cambodian government at
all,'' spokesman Khieu Kanharith said.
	   The resolution calls on the United States to collect information
against Hun Sen and supply it to ``an appropriate international
judicial tribunal for use as evidence to support a possible
indictment and trial of Hun Sen for violations of international
humanitarian law after 1978.''
	   Events mentioned in the resolution include Hun Sen's coup d'etat
against his co-Prime Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh last year,
and his violent crackdown in September against antigovernment
demonstrations.
	   The resolution was written by Rep. Dana Rohrabacher (R-Calif.),
a staunch critic of Hun Sen who represents a district with
America's largest ethnic Cambodian population.
	   The U.S. Embassy in Phnom Penh released a statement last week
saying the State Department supported investigations into political
killings and other serious human rights violations in Cambodia, but
not the House resolution because it called for the establishment of
a tribunal focusing on a single individual.
	   ``This resolution, like the numerous other resolutions passed by
the House and Senate, does not have the force of law and is not
binding,'' the embassy stated.
	   Khieu Kanharith said that the only effect the resolution may
have is to embolden opposition party leaders, such as former
Finance Minister Sam Rainsy, to increase their verbal attacks
against the government.
	   Sam Rainsy, who lobbied U.S. lawmakers to support the
resolution, told a local newspaper Sunday that he was ``very
satisfied'' by its passing.
	   ``I think that it will send a message to Hun Sen to be very
careful not to use violence against his opponents,'' Sam Rainsy
told The Cambodia Daily by phone from Paris.
	   An earlier draft of the resolution included charges that Hun Sen
was involved in the genocide of more than 1 million Cambodians
during the communist Khmer Rouge's brutal 1975-79 reign.
	   However, historians say there is no evidence that Hun Sen, a
young Khmer Rouge field commander at the time, was responsible for
mass killings. 	   
</TEXT>
