<SLUG> BC-EU-Finance </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World economic woes, budget wrangle dominate EU finance talks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: will be UPDATED &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos Covering &QL; 
 &UR; By PAUL AMES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LUXEMBOURG _ The turmoil on world markets, a battle over the
European Union's budget and the economic impact of Italy's
government crisis dominate Monday's meeting of EU finance
ministers.
	   The meeting comes as slower growth rates and fears of more gloom
spreading from Asia, Russia and South America take some of the
shine off preparations for the launch of the euro as the common
currency of 11 EU nations on Jan. 1.
	   So far, the EU has avoided the worst of the global crisis.
Supporters say that's partly down to confidence in the euro as a
strong currency and the strict budget policies nations must follow
to join the single currency.
	   However, ministers face mounting pressure for action to halt any
further decline in growth and help prevent future outbreaks of
global turbulence.
	   ``We've got to contribute to maintaining the conditions for
growth and stability round the world,'' Britain's Chancellor of the
Exchequer Gordon Brown told BBC television Sunday. ``My European
colleagues ... must share responsibility for creating these
conditions.''
	   With that in mind, ministers were expected to discuss plans for
strengthening international financial institutions and growing
calls for interest-rate cuts. They also expected to look at the
impact for Europe of the dollar recent tumble.
	   The one-day EU meeting should be the last for German Finance
Minister Theo Waigel. Defeat in last month's elections means the
Bavarian conservative is stepping down after almost 10 years at the
helm of the EU's biggest economy.
	   As a parting shot, Waigel is likely to knock home Germany's
tough line over plans to overhaul the EU's dlrs 100 billion budget
from 2000 so the Union can pay for it's planned expansion into
eastern Europe.
	   Germany, along with Austria, Sweden and the Netherlands, says it
pays too much into EU coffers and gets too little back in return.
They insist any reform correct the imbalance.
	   Since the incoming center-left government of chancellor-elect
Gerhard Schroeder is expected to continue to defend Germany's
stance, the budget wrangling is expected to drag on for months.
	   Italy's Carlo Azeglio Ciampi may also be making his last
appearance at a gathering of EU finance ministers, following the
fall of the center-left government in Rome Friday.
	   Other ministers will be looking for assurances that whoever
leads the next government _ perhaps Ciampi himself as caretaker
prime minister _ will continue Italy's efforts to cut debt and
budget deficit.
 &UR; (pa)
</TEXT>
