r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-ForeignMini     10-12 0446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Foreign Minister </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Foreign Minister reelected to parliament after close contest
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ALAN THORNHILL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ Foreign Minister Alexander Downer on
Monday won one of the tightest contests of Australia's election,
after being targeted by the right-wing populist One Nation party
for attacking its leader Pauline Hanson's criticism of Asians.
	   Nine days after the polls closed, candidate for the centrist
Australian Democrats party John Schumann conceded Downer was going
to win the electorate of Mayo with just a handful of votes
remaining to be counted and a very tight margin.
	   Downer went into the Oct. 3 election with what on paper was one
of the safest parliamentary seats held by the ruling conservative
coalition of Prime Minister John Howard.
	   But as counting began it became clear that the result was going
to be a cliffhanger, after One Nation sought to take its revenge on
Downer through Australia's convoluted system of preference-vote
distribution.
	   Downer has been one of Hanson's most unrelenting and fiercest
critics, reassuring Asian leaders during trips through the region
that her views are not representative of the government or most
Australians.
	   Hanson, who claims Australia is in danger of being ``swamped by
Asians,'' lost her Parliamentary seat at the election. Only one
party member was elected, despite One Nation gaining about 8
percent of the national vote.
	   One Nation was always unlikely to be able to mount a serious
threat to Downer in Mayo in its own right.
	   Lying in the hills outside Adelaide, the district incorporates
many ethnic communities, including the wine-growing town of Handorf
where many citizens have their own experiences of being the targets
of prejudice _ it was settled by German migrants, many of whom were
interred in detention camps during both World Wars.
	   But folk singer Schumann, as a member of the respectable
centrist Democrats, received ``preference'' votes from One Nation
supporters.
	   Under the system, the votes of minor candidates who are
eliminated early can be passed on to one of the remaining
contenders.
	   In Mayo, One Nation urged its supporters to direct their
preference votes against Downer and towards Schumann.
	   Conceding defeat, Schumann Monday said: ``It is clear ... that,
on present trends, Mr. Downer will fall across the line ahead of
me.''
	   Downer Monday said he had no regrets about his criticism of
Hanson.
	   ``I wear it as a badge of honor that One Nation put the
Democrats ahead of me (in order of preference),'' Downer said.
	   ``They wanted to get rid of me and they failed.'' 	   
</TEXT>
