<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-PLDT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLDT chairman confirms that company faces hostile takeover bid
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Philippine Long Distance Telephone Co. chairman
Roberto Romulo said Monday a hostile takeover is being mounted
against the company, but he declined to say whether the bidder was
an investment group or a foreign telecommunications company.
	   ``As a statement of fact there is a hostile takeover attempt on
going in Manila,'' said Romulo, who is attending an economic
conference in Singapore.
	   Romulo said he hoped Manila's Securities and Exchange Commission
would decide ``sooner rather than later'' on a company plan to
deter a hostile takeover.
	   PLDT, the Philippines' largest telecommunications company, has
seen its share price swing wildly since it announced Sept. 3 that
it had adopted a shareholder rights plan to protect against any
hostile takeover.
	   The plan needs SEC approval. The commission has not said how
long it expects to take before delivering its ruling.
	   The plan gives existing shareholders greater access to PLDT
stock in the event of a hostile takeover, making it more expensive
for an unwanted bidder to take a controlling stake in the company.
Shareholders of a record date yet to be set would be given the
right to acquire preferred shares in the event of an unwanted buyer
seeking to acquire more than 10 percent of the company's voting
stock.
	   Romulo said he is concerned about the impact of PLDT's share
volatility on the overall Philippine stock market.
	   ``It doesn't make the stock exchange look any better,'' he said,
noting that trading in PLDT invariably accounts for a large portion
of the daily volume of the 30-share Philippine Stock Exchange
Index.
	   Newspapers have cited various parties who are reportedly eyeing
a substantial stake in PLDT. Among them are Hong Kong's First
Pacific Co., Spain's Telefonica SA, and American International
Group.
	   Romulo reiterated that it would be ``inappropriate and quite
frankly counter productive to speculate on which group or groups
are involved ... but we know there is a hostile takeover.''
</TEXT>
