<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Bank Bills, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japanese upper house approves bank failure measures
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: PMs; RECASTS; UPDATES with stocks boosted by passage of bills,
details &QL; 
 &UR; By JOSEPH COLEMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Taking a major step toward tackling Japan's bad
debt crisis, the upper house of Parliament on Monday voted into law
a plan to use taxpayer money to clean up the country's deeply
troubled banks.
	   The package, which was passed by the more powerful lower house
on Oct. 2, also boosts Japan's efforts to overcome its deepest
recession since the end of World War II.
	   The markets took the vote as a healthy sign the country is
acting to address its financial problems. The benchmark Nikkei
Stock Average surged 675.04 points, or 5.24 percent, closing the
day's trading at 13,555.01.
	   The so-called financial stabilization plan creates a special
committee to oversee the cleanup of the nearly dlrs 1 trillion in
bad debts left over from the burst of the speculative ``bubble
economy'' in the early 1990s.
	   Also set up would be an organization similar to the U.S.
Resolution Trust Corp., created during the 1980s U.S. savings and
loan crisis to buy the bad debt from banks.
	   The Japanese economy could use the help. New loans are hard to
get and business has been suffering, especially small and
medium-size companies. Unemployment is at a record high,
bankruptcies are soaring and consumer spending is falling.
	   Growth shows no sign of coming back soon. The Economic Planning
Agency announced last week that the economy would shrink by 1.8
percent this year, and the head of the agency said on Sunday that
it could shrink next year as well.
	   The legislation passed Monday provides a framework for the
bailout, but does not specify the amount of money to be used.
	   The ruling Liberal Democratic Party originally proposed using
about 10 trillion yen (dlrs 86 billion), but reportedly agreed with
opposition parties over the weekend to increase that to 50 trillion
yen (dlrs 435 billion).
	   The new committee has the authority to pursue three courses of
action when dealing with a failed bank: to nationalize the bank
temporarily through the government's purchase of its shares; to
order the liquidation of the institution; or to transfer the bank's
operations to a public bridge bank.
	   It was unclear, however, what standards would be used to decide
which banks would fall under each method.
	   With Japan under pressure to turn around its economy and help
Asian neighbors, the bills also are a major victory for Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi and end one phase of a fierce dispute between
his ruling party and the opposition.
	   But the complicated implementation of the plan was expected to
be the center of another protracted political struggle.
	   ``It is one thing to pass a package of measures ... and it is
quite another to make sure they are workable,'' LDP lower house
member Nobuteru Ishihara was quoted as saying in the Asahi
newspaper Monday.
	   The first test case of the new legislation will be the troubled
Long-Term Credit Bank, which has been rumored to be on the verge of
collapse since summer. LTCB, one of Japan's biggest lenders, is
struggling under the weight of failed real estate loans.
	   In June, LTCB announced it was in talks to merge with Sumitomo
Trust _ a move that was widely regarded as a government-directed
bailout. But under the new legislation, the bank will be
nationalized temporarily and its bad loans will be sold, Kyodo News
agency reported.
	   The bills also abolish a 13 trillion yen (dlrs 113 billion) fund
that previously provided public money to be pumped into the banking
system to recapitalize banks.
	   Attention will now focus on the parliamentary debate regarding a
bill that would set up a replacement for the abolished fund,
allowing the government to pump cash into the banking system as a
means of easing the nation's credit crunch.
	   The ruling and opposition political camps have moved closer
toward an agreement on this issue in recent days.
 &UR; (jc-apdj)
</TEXT>
