<HEADLINE>
Search team finds downed helicopter in Russian Far East
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS to UPDATE with helicopter found. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A search team on Russia's Sakhalin Island found a
helicopter Monday that had caught fire and gone down the day
before, the ITAR-Tass news agency said.
	   The Mi-2 helicopter was spotted from the air on Sakhalin,
located off Russia's Pacific coast, after a search team of more
than 130 soldiers, border guards, police and forest rangers began
hunting for it Monday morning.
	   The helicopter had been inspecting forest fires Sunday in a
northern part of the island when it caught fire and went down,
ITAR-Tass said.
	   When the search team arrived they found a note from the two crew
members saying they had headed to the nearest settlement.
	   The search for the helicopter, which belonged to the Vostok
airline, took longer than expected because of smoke from forest
fires still burning out of control in the region, ITAR-Tass said.
