</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Yugoslavia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government urges Australians to leave Yugoslavia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ Australia would support NATO
airstrikes if negotiations failed to persuade Yugoslavia to accept
international demands on Kosovo, Foreign Minister Alexander Downer
said Monday.
	   Downer upgraded warnings to the about 2,000 Australians in the
region, urging them to immediately leave the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia.
	   ``Australians should get out of Yugoslavia as soon as
possible,'' Downer told reporters. ``The situation has obviously
reached a point of crisis in Kosovo.''
	   Downer urged President Slobodan Milosevic to withdraw his troops
from the Kosovo region.
	   ``The situation there is a humanitarian disaster,'' he said,
adding that 250,000 people had been displaced from their homes.
	   ``You have winter coming and it is very important that President
Milosevic listens to the international community,'' Downer said.
	   ``I hope very much that it won't come to the need for a NATO
strike, but that clearly is a possibility. ... We will support NATO
action if it comes to that.''
</TEXT>
