<SLUG> BC-Australia-Gas Shortage </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
High level inquiry announced into gas facility explosion
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) _ The government of Victoria state on
Monday ordered a high-level investigation into the gas refinery
explosion last month which killed two people and cut supply to
Australia's second most populous state for almost two weeks.
	   Announcing a royal commission into the crisis, Premier Jeff
Kennett said gas producer Esso-BHP had failed the state's more than
3 million residents, who deserved the highest level inquiry
possible.
	   The explosion on Sept. 25 killed two workers and cut gas
supplies to most of the state for almost two weeks, costing
industry millions of dollars and leaving householders without
gas-powered cooking facilities, hot water or heating.
	   Gas for factories, businesses and hot-water heaters was restored
last week, but full supply to all domestic users was not expected
to be reconnected until late Monday, distributor VENCorp said.
	   Kennett said the royal commission would investigate both the
explosion at Esso's Longford facility and an earlier incident there
in June, when an ice plug in the pipeline choked gas supplies.
	   ``The people of Victoria are owed nothing less than the most
serious investigation,'' Kennett said.
	   Former High Court judge Sir Daryl Dawson would head the
commission, which is expected to hand down its report in February.
	   A royal commission is a government-appointed fact finding
inquiry which has many of the same powers of the Supreme Court,
including being able to compel people to give evidence and produce
documents.
	   Meanwhile, Kennett said the government was seeking guarantees
from Esso-BHP that the state's gas supply would not be interrupted
next winter, beginning in July.
	   The company has said damage to the Longford facility may mean
gas will have to be rationed next winter.
	   Kennett said he would look to resource companies elsewhere if
Esso BHP could not guarantee security of supply. 	   
</TEXT>
