<SLUG> BC-Koreas-Tourism, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hyundai chief likely to meet North Korean leader Kim Jong Il
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds; UPDATES with Hyundai's plan to send construction workers and
equipment in grafs 8-10

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Chung Ju-yung, founder and honorary
chairman of the Hyundai business group, plans to visit North Korea
later this month and meet leader Kim Jong Il, an aide said Monday.
	   Kim Yun-kyu, a senior Hyundai executive, made the statement
after a weekend visit to North Korea, where he discussed Hyundai's
plans for sightseeing tours of a scenic northern mountain.
	   ``There is a high probability that honorary chairman Chung will
visit North Korea within this month and have a meeting with leader
Kim Jong Il,'' Kim told reporters.
	   The aide said all important pending issues concerning the tours
were settled during his visit to North Korea. He declined to
disclose what the pending problems were.
	   The aide said Hyundai can expect to start the tours later this
month. The tours have been delayed since September because of
financial, safety and other problems.
	   The Hyundai chief, Chung, visited his native North Korea in June
with a gift of 500 cattle and agreed to set up the tours as a joint
venture with the communist nation.
	   Hyundai, South Korea's largest conglomerate, hopes to send up to
2,000 tourists a week on two luxury cruise ships to Diamond
Mountain on the North's east coast.
	   Hyundai said it plans to send 88 workers and construction
equipment by ship and barge Tuesday to build berthing facilities at
Changjun, a North Korean port near the mountain.
	   Also to sent aboard the barges will be 65 tourist buses,
officials said.
	   Eight Hyundai executives will fly to North Korea by way of
Beijing Tuesday to discuss other business ventures, including
assembly of car audio sets and hiring of North Korean workers for
Hyundai's overseas construction projects, they said.
	   The tourism project would mark the first major joint venture
between the two hostile Korean states and give Pyongyang a new
source of badly needed foreign currency.
	   The Korean peninsula was divided into the communist North and
the capitalist South in 1945. They fought a three-year war in the
early 1950s. Their border is sealed with 2 million troops deployed
on both sides.
</TEXT>
