<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Finance Minister: No long-term strategy yet for Russian economy
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with former deputy prime minister's comments on food
aid, IMF visit delayed. &QL; 
 &UR; By LESLIE SHEPHERD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia's finance minister has acknowledged there
is no comprehensive, long-term strategy for rescuing the country's
economy and no plans to draft one this year.
	   ``I think that it would be rather difficult to draw up such an
integrated, comprehensive program now, since the situation,
firstly, changes very quickly, and secondly, it is too
sophisticated to be covered by any one single document,'' Mikhail
Zadornov said.
	   Zadornov spoke Sunday on the Russian television program
``Zerkalo.'' (Mirror).
	   The government has promised to make public its short-term plans
for dealing with the economic crisis by Oct. 20.
	   Zadornov said the government would not draw up any long-term
plans ``for at least the next three months.'' Instead, iin said that an International
Monetary Fund delegation that had been expected to arrive in Moscow
on Monday has been postponed until later this month because of the
Russian government's failure to submit all the information sought
by the IMF.
	   ``The IMF decided not to hurry because data for Oct. 1 will be
available only after the 20th of this month,'' Vyugin said,
according to the Interfax news agency.
	   Russia is urging the IMF to release the next installment on a
dlrs 22.6 billion loan negotiated before the latest crisis struck
in mid-August. Russia badly needs the money to help pay its debts,
but the IMF says it must first come up with and implement measures
to end the crisis.
	   Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov maintains the government's plans
hinge on whether it gets the foreign aid. Without that aid, Russia
is widely expected to start printing more money, which will stoke
inflation.
	   Russia has also asked the European Union for food and medicine
to help restock store shelves emptied by the latest economic
crisis, that struck in mid-August.
	   Russian officials are also reportedly holding informal talks
with the U.S. Department of Agriculture for as much as 3 million
metric tons (3.3 million short tons) of donated grains. Russia is
expecting one of the lowest harvest in 40 years because of
droughts.
	   Former deputy prime minister Boris Nemtsov said Monday the
Russian government is also seeking humanitarian aid from the United
States. He said U.S. administration officials told him of the
request during a recent trip to the United States.
	   Nemtsov had no further details, but said the situation was
extremely embarrassing for Russia.
	   ``We must tackle our problems on our own rather than beg,'' he
said, according to the Interfax news agency.
	   (ls/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
