<HEADLINE>
Australian facing child sex charges pleads innocent
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Note contents of some grafs. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ An Australian former millionaire
pleaded innocent Monday to 38 charges of child sexual assault at
the District Court in Sydney.
	   Phillip Harold Bell, 62, appearing in a dark suit before Judge
Thomas Davidson and a jury of eight men and four women, replied,
``Not guilty,'' as each count of the indictment was read to the
court.
	   Prosecutors say Bell committed indecent assaults and acts of
homosexual intercourse on five boys aged between 13 and 15 between
1983 and 1988.
	   The alleged offenses took place at a rural property on coast of
New South Wales state, at two other locations and on boats moored
in Sydney Harbor.
	   Prosecutor Mark Tedeschi said Bell is accused of taking part in
masturbation, oral sex and anal sex with the boys.
	   He said up to 64 witnesses would be called to give evidence
during the trial, expected to last between six and eight weeks.
	   After nearly a year's international search, Bell was arrested
last December in Jeffrey's Bay, where he was running a surfing
school on South Africa's southern coast.
	   Bell was extradited to Australia after spending nearly five
months in a jail cell in Humansdorp, about 75 kilometers (46 miles)
west of Port Elizabeth.
</TEXT>
