<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Philippines </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine president urges deeper ties with Singapore
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Asia-Economic Conference

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Philippine President Joseph Estrada, on his
first overseas trip, met Monday with Singapore's leaders and called
for more cooperation between the two once-estranged countries.
	   ``My decision to visit Singapore first was right ... as our
relations are very important,'' Estrada said in a speech to the
Philippine and Singaporean businessmen.
	   Estrada said his ``pro-poor'' policies cannot be implemented
without the help of the foreign business community.
	   ``The government recognizes the crucial role of foreign direct
investment for rural projects,'' he said.
	   Estrada, who won the presidency by appealing to the poor and the
disenchanted, reiterated his promise to transform the country
economically without neglecting the poor.
	   ``We are pro-market, pro-investment, pro-competition,'' he said,
``but we will not forget safety nets for the marginalized sectors
of the society.''
	   Earlier Monday, Estrada met with Singapore Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong and President Ong Teng Cheong.
	   ``We share a strong commitment to strengthening the cooperation
between our countries,'' Estrada said after the meeting.
	   Estrada, on his first trip abroad since assuming the presidency
in June, is to deliver the keynote address on Tuesday at the East
Asia Economic Summit sponsored by the World Economic Forum.
	   Singapore is the Philippines' third-largest trading partner,
with total trade reaching dlrs 3.8 billion last year. Singapore
also is the fourth-largest importer of Philippine products and an
important investor.
	   Estrada said the two countries enjoy a balanced trade
relationship, adding that Philippine businessmen are now investing
in Singapore in larger numbers to take advantage of Singapore's
``dynamic competitiveness.''
	   He said he was confident the Philippines will be the first in
Asia to recover from the regional economic crisis.
	   The Philippines' projected economic growth for this year is 1
percent, higher than most of its Southeast Asian neighbors.
	   Estrada on Sunday met with some of about 100,000 Filipino women
who work as domestic helpers in Singapore and praised them as
saviors of the Philippine economy. Overseas Filipino workers are
expected to send home more than dlrs 6 billion this year through
official channels, and much more through other means.
	   Relations between the two countries were hurt in 1995, when
Singapore convicted Flor Contemplacion, a Filipino maid, of killing
another Filipino maid and a young Singaporean boy she cared for.
	   Singapore insists Contemplacion confessed, but many Filipinos
believe she was a victim of injustice. Mass protests forced the
Philippine government to withdraw its ambassador, and Singapore
responded by doing the same.
	   Relations were normalized in 1996 with the exchange of new
ambassadors. 	   
</TEXT>
