<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Malaysia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore shrugs off Malaysian currency controls and airspace
</HEADLINE>
restrictions
 &UR; By JONATHAN DRAKE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Singapore on Monday shrugged off recent moves
by Malaysia seen as detrimental to the small city-state, including
the imposition of market controls and restrictions of military
airspace.
	   Malaysia's decision to ban overseas trading of its currency and
stocks in early September had been viewed as particularly damaging
to Singapore's vulnerable economy, which relies on regional
financial activity and counts Malaysia as its second-largest
trading partner.
	   ``Given the close interdependence of the Singapore and Malaysian
economies, it is inevitable that Singapore will be affected by
Malaysia's capital and exchange control measures,'' Minister of
Trade and Industry Lee Yock Suan told Parliament on Monday.
	   But he said trading of ringgit, the Malaysian currency, in
Singapore's foreign exchange market had declined over the past
months and was ``only a small proportion of total turnover.''
	   Minister for National Development Lim Hng Kiang said the
government was confident about Singapore's strengths as the
region's financial hub.
	   He pointed to growing business for many products on the
Singapore International Monetary Exchange despite the volatility in
regional markets.
	   Lim added that the ``closure of trading of Malaysian shares on
(the local stock market) is a loss to Singapore's financial sector,
but the loss is not significant relative to the size of the
financial sector'' here.
	   As with ringgit transactions, he noted that trading of Malaysian
shares had declined to only 3 to 8 percent of the total turnover in
the stock market in the months before Malaysia imposed
restrictions.
	   Lee added that bilateral trade, although likely to be affected
by the Malaysian restrictions, would not affect all Singapore-based
companies.
	   In addition to frayed economic ties with Malaysia, a series of
acrimonious disagreements over a wide range of issues has soured
relations between the two countries.
	   In mid-September, Malaysia abruptly revoked a long standing
agreement allowing Singapore military planes to transit through
their airspace without prior approval.
	   Minister of State for Defense Matthais Yao told Parliament that
Malaysia's decision will not affect training and operations of
Singapore's air force, which has started alternative routes, but
acknowledged it will hurt search and rescue efforts. 	   
</TEXT>
