w2867 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-PartyTalks 1stLd-Writethru   10-12 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Party Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Opposition wants summit of party leaders held outside Cambodia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS king's reaction, background in grafs 3, 17-18; edits 19th
graf to conform. &QL; 
 &UR; By CHRIS FONTAINE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Cambodia's opposition parties
demanded Monday that talks between their leaders and strongman Hun
Sen aimed at forming a coalition government take place outside the
country.
	   A spokesman for Hun Sen's party called the demand an opposition
trick, but did not rule out meeting abroad if King Norodom Sihanouk
endorsed the idea.
	   The king said Monday in a letter to junior opposition party
leader Sam Rainsy that he would have to consult with Hun Sen and
ruling party president Chea Sim on a foreign venue.
	   Hun Sen's party won 64 of the 122 seats in the National
Assembly, or parliament, in a July 26 election, not the two-thirds
majority necessary to form a government on its own.
	   The opposition insists the victory was achieved through fraud
and intimidation. Talks between Hun Sen's party and the opposition
over forming a government have been deadlocked.
	   The opposition says it wants to negotiate outside the country
because it is being threatened by Hun Sen's party.
	   In a joint statement, opposition party leaders Prince Norodom
Ranariddh and Sam Rainsy suggested Tokyo and several other foreign
capitals as neutral ground where talks could be held.
	   ``We cannot join a meeting in Cambodia as we will not negotiate
under threat, including the threat of further so-called `attacks'
on Hun Sen, which could bring consequences of the most serious
magnitude,'' the opposition leaders said.
	   Sam Rainsy and several others have been under investigation
since a grenade attack on Hun Sen's residence sparked a crackdown
on demonstrations against the results of the July 26 national
election.
	   Hun Sen was not in Phnom Penh at the time and no one was hurt in
the attack. The opposition claimed it was staged as an excuse to
break up the protests.
	   The Phnom Penh municipal court filed charges against Sam Rainsy
and summoned him to appear for questioning.
	   Both Ranariddh and Sam Rainsy have stayed outside Cambodia since
parliament was ceremonially opened on Sept. 24.
	   A spokesman for Hun Sen's Cambodian People's Party said Monday
that the statement was a ploy to portray the ruling party as
hostile toward the opposition.
	   ``This is one of the tricks of Sam Rainsy to show he is a victim
and that there is a threat inside the country,'' ruling party
spokesman Khieu Kanharith said.
	   A second alleged attempt on Hun Sen's life came in the
northwestern town of Siem Reap. A rocket-propelled grenade exploded
near Hun Sen's car, killing a 12-year-old bystander.
	   King Norodom Sihanouk's mediating efforts in a September summit
among Hun Sen, Ranariddh and Sam Rainsy led to the convening of the
legislature. The ruling party called on the 75-year-old monarch
last week to host more talks.
	   Sam Rainsy on Sunday sent his request to the king to chair the
summit and asked the monarch to hold the meeting outside Cambodia.
	   Sihanouk responded that he was still waiting for Ranariddh's
request for a summit, but if both opposition parties suggest a
foreign venue, he would have to consult with the ruling party
before making a decision.
	   The king had said in a weekend statement that he could not order
opposition leaders to attend the summit but would chair the meeting
if asked.
	   Khieu Kanharith said the opposition's demand for talks to be
held in another country would only be agreed to by Hun Sen's side
if the king also proposed it.
</TEXT>
