<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Norway-Plane Crash,0169 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Charter airplane crashes in Norway; eight killed
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   OSLO, Norway (AP) _ A nine-passenger charter airplane crashed
short of a runway in western Norway Monday, killing all eight of
those believed on aboard, police said.
	   The plane, a Cessna 402, was en route from Aalborg, Denmark, to
Stord, Norway, when it crashed 200 meters (yards) short of the
runway after midnight. The cause of the crash was not known.
	   ``Everything seemed normal, and we had visual contact with the
plane,'' said Jan Morten Myklebust, head of the Stord airport. ``It
was dark and raining, but there as a high cloud ceiling and little
wind. The plane just suddenly went down.''
	   The Norwegian state radio network NRK said eight bodies had been
recovered from the wreckage.
	   The plane had been chartered to fly Danish workers to the Aker
Stord shipyard 300 miles (480 kilometers) west of Oslo after a
weekend off. The identities and nationalities of the victims were
not immediately released. 	   
</TEXT>
