<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 10/12/1998 04:32:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2881 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Yeltsin 2ndLd-Writethru   10-12 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Yeltsin, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin cuts short meetings for second day
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with Yeltsin canceling more events on
Monday, but appearing at news conference, Russia and Uzbekistan
signing agreement to help each other against aggression, other
details, color, Yeltsin leaving for Kazakstan. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos planned &QL; 
 &UR; By TIMOFEI ZHUKOV
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TASHKENT, Uzbekistan (AP) _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin cut
short his meetings in Uzbekistan on Monday, after canceling events
the previous day, but aides said he was recovering from a cold and
feeling better.
	   Yeltsin appeared stiff and stumbled Sunday on his arrival in
Tashkent, the capital of Uzbekistan, and had to be supported by
Uzbek President Islam Karimov.
	   He canceled his other public events, saying he wasn't feeling
well, but held one-on-one talks with Karimov as scheduled.
Yeltsin's chief spokesman, Dmitry Yakushkin, said the president was
suffering from a cold and had had a bad flight from Moscow.
	   Yakushkin and Yeltsin's doctor, Sergei Mironov, said he was
feeling better Monday, the Interfax news agency reported.
	   However, Yeltsin showed up one hour late for talks Monday
between Russian and Uzbek officials, catching only the last 20
minutes. He also cut short his scheduled 20-minute news conference
to just a few minutes.
	   He and Karimov made brief statements and walked away without
taking any questions. Yeltsin walked unaided, but was closely
flanked by bodyguards.
	   ``We had to slightly change the program because of the tight
schedule,'' Yakushkin told reporters, refusing to give any further
details.
	   Following the talks, Yeltsin and Karimov signed a package of
agreements to boost economic and other ties.
	   ``We have agreed to establish closer cooperation in the
economic, political and military fields,'' Yeltsin said in his
statement.
	   Yeltsin then flew to neighboring Kazakstan for a two-day visit.
	   The trip to Central Asia is Yeltsin's first outside of Russia
since May, when he traveled to Britain for a meeting of the Group
of Seven industrialized countries.
	   In both Central Asian countries, Yeltsin is discussing economic
issues as well as concerns about the fighting in Afghanistan.
Former Soviet republics in the region fear an influx of refugees
and weapons from Afghanistan, and possibly a spill over of fighting
that has wracked the country.
	   Yeltsin and Karimov made a joint statement on Monday expressing
``serious concern'' over the developments in Afghanistan and
calling on the ruling fundamentalist Islamic movement Taliban to
end hostilities.
	   The two presidents also signed a declaration promising to help
one another in the event of an outside attack. The document was
signed earlier by President Emomali Rakhmonov of Tajikistan _
another former Soviet republic that borders both Uzbekistan and
Afghanistan.
	   Yeltsin, whose health has often sidelined him during his seven
years in power, has spent most of the last two months out of the
limelight and out of the Kremlin, holding meetings in his country
home outside Moscow.
	   (str/vi/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
