<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vietnam-Migration </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Economic migrants on rise in Vietnam
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ Economic migration is on the rise in
Vietnam as people move in search of better paying jobs in the
cities, a government official said Monday.
	   Hoang Dong, director of the Ministry of Agriculture's Department
of Settlement and Economic Zones, said such migration is increasing
because government-sponsored economic zones, which accommodate
100,000 people each year, cannot meet the demand.
	   Dong said a survey funded by the U.N. Development Program over
the past two years showed that 100,000 people are moving each year
to Ho Chi Minh City and 55,000 to Hanoi.
	   The survey also showed that these people earn an average of
471,000 dong (dlrs 34) per month, much higher than 100,000 dong
(dlrs 7) they could earn on the farm. By moving, migrants can send
some money back to their families each month, it said.
	   The massive migrations to major cities have complicated social
issues and put more pressure on the country's already overloaded
infrastructure.
	   Migration is also blamed for deforestation in four central
highland provinces as new residents, particularly from the northern
mountainous provinces, continue slash-and-burn cultivation
practices.
</TEXT>
