<SLUG> BC-Algeria-Strike </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Deadlock as Air Algerie strike enters seventh day
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) _ There was no end in sight Monday to a
seven-day strike by Air Algerie after unions voted to withdraw a
guarantee of minimal flights.
	   Since Friday, at least 30 percent of flights have been running
as normal from Algiers, especially on services to Paris and the
southern French city of Marseille.
	   But the strikers' position hardened after company officials said
Sunday they would not accept changes to a restructuring plan.
	   Air Algerie officials say a restructuring is essential to
maintain the company's competitiveness. But staff fear there will
be inevitable job losses.
	   The strike has left thousands of people stranded, and many have
had to take ferries to Europe.
	   ``I risk losing my job. I had to be back today,'' said Mouloud
Benlazreg, a businessman based in Paris who was trying to find an
alternative route.
	   Commuters whose domestic flights have been canceled have had to
resort to trains and buses to make their journeys.
	   (parf-ip)
</TEXT>
