r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Bulgaria-MrsClinton     10-12 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bulgaria-Mrs Clinton </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. first lady encourages businesswomen in Bulgaria
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By VESELIN ZHELEV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) _ U.S. first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
praised Bulgarians on Monday for their reform efforts and
encouraged women who are trying to help create a new business
culture in this former communist country.
	   On the second day of her four-day trip to promote women's rights
in Eastern Europe, Mrs. Clinton met with businesswomen at a Sofia
bakery and discussed the challenges of running a business in the
new Bulgaria.
	   ``We're very impressed by the reform effort and the difficult
decisions that your government is making on behalf of the future,''
she told the women.
	   Mrs. Clinton also accepted an offer to allow her book ``It Takes
a Village'' to be translated and published into Bulgarian.
Businesswoman Iren Komitova suggested the proceeds go to the
American University in Bulgaria's southwestern city of Blagoevgrad.
	   After talking with students at the American College of Sofia,
the first lady was headed later Monday to Prague to meet with Czech
leaders and speak at a conference organized by President Vaclav
Havel and Nobel laureate Elie Wiesel.
	   On her first day in Bulgaria, far from the pressures of
Washington and talk of her husband's impeachment, Mrs. Clinton on
Sunday announced new American aid grants and posed for pictures
with former street children.
	   Although Sunday was the Clintons' 23rd wedding anniversary, the
couple marked the occasion apart, having celebrated on Friday with
a dinner on the eve of Mrs. Clinton's departure.
	   The first lady addressed the opening session of a conference
entitled ``Women in the 21st Century'' focusing on the role of
women in social issues confronting southeastern Europe, much of
which is still recovering from a half-century of Communist rule.
	   ``The American people, the American government and the president
of the United States will stand with you as you press ahead to meet
the challenges before you,'' she said.
	   ``Democratic progress depends on the progress of women,'' Mrs.
Clinton told delegates at the two-day conference. ``Economic
progress depends on progress of women. A vibrant civil society
depends upon the full contribution of women.''
	   She announced a dlrs 15 million grant to bolster civil society
in southeastern Europe, to be channeled through the U.S. Agency for
International Development, and said a new program would provide
dlrs 300,000 in training and internships for women business leaders
and entrepreneurs.
	   Later, at a meeting with activists at a Jewish center in
downtown Sofia, Mrs. Clinton praised Bulgarians for their tolerance
and their progress in establishing democratic principles since the
fall of Communism in 1989.
	   Bulgaria is one of the few former communist states to have
addressed issues involving its minorities, in particular, the
800,000 Turks and 300,000 Gypsies, or Roma, who live in the
country.
	   ``It is a great pleasure for me to be in a country well known
for its tolerance,'' Mrs. Clinton said. ``In comparison to many
other transition countries, Bulgaria sets quite an example.''
	   Before having dinner with President Petar Stoyanov and his wife,
she shook hands with some 50 local people and was cheered by
foreign tourists.
	   ``She is a nice strong lady because she stands by her husband
and defends him,'' said Ivan Ivanov, 28, one of the bystanders who
turned out for a glimpse of the first lady.
	   (vz/dc)
</TEXT>
