r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Singapore-BadDebt     10-12 0343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Bad Debt </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore banks' bad loans likely to grow as regional crisis
</HEADLINE>
continues

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Bad loans made by Singapore banks are likely to
increase as the regional crisis continues and the local economy
slows, a minister said Monday.
	   Minister for National Development Lim Hng Kiang told Parliament
that Singapore's six banks have set aside some capital as a
preparation.
	   He said non-performing loans amounted to 6.1 percent of total
loans at the end of August for Singapore banks.
	   About 2.7 percent of their total bad loans were made to
Malaysia, Indonesia, Thailand, South Korea and the Philippines _
nations at the center of the regional crisis.
	   But the level of bad debt ``does not threaten the financial
health of any of the local banks,'' adding that the sector remained
``resilient,'' Lim said.
	   The six banks are Development Bank of Singapore, Oversea-Chinese
Banking Corp., United Overseas Bank, Overseas Union Bank, Keppel
Bank and Tat Lee Bank.
	   Lim said that the city-state's de facto central bank, the
Monetary Authority of Singapore, will soon begin releasing data on
non-performing loans on a quarterly basis.
	   The move is in line with recent measures to make the financial
sector here more transparent.
	   On Singapore's fiscal policy, Lim noted that the government is
pursuing more expansionary policies, but warned that Singapore will
not be able to reverse the downturn by merely stimulating domestic
spending.
	   He emphasized that the government's main response to the
slowdown was to reduce business costs ``decisively.'' Reduced
tariffs and taxes, lower rents and utilities, and wages freezes
have already been adopted.
	   The government has strongly hinted that further measures,
including a cut in the amount employers and workers contribute to a
mandatory pension fund, will be forthcoming.
	   ``We need to be realistic and recognize that ultimately the
external environment must improve before an enduring economic
recovery in Singapore can take place,'' said Lim.
</TEXT>
