<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-China Visit </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chinese Vice Governor to visit in breakthrough exchange
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ Zhang Jiakun, vice governor of China's
Fujian province, will visit business leaders in Taiwan starting
Tuesday, the highest-ranking local-level Chinese official ever to
visit the island.
	   Zhang will lead a small delegation on a four-day visit at the
invitation of Taiwan's Chinese National Federation of Industries,
the federation said Monday.
	   He will visit leading Taiwanese investors in China including the
Formosa Plastics group, which is participating in a multi-billion
U.S. dlrs power plant project in Fujian, the United Evening News
said.
	   The vice governor's visit comes at a moment when Taipei is
hoping for a breakthrough in exchanges between the sides, divided
politically since 1949 when the Nationalists fled here ahead of the
communist takeover of the China.
	   Taiwan's top negotiator with China travels to the mainland on
Wednesday for contacts that Taipei hopes will help end a three-year
break in negotiations.
	   Fearing over-dependency, Taiwan's government has sought to rein
in Taiwanese investment in China, where the island's businesses
have sunk about U.S. dlrs 30 billion.
	   The government bans Taiwanese from investing in infrastructure
projects including railroads, highways, power plants and banks in
China, and mandates fines of up to dlrs 540,000 for unauthorized
investments.
</TEXT>
