<SLUG> BC-Russia-Regional Elections </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nizhny Novgorod, Lipetsk get new mayors, runoffs expected in
</HEADLINE>
Kaliningrad &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Residents of Russia's third-largest city elected
the chairman of a local religious organization to be their mayor,
after the winner of the last election was convicted of stealing
government funds, news agencies reported Monday.
	   The incumbent mayor was re-elected Sunday in the industrial town
of Lipetsk, south of Moscow, while mayoral votes in two cities in
the western enclave of Kaliningrad will go to runoffs.
	   Voters in Nizhny Novgorod gave 44 percent of the vote to Yuri
Lebedev, the 47-year-old chairman of a local religious charity and
the former vice governor of the region, the ITAR-Tass news agency
said.
	   The runoff vote was required after the first round last month
produced no winner.
	   Lebedev defeated former mayor Dmitry Bednyakov, who won 41
percent of the vote. More than 12 percent of voters cast ballots
against both candidates in the city, about 400 kilometers (250
miles) east of Moscow.
	   Nizhny Novgorod's previous mayor, entrepreneur Andrei
Klimentyev, was elected in March but election officials invalidated
his victory after President Boris Yeltsin expressed concern about
the results.
	   Klimentyev was convicted in May of forging documents, embezzling
part of a government loan to a shipbuilding plant and appropriating
a large share of the plant's stock. He was sentenced to six years
in prison.
	   Meanwhile, in the industrial city of Lipetsk, 300 kilometers
(180 miles) south of Moscow, preliminary results showed incumbent
Alexander Korobeinikov winning the mayoral election with 40.9
percent of the vote, ITAR-Tass said.
	   Korobeinikov's nearest rival garnered 23.9 percent.
	   Mayoral elections in two cities in Kaliningrad, 1,000 kilometers
(620 miles) west of Moscow, will both go to runoffs after no
candidate won 50 percent of the vote plus one ballot _ the level
required in the region.
	   In the city of Kaliningrad, acting mayor Yuri Savenko led with
42 percent. Anatoly Khlopetsky, director of the Transrailwest
company, took 14 percent.
	   And in Sovetsk, the director of a film-making school, Vyacheslan
Svetlov, captured 22.3 percent of the vote. His main opponent,
Nikolai Nikolayev, the director of the Sandorgaz company, took 18
percent.
	   Runoffs in both places are likely to be scheduled for Oct. 25,
ITAR-Tass said. Kaliningrad is separated from the rest of Russia by
Belarus and Lithuania.
	   (nw/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
