<SLUG> BC-France-Kosovo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
French minister: NATO strikes on Yugoslavia could be lengthy
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ France's Defense Minister, announcing a plan to
provide planes for possible NATO strikes against Yugoslavia, said
Monday a military attack could last ``several days.''
	   Alain Richard, speaking in an interview with television channel
France-2, said France would provide around 40 planes for possible
air strikes.
	   ``France has agreed to contribute to the air force which perhaps
will act,'' Richard said.
	   He added that most of the aircraft would be based on the French
aircraft carrier Foch, currently heading towards the region. Other
planes, he said, would be stationed at Italian air bases.
	   France, active in seeking a solution to the Kosovo crisis, is
not a member of NATO's military wing, but is consulted over action.
	   Kosovo was the subject of talks last Sunday between French
Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine and British counterpart Robin Cook.
	   U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke on Monday described the Kosovo
standoff as an ``emergency'' and demanded that Yugoslav leader
Slobodan Milosevic end his crackdown.
	   (parf-ip)
