<SLUG> BC-Russia-Chechnya </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chechen leader again criticizes generals calling for his ouster
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The president of Russia's breakaway Chechnya
region criticized political opponents who claim he is not capable
of stopping violence in the area and should step down, a news
agency said Monday.
	   In a televised address Sunday night, President Aslan Maskhadov
said his opponents, led by former rebel leaders Salman Raduyev and
Shamil Basayev, ``are being manipulated by groups intent on
increasing tension in Chechnya and plunging the republic into
chaos,'' the Interfax news agency reported.
	   Raduyev and Basayev, two field generals who played prominent
roles in Chechnya's 1994-96 independence battle from Russia, have
said Maskhadov should be prosecuted for crimes against the people
and should step down from his post.
	   But a commission convened to investigate their charges ruled
that Maskhadov has not violated Chechnya's constitution, ITAR-Tass
reported Monday.
	   Maskhadov also cited a recent endorsement of his foreign and
domestic policies by the Congress of the Chechen People, a
government-sponsored meeting, Interfax said.
	   ``The Chechen people did not support the generals, and they are
doomed to shame and rejection by the entire nation,'' Maskhadov
said in his TV address.
	   Maskhadov won a landslide election victory in January 1997, but
during his time in office, Chechnya has seen a steep rise in
kidnappings and other crimes.
	   No country has recognized Chechnya's claims of independence, and
Russia still considers it a semi-autonomous Russian republic.
	   (nw/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
