<HEADLINE>
APEC: Women hurt by Asian crisis
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS typo in lead; no pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; By JIM GOMEZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Deprived of protection from
unemployment because of decades-old social biases, women have been
especially hurt by Asia's financial storm, officials said Monday.
	   Delegates to a conference on women at a meeting of Pacific Rim
leaders have urged steps to demolish such discrimination and to
provide women with better opportunities to overcome the crisis.
	   ``Where poverty reigns, women are poorer than most men. Gender,
to be sure, is a function of nature. Poverty, however, is not,''
Philippine congresswoman Bellaflor Castillo told the delegates at
the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation Forum.
	   ``Sex-based discrimination has thrived because those who are in
a position to make a difference have chosen to ignore it,'' she
said.
	   The conference of senior officials from APEC member countries
aims to find ways of giving women equal opportunities in workplaces
and trade. The recommendations will be offered to APEC ministers,
who will hold a two-day meeting in Manila starting Thursday.
	   The ministers would then bring the proposals to APEC heads of
state, who will hold a summit in the Malaysian capital of Kuala
Lumpur next month.
	   Philippine Foreign Undersecretary Rosario Manalo said women were
the first to be laid off when companies shut down because women
tend to be assigned to dispensable work.
	   A conference paper also found that women workers have been
primarily assigned to certain low-paying and dangerous jobs, such
as the garment industry and home-based industries.
	   ``Because of gender stereotypes, women are expected to engage in
paid work on a temporary basis, such as during the time between
finishing school and marriage and pregnancy,'' it said.
	   Although women have been found to be owners or managers of at
least half the number of small- and medium-scale firms among APEC
countries, they still find it more difficult to obtain credit or
loans than their male counterparts, Manalo said.
	   This has made it difficult for women entrepreneurs to adjust to
economic difficulties, she said.
	   Manalo called on APEC countries to jointly study the effect of
Asia's financial crisis on women to know how they could be
effectively helped.
	   She also urged countries to start compiling data on women's
contribution to production and trade to find out their impact on
APEC economies.
	   APEC, which accounts for half of global trade, consists of
Australia, Brunei, Canada, Chile, China, Hong Kong, Indonesia,
Japan, Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Papua New Guinea,
Philippines, Singapore, South Korea, Taiwan, Thailand and the
United States.
