<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Kia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Four carmakers submit bids to buy bankrupt Kia Motors
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Ford Motor Co. rejoined the bidding
for Kia Motors Corp. on Monday, submitting an offer for the
bankrupt firm in a third attempt by creditors to auction it off.
	   The U.S. auto giant joined three South Korean carmakers in the
bidding after sitting out the second failed auction because of
Kia's huge debts.
	   Also submitting bids were Samsung Motors, Inc., Daewoo Motor Co.
and Hyundai Motor Co.
	   All four participated in the first failed auction, but only the
South Korean firms submitted offers in the second round of bidding.
	   Both the first and second auctions were canceled after bidders
demanded bigger writeoffs of Kia's dlrs 8.4 billion debt than
creditor banks were willing to make.
	   The creditors bowed to those demands in the third auction,
saying they would award Kia to the bidder seeking the smallest
reduction of its debt if the difference between the first and
second-place bids is greater than dlrs 500 million.
	   If the difference is less than that, the creditors will take
other factors into consideration, including suggested terms of debt
repayments.
	   The move to sell Kia is part of the government's effort to
restructure its battered economy under a dlrs 58 billion bailout
from the International Monetary Fund.
	   Kia's collapse last year helped erode investor confidence in
South Korea's industries, leading to a flight of capital. 	   
</TEXT>
