<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Mad Cow </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
France announces 12th case of mad cow disease this year
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ French authorities on Monday announced the
discovery of another cow infected with mad cow disease _ the 12th
case in France this year.
	   The Agriculture Ministry said the infected animal was a milk cow
born in 1994 at a farm in the Orne region, west of Paris.
Conforming to French regulation, the farm's 137 other cows were
slaughtered as well.
	   Since 1990, 43 cases of mad cow disease have been reported in
France, the ministry said.
	   The disease, bovine spongiform encephalopathy, was first
detected in 1985. The ailment eats holes in the brain, causing
cattle to stagger and drool. There is no cure.
	   Scientists believe the mad cow disease may be linked to an
equally fatal human brain ailment, Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease.
	   (parf-ad-ip)
</TEXT>
