<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Share prices surge on interest rate cut hopes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with closing figures

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Shares prices in Hong Kong surged for the
second consecutive session Monday on expectations of cuts in both
local and U.S. interest rates.
	   The blue-chip Hang Seng Index rose 483.48 points, or 5.6
percent, to close at 8,990.27, its highest close since July 2. On
Friday, the index had soared 567.28 points.
	   Turnover also rose to 12.807 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S.
dlrs 1.64 billion), up from Friday's 9.126 billion Hong Kong
dollars (U.S. dlrs 1.17 billion).
	   Dealers say investors are piling into the market on expectation
that the territory's banks will cut interest rates as early as this
week. Such hopes have set off a 12-percent rally in the index for
the past three sessions.
	   Hopes of yet another rate cut in the United States at the next
meeting of the Federal Open Market Committee in mid-November are
also bringing institutional investors back, traders add.
	   ``There's more fear of being left out than buying high,'' said
Kent Rossiter, head of institutional sales at Nikko Securities Co.
Asia.
	   Monday's gains on the Tokyo stock market and on Wall Street
Friday also buoyed sentiments, traders said.
	   Among properties, Cheung Kong rose 4.60 Hong Kong dollars to
45.90, and Sun Hung Kai Properties rose 2.20 dollars to 37.50. In
the banking sector, HSBC Holdings rose 9.00 dollars to 155.50, and
Hang Seng Bank rose 2.25 dollars to 59.00.
	   Elsewhere, Hutchison Whampoa rose 4.00 dollars 49.80, and Swire
Pacific ``A'' rose 45 cents to 27.80. 	   
</TEXT>
