<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 5th Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. bombers prepare for airstrikes amid marathon Kosovo talks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Recasts Ld to raise talks resumed; details of observer
evacuation; UPDATES with German embassy reported shut down; France
earmarking 40 war planes for any strike, attack would last several
days.
 &UR; AP Photos BEL101
 &UR; By KATARINA KRATOVAC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ With NATO warplanes shifted closer
for possible NATO airstrikes, U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke
described the Kosovo standoff as an ``emergency'' on Monday and
demanded the Yugoslav leader end his crackdown.
	   After a rest of just a few hours, Holbrooke resumed talks with
President Slobodan Milosevic on defusing the Kosovo crisis and
avoiding threatened NATO airstrikes on Yugoslav military targets.
	   Holbrooke described his earlier overnight meeting with Milosevic
as ``intense, indeed, and at times very heated.'' He said the
standoff between NATO and the Yugoslav president ``can only be
called an emergency.''
	   NATO officials also met in Brussels, Belgium, first on an
informal level in the morning. An official conference was scheduled
for later in the day, which was expected to result in an
``activation order'' for NATO airstrikes against Yugoslavia unless
diplomacy produces a breakthrough.
	   In Paris, French Defense Minister Alain Richard said his country
would provide around 40 aircraft for possible airstrikes, which
could last ``several days.''
	   Foreign presence was being reduced in anticipation of NATO
action.
	   The last two vehicles of international team of U.S., Russian and
other diplomats observing events in Kosovo over the past months
left for neighboring Macedonia before midday, carrying Americans
and Europeans. Sources at the American embassy said all but 12
people would be evacuated from Belgrade to Budapest.
	   The German embassy was closed down Monday morning, said local
employees, speaking on condition of anonymity, while British
embassy staff were waiting for the outcome of the latest
Holbrooke-Milosevic talks.
 &UR; The Americans, 6th graf pvs
