<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia: NATO airstrikes could lead to international chaos
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Foreign Ministry saying recall of diplomats
open-ended, Russia continuing to lobby against airstrikes. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ NATO airstrikes against Serbia could encourage
countries elsewhere to use force to solve disputes, Russia's
foreign minister said in pressing his country's opposition to
military action by the Western alliance.
	   ``That is very dangerous because we can enter a phase of
international chaos when states solve differences on borders with
their methods, the use of force,'' Igor Ivanov said.
	   He spoke Sunday on the Russian television program ``Zerkalo''
(Mirror).
	   Russia opposes possible NATO airstrikes a Serbia, a traditional
ally with which it shares a Slavic heritage and Orthodox religion.
	   It has recalled its representative to NATO and its ambassador to
Belgium, where NATO has its headquarters, for consultations.
Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir Chizov said their return will
depend on developments, the Interfax news agency reported Monday.
	   Chizov, director of the Foreign Ministry's Third European
Department, said Russia is staying in touch with Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic and members of the Contact Group on Yugoslavia.
	   The fact that U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke is still holding
talks in Belgrade suggests that an agreement is still possible,
Chizov said.
	   ``If Holbrooke reaches a political settlement acceptable to
Belgrade, we will most probably support it,'' he said.
	   Ivanov said Russia was still considering how it would respond if
NATO went ahead with the airstrikes to force Serbia to end its
violent crackdown on ethnic Albanians in Kosovo province.
	   Ivanov said Sunday in Uzbekistan, where he is accompanying
President Boris Yeltsin on an official visit, that a Russian
military response was ``out of the question.''
	   ``We continue to believe and not only to believe but also to do
everything to prevent the worst,'' he said on TV.
	   (ls/nw) 	   
</TEXT>
