<SLUG> BC-Iran-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iran accuses United States of trying to increase Gulf tension
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ The United States is trying to increase
tension between Iran and its Arab neighbors in the Gulf, a Foreign
Ministry spokesman was quoted as saying Monday.
	   The spokesman, Mahmoud Mohammadi, was reacting to U.S. Defense
Secretary William Cohen's comments that it was imperative for
American allies in the Gulf to acquire missile defense systems to
counter weapons in the hands of Iran and Iraq.
	   ``Washington, following its backward policies, is trying to
foment tension in the region now that suitable grounds have been
established for cooperation among the Islamic nations of the
region,'' Iran News quoted Mohammadi as saying.
	   An Iraqi newspaper also criticized Cohen's comments.
	   ``We find the American defense minister in a new tour in the
region coming out with silly, unexplained and strange threats,''
said Al-Thawra, the newspaper of Iraq's ruling party.
	   Cohen told reporters Saturday in Bahrain that the United States
would share its missile technology with Gulf allies because of the
proliferation of missile technology in the Gulf.
	   The United States sees Iraq and Iran, which recently tested a
long-range missile, as major threats to the Gulf region.
	   Cohen said Iraq, which has been under U.N. sanctions since 1990,
continues efforts to acquire missile technology that would give
weapons a longer range than they are permitted to have.
	   Cohen was in Bahrain as part of a six-nation Gulf tour, which
includes the United Arab Emirates, Oman, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.
