purchase of art work.
	   _ITALY-POLITICS. Italian president begins consultations to form
new government.
 &UR; MAIN SPOT NEWS:
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ With NATO warplanes being moved closer
for possible airstrikes, U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke describes the
Kosovo standoff as an ``emergency'' on Monday and demands the
Yugoslav leader end his crackdown. YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO. Developing.
By Katarina Kratovac. AP Photos BEL101, BON103-104.
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ The NATO nations are awaiting word from the
talks in Belgrade on Monday before moving to the next phase of
carrying out their threat of military action against the Serbs _ an
``activation order'' that could produce air strikes within days.
NATO-KOSOVO. Expected by 1200 GMT. By Raf Casert. AP Photo BRU101.
	   ANTALYA, Turkey _ Yugoslavia's stubborn refusal to make even the
smallest of concessions on Kosovo is uniting even traditional
rivals Turkey and Greece at a summit of Balkan leaders in an effort
Monday to convince their neighbor to accept international demands
and avert NATO airstrikes. BALKAN SUMMIT. Lead expected by 1200
GMT. By Suzan Fraser.
	   ALSO MOVED:
	   _US-KOSOVO. Intimidation of Milosevic said to be first aim of
NATO attacks.
	   _KOSOVO-PRISTINA MOOD _ Fear and apprehension grip provincial
capital. AP Photo NY110.
	   _RUSSIA-KOSOVO; GERMANY-KOSOVO; FRANCE-KOSOVO.
	   STOCKHOLM, Sweden _ Robert F. Furchgott, Louis J. Ignarro and
Ferid Murad of the United States won the Nobel Medicine Prize today
for discoveries that shed light on the cardiovascular system.
NOBEL-MEDICINE. Developing. By Jim Heintz. AP Photos planned.
	   TASHKENT, Uzbekistan _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin cuts
short his meetings in Uzbekistan on Monday, after canceling events
the previous day, but aides say he is recovering from a cold and
feeling better. RUSSIA-YELTSIN. Has moved; developments will be
expedited. By Timofei Zhukov. AP Photos planned.
	   ALSO MOVED:
	   _RUSSIA-ECONOMY. Finance minister says there is no long-term
strategy yet for Russian economy.
	   TEHRAN, Iran _ An Iranian foundation has added dlrs 300,000 to
the reward for Salman Rushdie's death, just weeks after the Iranian
government tried to distance itself from the bounty. IRAN-RUSHDIE.
Developing.
	   BAKU, Azerbaijan _ With opposition groups boycotting the vote,
Azerbaijan's authoritarian leader looks certain to be re-elected
president by voters seeking stability and long-elusive prosperity
for their oil-rich Caspian Sea country. AZERBAIJAN-ELECTION. Has
moved; developments will be expedited. Final results expected
Thursday. By Misha Dzhindzhikashvili.
	   LUXEMBOURG _ The turmoil on world markets, a battle over the
European Union's budget and the economic impact of Italy's
political crisis dominate Monday's meeting of EU finance ministers.
EU-FINANCE. Has moved; developments will be expedited. By Paul
Ames. AP Photos planned.
	   TOKYO _ Taking a major step toward tackling Japan's bad debt
crisis, the upper house of Parliament on Monday votes into law a
plan to use taxpayer money to clean up the country's deeply
troubled banks. JAPAN-BANK BILLS. Has moved. By Joseph Coleman.
	   HONG KONG _ Asian stock markets open the week sharply higher
Monday as the stronger yen and and Japan's action to address its
ailing banks generate hopes that the worst in Asia's protracted
financial chaos is finally over. ASIAN MARKETS. Has moved. By
Priscilla Cheung. AP Photos TOK101-102.
	   SINGAPORE _ Leading economists and businessmen disagree Monday
on solutions for Asia's financial turmoil, but warn that a
mishandling of the situation could lead to the world's worst
economic crisis in more than 50 years. ASIA-ECONOMIC CONFERENCE.
Has moved; developments will be expedited. By David Thurber.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ The discontent with Prime Minister
Mahathir's 17-year-rule is swelling the ranks of an Islamic group
that is leading the anti-government campaign and triggering
defections from the ruling party, a party official said Monday.
MALAYSIA-POLITICS. Has moved. By Jocelyn Gecker.
	   WASHINGTON _ Budget negotiations are entering their second week,
with the White House and Republican leaders narrowing major
differences and lawmakers stuck in Washington for the duration
nervously eyeing the Nov. 3 elections. US-CONGRESS ROUNDUP. Lead
expected by 1600 GMT. By Jim Abrams. AP Photo WX102.
	   ALSO MOVED:
	   _US-CONGRESS-IMPEACHMENT. President Bill Clinton and prosecutor
Kenneth Starr both could end up testifying to the House impeachment
inquiry. AP Photos WX101, WX103.
 &UR; BC-Italy-Politics
 &UR; Italian president begins consultations to form new government
	   ROME _ Three days after the collapse of Premier Romano Prodi's
center-left government, Italy's president begins calling in
political leaders Monday to try to reach a consensus on a new
government. ITALY-POLITICS. Has moved.
	   JERUSALEM _ A senior Palestinian negotiator says the success of
a peace summit in Washington depends on a clear-cut ``yes'' from
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to an American
initiative. ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS. Has moved; developments will be
expedited.
	   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands _ Prime Minister Wim Kok, his finance
minister and the chief of the Dutch Central Bank are rebuked for
buying a dlrs 40 million abstract painting with taxpayers' money
and donating it to a museum. NETHERLANDS-MONDRIAN FLAP. Has moved.
By William J. Kole. AP Photo AMS101.
	   LOOKING AHEAD: On Monday, a summit meeting of heads of state of
