<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Koreas-Japan-Sex Slaves </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Activists from Japan, two Koreas agree on sex slave issue
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Activists from Japan and both North
and South Korea have banded together to jointly urge Japan to
compensate women forced into sexual slavery in World War II.
	   Twenty-one leaders of women's groups from the three countries
met in Beijing over the weekend and issued a joint statement
condemning Japan for an ``unbearable debasement'' of women.
	   The statement was made available in Seoul Monday by Yang
Mi-kang, secretary general of the Korean Council for the Women
Drafted for Military Sexual Slavery by Japan.
	   ``The meeting created a basis for the three parties to further
cooperate and jointly deal with the issue,'' said Yang, who
attended the conference.
	   ``It is an unbearable debasement of women's human rights... that
the Japanese government neither recognizes its legal responsibility
nor apologizes to the women,'' their joint statement said.
	   The statement, among other things, urged Japan to stop trying to
compensate the former sex slaves through private donations and
address the issue by mentioning it in Japan's history textbooks.
	   Yang said it was the first time that activist groups from the
three countries had met to discuss the issue. Japanese and South
Korean women's groups had discussed the issue several times, but
never with their North Korean counterparts.
	   The three parties, Yang said, agreed to send a petition to the
U.N. Human Rights Commission later this month, asking it to
intervene to resolve the issue.
	   Historians estimate that as many as 200,000 women from Korea and
other Asian nations were taken to Japanese army brothels during
World War II.
	   Most of those sex slaves were from Korea, which was a colony of
Japan from 1910 to 1945. Some 150 South Koreans are registered as
former sex slaves.
	   Japan set up the private Asia Women's Fund in 1995 to dole out
financial assistance to the women, which it euphemistically refers
to as comfort women.
	   But the fund's offer of dlrs 17,000 to each surviving victim was
rejected by most South Koreans, who demand that any compensation
come directly from the Japanese government. 	   
</TEXT>
