<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bulgaria-Mrs Clinton, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. first lady encourages businesswomen in Bulgaria, travels on to
</HEADLINE>
Prague &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with visit to Sofia college, quote, departure for
Prague; TRIMS &QL; 
 &UR; By VESELIN ZHELEV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) _ U.S. first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
praised Bulgarians on Monday for their reform efforts and
encouraged women who are trying to help create a new business
culture in this former communist country.
	   Before leaving for the Czech Republic on the second day of a
four-day trip to promote women's rights in Eastern Europe, Mrs.
Clinton met with businesswomen at a Sofia bakery and discussed the
challenges of running a business in the new Bulgaria.
	   ``We're very impressed by the reform effort and the difficult
decisions that your government is making on behalf of the future,''
she told the women.
	   Mrs. Clinton also accepted an offer to allow her book ``It Takes
a Village'' to be translated and published into Bulgarian.
Businesswoman Iren Komitova suggested the proceeds go to the
American University in Bulgaria's southwestern city of Blagoevgrad.
	   After talking with students at the American College of Sofia,
the first lady flew later Monday to Prague to meet with Czech
leaders and speak at a conference organized by President Vaclav
Havel and Nobel laureate Elie Wiesel.
	   Mrs. Clinton met with some 500 students at the American College
of Sofia, where she also toured the school, talked to teachers and
alumni and looked at their computer laboratory.
	   ``I saw the future of Bulgaria in the eyes of the brilliant and
dynamic students I met at the American College of Sofia,'' she
said. ``That school is but one example of the ties of trade,
investment, culture and friendship between our two countries.''
	   The college, established in 1860 while Bulgaria was still under
Turkish rule, was closed down by the communists in 1948 shortly
after they came to power. College alumni were persecuted, but the
school's book collection was preserved at the local monastery and
the college was resurrected in 1992.
	   Mrs. Clinton presented the college with 100 volumes of the
Library of America, containing the best works of famous American
writers, historians, philosophers and statesmen.
	   The students presented her with a book entitled ``Heroines of
History'' that contains a chapter about her.
	   On her first day in Bulgaria, far from the pressures of
Washington and talk of her husband's impeachment, Mrs. Clinton on
Sunday announced new American aid grants and posed for pictures
with former street children.
	   ``It is a great pleasure for me to be in a country well known
for its tolerance,'' she told one audience. ``In comparison to many
other transition countries, Bulgaria sets quite an example.''
	   A popular figure abroad, she shook hands with some 50 local
people and was cheered by foreign tourists.
	   ``She is a nice strong lady because she stands by her husband
and defends him,'' said Ivan Ivanov, 28, one of the bystanders who
turned out for a glimpse of the first lady.
	   (vz/dc)
</TEXT>
