<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asian Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Asian markets rally on growing optimism that worst is over
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with closing figures for all markets
 &UR; By PRISCILLA CHEUNG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Most Asian stock markets closed sharply higher
Monday, boosted by the passage of legislation in the Japanese
parliament to help the country's ailing banks.
	   Asian bourses were also boosted by Wall Street's 2.17 percent
gain Friday, and hopes of a fresh round of global interest rate
cuts.
	   Tokyo's benchmark Nikkei Stock Average rose 675.04 points, or
5.24 percent, closing at 13,555.01. On Friday, the index had
tumbled 146.09 points, or 1.12 percent, finishing at 12,879.97 _
its lowest finish since December 1985.
	   Share prices surged in the afternoon after Japan's upper house
of Parliament passed a package of bills to create a framework to
deal with banks that have failed.
	   The package already passed the more powerful lower house on Oct.
2. The law marks a major step in cleaning up the bad debt problem
and in turning around the economy out of its deepest recession in
decades.
	   Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar bought 116.72 yen in late afternoon,
down 0.48 yen from late Friday in Tokyo and also below its late
Friday level in New York of 116.95 yen.
	   Hong Kong shares surged for the second consecutive session
Monday on expectations of cuts in both local and U.S. interest
rates.
	   The blue-chip Hang Seng Index rose 483.48 points, or 5.6
percent, to close at 8,990.27, its highest close since July 2. On
Friday, the index had soared 567.28 points.
	   Other Asian markets were also buoyed by the Nikkei's jump and
hints that the United States and Europe are ready to coordinate
efforts to help Asia, said Richard Verin, director of Asia equity
trading at Credit Suisse First Boston in Hong Kong.
	   Malaysian shares surged 4.6 percent on local institutional
buying. The Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange's benchmark Composite Index
rose 17.28 points to 389.50.
	   Elsewhere:
	   SINGAPORE: Shares closed sharply higher as Friday's rally on
Wall Street and expectations of more interest rate cuts propelled
the benchmark index to end above the 1,000 mark for the first time
in about two months. The benchmark Straits Times Index rose 4.1
percent, or 39.95 points, to 1,016.60.
	   SEOUL: Share prices also closed sharply higher, with the key
index surging 4.1 percent on expectations that the recent rise of
the Japanese yen will help local companies gain a price
competitiveness against their Japanese rivals. The Korea Composite
Stock Price Index rose 13.74 points to 352.17.
	   TAIPEI: Share prices closed lower on profit-taking. The market's
key Weighted Stock Price Index fell 23.72 points, or 0.3 percent,
to 6,920.45.
	   WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed higher in reaction
to Friday's gains on Wall Street. The NZSE-40 Capital Index rose
19.18 points, or 1.1 percent, to 1,723.65.
	   MANILA: Philippine shares closed higher for a fifth consecutive
session on the back of Wall Street's gains on Friday. The
Philippine Stock Exchange Index of 30 selected stocks rose 41.91
points, or 3.2 percent, to 1,343.27.
	   SYDNEY: The Australian stock market closed moderately higher.
The All Ordinaries Index rose 10.3 points, or 0.4 percent, to
2,501.6.
	   JAKARTA: Share prices closed higher. The Composite Index rose
2.577 points, or 0.8 percent, to 307.417.
	   BANGKOK: Thai shares closed lower on profit-taking. The Stock
Exchange of Thailand index fell 1.70 points, or 0.6 percent, to
290.80. 	   
</TEXT>
