<SLUG> BC-Czech-Forum 2000 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Havel, Kissinger reflect on Kosovo crisis
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) _ The Kosovo crisis bore heavily on
a gathering of more than 50 prominent thinkers and activists
meeting here Monday to discuss the process of globalization at the
end of the millennium.
	   Opening the prestigious event Monday, Czech President Vaclav
Havel asked for a minute of silence to honor the plight of Kosovo
refugees.
	   During his brief welcome speech he also commemorated Edith
Stein, an Auschwitz martyr and the first Jewish-born saint of the
modern era, canonized Sunday in the Vatican by Pope John Paul II.
	   Fears of another potential Balkan war and looming NATO
airstrikes in Kosovo were acknowledged by others as well.
	   ``I am uneasy about it,'' said former U.S. Secretary of State
Henry Kissinger.
	   ``I would like to know exactly what the objective is ... and
what happens after the use of military force,'' he said. ``These
answers have to be given before a military strike.''
	   The conference includes a wide range of political and religious
activists, such as former Polish Premier Hana Suchocka and the
chief rabbi of Israel, Meir Lau.
	   U.S. first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, arriving later Monday en
route from the Bulgarian capital of Sofia, is to address the
gathering Tuesday.
	   The conference, sponsored by Japan's Nippon Foundation, is the
second of its kind held in Prague. The first was held in 1997.
Three more will be held here until 2001.
	   Havel, a former playwright and dissident, is known for his
efforts to make Prague the center of intellectual activity in the
post-Communist world.
	   After opening the event Monday, he dashed off to Vienna to
attend a summit of six Central European presidents held in the
Austrian capital.
	   He is due to return to Prague later Monday to meet with Mrs.
Clinton and hold a ceremonial dinner at Prague Castle for Forum
2000 participants.
	   (oh/nr/scl) 	   
</TEXT>
