<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Algeria-Truce </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Muslim leaders around world voice support for Algerian truce
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ELAINE GANLEY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Thirty Muslim leaders from around the world have
appealed to Islamic insurgents in Algeria to join a truce called a
year ago, saying blind violence by fighters was helping to pervert
Islam.
	   ``We bless this noble, patriotic initiative,'' said a statement
obtained Monday.
	   A copy of the statement, dated Sunday, was obtained by The
Associated Press. The truce by the Islamic Salvation Army went into
effect on Oct. 1, 1997.
	   The statement called on Algerian authorities to use the truce to
``strengthen the bases for national global reconciliation.''
	   The statement was signed by Muslim leaders from Malaysia to
Morocco, and included diverse names on the list of 30 that included
activists like the head of Egypt's banned Muslim Brotherhood,
university professors and thinkers.
	   The signatories ``consider the truce ... a good work and a bold
patriotic position that has contributed in an appreciable manner to
diminishing the level of killings, destruction and attacks on
sacred laws,'' the statement said.
	   It added that the signatories agree that accusations of apostasy
by armed groups concerning fellow Muslims are an ``ignomy,''
leading to ``great evil.'' Blind killings, likewise, give ``the
enemies of Islam the occasion to deform (the religion) ....''
	   ``Islam always insists, even in cases of war ..., on preserving
the blood of non-combatants, particularly women, children and the
elderly,'' the statement said.
	   In Algeria, there was no immediate reaction from authorities or
from the Armed Islamic Group, the radical insurgency movement held
responsible for numerous massacres.
	   The Islamic Salvation Army, the military wing of the banned
Islamic Salvation Front, called the truce in part to ``unmask the
enemy hiding behind the abominable massacres.''
	   But the truce has been belittled by some as a unilateral
cease-fire by a poorly equipped force. It even divided the Islamic
Salvation Front, some of whose members consider the truce a virtual
surrender.
	   An estimated 75,000 people have been killed since violence
erupted nearly seven years ago, after the army canceled January
1992 legislative elections to thwart a likely victory by the
Islamic Salvation Front.
	   The party was banned in a massive crackdown by authorities and
the Islamic Salvation Army was born to win back ``stolen votes.''
After the Armed Islamic Group was formed in 1994, sharp ideological
and territorial rivalries developed between the two groups.
	   The text was interspersed with quotes from the Koran and the
Sunna, the traditions of Prophet Mohammed, founder of the Islamic
faith.
	   Among the signatories were: Mustapha Mashhour, leader of Egypt's
Muslim Brotherhood; Tunisian Rachid Ghannouchi, living in exile in
London; Ghulam A'dham Amir of the Jamaat Islami group in
Bangladesh; Qadi Hussein of the Jemaat Islami in Pakistan; Fadel
Nour, president of the Islamic Party of Malaysia; Dr. Azzam Tamimi,
head of the British-based Liberty organization.
	   (eg-ip)
</TEXT>
