<SLUG> BC-Australia-Britain-Foster </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Foster has limited victory in battle against extradition
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRISBANE, Australia (AP) _ Convicted international conman Peter
Foster succeeded Monday in temporarily challenging his extradition
to Britain but was ordered to remain in jail until proper
extradition steps were taken.
	   Federal Court Judge Jeffrey Spender found that Justice Minister
Amanda Vanstone did not have the power to sign the extradition
warrant authorizing Foster's deportation to England to face
fraud-related charges.
	   Spender said only Australia's attorney general had the authority
to sign such a warrant and that it had been wrongly delegated to
Vanstone.
	   But Spender also ordered Foster remain in prison until Attorney
General Daryl Williams signs the warrant.
	   Foster, 35, of the Gold Coast, in Queensland state, faces five
charges _ two of conspiracy to defraud and three of using a false
instrument _ in the United Kingdom and has been fighting
extradition since last year.
	   He has been in jail since he was recaptured in Melbourne after
going on the run last November.
	   Foster has been jailed in three countries on convictions of
various crimes. He was captured in Australia and jailed for
breaching bail conditions and trying to escape lawful custody.
</TEXT>
