<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Greek Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU gives cautious approval to Greek economic plans
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; with EU-Finance &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LUXEMBOURG (AP) _ European Union finance ministers Monday
approved Greek government plans to get the economy in shape for
joining the EU single currency bloc, but they warned extra efforts
may be need to meet the ambitious targets.
	   High levels of inflation, public debt and budget deficit
excluded Greece from the first group of 11 nations set to adopt the
euro as their common currency on Jan. 1. Greece hopes it can be
ready to join in 2001.
	   Under EU rules, the four nations staying outside the euro-zone
present mid-term economic programs intended to promote policy
convergence within the EU.
	   While Denmark, Britain and Sweden voluntarily opted out of the
euro, Greece is hoping it's ``convergence program'' will keep in on
track for early membership.
	   Under the plan, Greece aims to have debt and deficits down to
the levels required for participation in by the end of this year
and inflation in line by the end of 1999.
	   However, the EU said an expected slow down in growth because of
the shaky world economic situation could call for extra effort to
meet the targets.
	   The program shows the budget deficit falling to 2.4 percent of
gross domestic product this year, from 4 percent in 1997. The
deficit is seen at 2.1 percent in 1999.
	   Inflation is seen at an average of 4.5 percent in 1998, compared
to 5.5 percent in 1997. Inflation is expected to drop to 2.5
percent in 1999.
 &UR; (pa-dj)
</TEXT>
