r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-PAL     10-12 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-PAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAL indefinitely suspends resumption of international flights
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Philippine Airlines on Monday
indefinitely put on hold a plan to resume international flights,
initially set for this week, on request of potential investors.
	   Debt-laden PAL reopened Wednesday with domestic flights after a
13-day shutdown caused by disagreements with its largest labor
union over a management recovery plan.
	   The flag-carrier was scheduled to resume flights to Hong Kong,
Tokyo, Los Angeles and San Francisco on Thursday and gradually add
flights to seven other destinations in Asia and the Middle East.
	   A PAL statement said without elaborating that the resumption of
international flights was aborted on request of potential
investors, who have been studying the airline's records the past
week.
	   It said domestic flights would continue.
	   Jimmy Bautista, PAL's chief finance officer, said there were at
least three investors in talks with PAL officials, Hong Kong's
Cathay Pacific Airways, Northwest Airlines and Singapore Airlines.
	   Two of PAL's four 747-400 Boeing planes, used on international
flights, have been seized by authorities in Hong Kong and Los
Angeles recently on demand of the U.S. Export-Import Bank, which
financed them.
	   It was not immediately clear if the airline put on hold the
resumption of international flights due to fears by PAL officials
that its other leased planes could be garnished by authorities in
foreign airports as well.
	   A PAL plane brought President Joseph Estrada to Singapore on
Sunday, where he will address an international economic summit and
make a state visit. He has wanted the flight to signal the
resumption of PAL's international flights this week.
	   PAL, which has been unable to make payments on dlrs 2.1 billion
in debt, was devastated by a pilots' strike in June and by the
region's currency crisis, which reduced passenger numbers and
inflated costs.
	   PAL, Asia's oldest airline, shut down operations on Sept. 23
after a union representing ground personnel turned down a
management-proposed recovery plan that would suspend labor strikes
and collective bargaining negotiations for 10 years.
	   Union members turned down the proposal in an initial
government-supervised referendum but accepted it in a second
referendum after Estrada brokered an agreement between PAL majority
owner and Chairman Lucio Tan and the union.
	   Under the accord, workers agreed to the suspension of their
collective bargaining agreement for 10 years in exchange for 20
percent ownership of the airline.
</TEXT>
