r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Koreas-POW     10-12 0234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Koreas-POW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Seoul to launch campaign to account for MIAs from Korean War
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ South Korea will launch a new campaign
to account for hundreds, perhaps thousands, of its soldiers missing
from the Korean War, the Defense Ministry said Monday.
	   ``The efforts will be through direct South-North Korea channels
or the U.N. Human Rights Commission,'' the ministry said in a
statement.
	   The statement came after a South Korean soldier who escaped
after being held in North Korea for 45 years claimed he knew of
about 30 other prisoners of war still alive in the communist
country.
	   Staff Sgt. Chang Moon-hwan, 72, arrived in South Korea late last
month after fleeing into China from North Korea, where he had been
held captive and forced to work as a coal miner since 1953.
	   Chang, who was captured two weeks before the Korean War ended in
1953, reported seeing about 70 South Korean prisoners of war
working at the coal mines, of whom about 40 have died.
	   Chang was the third South Korean prisoner of war to escape North
Korea. Former POW Yang Soon-yong, who escaped to the South in
December, said at least 59 ailing South Korean prisoners of war
were still alive in a North Korean concentration camp.
	   Seoul says more than 40,000 South Korean prisoners were not
returned at the end of the Korean conflict, but the North says all
POWs went home in 1953.
</TEXT>
