<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0929 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ With NATO warplanes being moved
closer for possible airstrikes, U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke on
Monday described the Kosovo standoff as an ``emergency'' and
demanded the Yugoslav leader end his crackdown. After a rest of
just a few hours, Holbrooke resumed talks with President Slobodan
Milosevic on defusing the Kosovo crisis and avoiding threatened
NATO airstrikes on Yugoslav military targets. Holbrooke described
his earlier overnight meeting with Milosevic as ``intense, indeed,
and at times very heated.'' He said the standoff between NATO and
the Yugoslav president ``can only be called an emergency.'' NATO
officials also met in Brussels, Belgium, first on an informal level
in the morning. An official conference was scheduled for later
Monday, expected to result in an ``activation order'' for NATO
airstrikes against Yugoslavia unless diplomacy produces a
breakthrough. In Paris, French Defense Minister Alain Richard said
his country would provide around 40 aircraft for possible
airstrikes, which could last ``several days.'' (YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO)
	   ANTALYA, Turkey (AP) _ Balkan leaders in Antalya, a Turkish
seaside resort, tried Monday to persuade Yugoslavia to accept
international demands on Kosovo and avoid NATO airstrikes. Although
Yugoslav Premier Momir Bulatovic and Foreign Minister Zivadin
Jovanovic were said to be bearing ``new ideas,'' it seems unlikely
the heads of government attending Monday's two-day Balkan summit
will be able to persuade them to accept a key U.N. demand that
could avert a NATO decision to authorize military action. NATO
meets Monday to decide on the use of force, and Balkan leaders here
_ including alliance members Greece and Turkey _ want to attempt
their own 11th-hour effort to find a peaceful solution. Diplomats
say Yugoslavia has so far refused to even accept a mention of
Kosovo in a joint declaration to be issued at the end of the
meeting, forcing other countries to draft a separate resolution on
the crisis in the Albanian-dominated Serbian province. (BALKAN
SUMMIT)
	   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) _ Robert F. Furchgott, Louis J. Ignarro
and Ferid Murad of the United States won the Nobel Medicine Prize
on Monday for discoveries that shed light on the cardiovascular
system. They discovered how nitric oxide acts as a signal molecule
for the body's blood vessels, a breakthrough with applications
ranging from hardening of the arteries to impotence. Understanding
how nitric oxide transmits the signals has sparked research on a
wide range of new drugs, including those that can be used in the
treatment of heart problems, atherosclerosis, shock and impotence.
Because of their work, ``we know today that nitric oxide acts as a
signal molecule in the nervous system, as a weapon against
infections and as a regulator of blood pressure,'' said the
citation from the Karolinska lnstitute. The citation said ``it was
a sensation that the simple, common air pollutant (nitric oxide),
which is formed when nitrogen burns ... could exert important
functions in the organism.'' (NOBEL-MEDICINE)
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Discontent with Prime Minister
Mahathir's 17-year-rule is swelling the ranks of an Islamic group
that is leading the anti-government campaign and triggering
defections from the ruling party, a party official said Monday. In
the last month, the Parti Islamic SeMalaysia or PAS, a conservative
group, said it had enrolled 5,000 new members, and was running out
of application forms. Defense Minister Syed Hamid Albar said the
defections of at least 500 members of his ruling United Malays
National Organization was ``good riddance,'' since their departure
will let the party will become stronger. More than half the
country's 22 million people are Malay Muslims who have
traditionally voted UMNO to power since Malaysia became independent
in 1957. Mahathir has denied that UMNO's strength is being corroded
by the campaign set off by the firing and later arrest of his
deputy prime minister, Anwar Ibrahim. Anwar, who faces trial on
corruption and sexual misconduct charges, has denied any
wrongdoing. He says the charges are politically motivated to
silence him, at a time when he is emerging as the biggest challenge
to Mahathir. (MALAYSIA-POLITICS)
	   TASHKENT, Uzbekistan (AP) _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin, who
is suffering from a cold, will cut short his trip to Central Asia
and return to Moscow on Monday, one day ahead of schedule, Russian
news agencies said. No reason was given for the change in plans.
The announcement came shortly after Yeltsin arrived in Almaty, the
main city in Kazakstan. He came from neighboring Uzbekistan, where
he appeared stiff and stumbled on Sunday and canceled his public
appearances. On Monday he turned up more than an hour late for
talks with officials and abruptly cut short a scheduled news
conference. Aides said Yeltsin, 67, was suffering from a cold and
had had a bad flight from Moscow. The Russian leader has a history
of health problems, including multiple heart bypass surgery two
years ago. He has spent most of the last two months out of the
limelight and out of the Kremlin, holding meetings in his country
home outside Moscow. The trip to Central Asia was his first outside
of Russia since May when he went to Britain for the Group of Seven
summit of industrialized countries. (RUSSIA-YELTSIN)
</TEXT>
