<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0897 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 0000 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Most Asian stock markets closed sharply higher
Monday, boosted by the passage of legislation in the Japanese
parliament to help the country's ailing banks. Asian bourses were
also boosted by Wall Street's 2.17 percent gain Friday, and hopes
of a fresh round of global interest rate cuts. Tokyo's benchmark
Nikkei Stock Average rose 675.04 points, or 5.24 percent, closing
at 13,555.01. Hong Kong shares surged for the second consecutive
session Monday on expectations of cuts in both local and U.S.
interest rates. The blue-chip Hang Seng Index rose 483.48 points,
or 5.6 percent, to close at 8,990.27, its highest close since July
2. Malaysian and other markets were also buoyed by hints that the
United States and Europe are ready to coordinate efforts to help
Asia, said Richard Verin, director of Asia equity trading at Credit
Suisse First Boston in Hong Kong. Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar bought
116.72 yen in late afternoon, down 0.48 yen from late Friday in
Tokyo. (ASIAN MARKETS)
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Taking a major step toward tackling Japan's bad
debt crisis, the upper house of Parliament on Monday passed a plan
to use taxpayer money to clean up the country's deeply troubled
banks. The package, which was passed by the more powerful lower
house on Oct. 2, also boosts Japan's efforts to overcome its
deepest recession since the end of World War II. The markets took
the vote as a healthy sign the country is acting to address its
financial problems. The benchmark Nikkei Stock Average surged
675.04 points, or 5.24 percent, closing the day's trading at
13,555.01. The so-called financial stabilization plan creates a
special committee to oversee the cleanup of the nearly dlrs 1
trillion in bad debts left over from the burst of the speculative
``bubble economy'' in the early 1990s. Also set up would be an
organization similar to the U.S. Resolution Trust Corp., created
during the 1980s U.S. savings and loan crisis to buy the bad debt
from banks. (JAPAN-BANK BILLS)
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia's finance minister has acknowledged there
is no comprehensive, long-term strategy for rescuing the country's
economy and no plans to draft one this year. Mikhail Zadornov said
Sunday that the government would not draw up any long-term plans
``for at least the next three months.'' Instead, the government has
promised to make public its short-term plans for dealing with the
economic crisis by Oct. 20. ``I think that, in essence, it is
precisely such moves that will lay the foundation for setting
medium-term tasks in 1999,'' he said. Russia is urging the IMF to
release the next installment on a dlrs 22.6 billion loan negotiated
before the latest crisis struck in mid-August. Russia badly needs
the money to help pay its debts, but the IMF says it must first
come up with and implement measures to end the crisis. Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov maintains the government's plans hinge on
whether it gets the foreign aid. Without that aid, Russia is widely
expected to start printing more money, which will stoke inflation.
(RUSSIA-ECONOMY)
	   LUXEMBOURG (AP) _ The turmoil on world markets, a battle over
the European Union's budget and the economic impact of Italy's
political crisis dominated Monday's meeting of EU finance
ministers. The meeting came as slower growth rates and fears of
more gloom spreading from Asia, Russia and South America take some
of the shine off preparations for the launch of the euro as the
common currency of 11 EU nations on Jan. 1. So far, Europe has
avoided the worst of the global crisis. However, ministers face
mounting pressure to halt any further decline in growth, including
calls for interest rate cuts to help business. Ministers were also
to discuss the impact of the dollar's recent tumble and proposals
for strengthening international financial institutions to prevent
future outbreaks of global turbulence. Britain's Chancellor of the
Exchequer Gordon Brown said Sunday that his European colleagues
must share responsibility for creating ``conditions for growth and
stability around the world.'' (EU-FINANCE)
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Deprived of protection from
unemployment because of decades-old social biases, women have been
especially hurt by Asia's financial storm, officials said Monday.
Delegates to a conference on women at a meeting of Pacific Rim
leaders have urged steps to demolish such discrimination and to
provide women with better opportunities to overcome the crisis.
``Where poverty reigns, women are poorer than most men. Gender, to
be sure, is a function of nature. Poverty, however, is not,''
Philippine congresswoman Bellaflor Castillo told the delegates at
the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation Forum. The conference of
senior officials from APEC member countries aims to find ways of
giving women equal opportunities in workplaces and trade. The
recommendations will be offered to APEC ministers, who will hold a
two-day meeting in Manila starting Thursday. The ministers would
then bring the proposals to APEC heads of state, who will hold a
summit in the Malaysian capital of Kuala Lumpur next month.
(PHILIPPINES-APEC)
</TEXT>
