<HEADLINE>
Pro-Suharto group accused in legal aid office attack
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos Staffing

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Supporters of former President Suharto
attacked the office of the Indonesian Legal Aid Foundation on
Monday, lawyers at the human rights group said.
	   Police dispersed the self-proclaimed People's Voice Committee
after they broke windows and doors at the entrance of the
foundation's office in central Jakarta. No one was injured.
	   The group demanded that the foundation stop sheltering about 200
labor activists who have been living in its compound as part of an
anti-government protest.
	   The attackers also complained about rising criticism of Suharto,
who is now at the center of a government corruption investigation.
	   They accused the foundation of supporting causes that harmed
Indonesia's image abroad.
	   Senior lawyer Adnan Buyung Nasution said Monday's attack was the
first since the foundation was founded in 1970.
	   Last week, there was a similar attack against pro-reform
businessman Arifin Panigoro in southern Jakarta.
