<HEADLINE>
Italian government approves use of bases for possible raids over
</HEADLINE>
Kosovo

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Italy on Monday authorized the use of its military
bases for possible NATO air raids against Yugoslavia.
	   The government approved the use of the bases during an
extraordinary Cabinet meeting.
	   Italian forces, however, cannot take part in any NATO action
without the approval of Parliament.
	   Italian bases, including the air base in Aviano north of Venice,
played a key support role for the alliance during the recent war in
the Balkans.
	   The Cabinet is acting in a caretaker role following the
resignation of Premier Romano Prodi last week. During parliamentary
debate Thursday, Prodi raised questions about any role by Italy
when he said conditions were not yet ripe for a military strike.
	   Prodi needed the votes of far-left legislators, who are opposed
to any military action by NATO in the Balkans, particularly without
specific United Nations approval.
	   (vg/vls)
