w1110 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-Crime     10-12 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Crime </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cambodian police to search door to door for illegal weapons
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Door-to-door checks for illegal
weapons are set to begin next month in the Cambodian capital in an
effort to combat a recent surge in crime, a senior municipal
official said Monday.
	   Citing an increase in kidnappings and robberies, Phnom Penh
Deputy Gov. Chea Sophara said a general search warrant has been
requested at the Municipal Court to carry out searches if a home is
suspected to contain illegal weapons.
	   ``Police will go house to house to question residents if they
have weapons or not. If they do have weapons, they must have a
license for them,'' Chea Sophara said.
	   The increase in crime has affected foreign investment as youth
gangs often target foreigners as relatively wealthy victims, the
deputy governor said.
	   Foreign embassies, non-governmental organizations and
international organizations will be exempted from the weapons
dragnet.
	   Cambodia is awash with weapons, a legacy of decades of civil war
and strife. Assault rifles and handguns are a common sight on the
streets of Phnom Penh. Firearms, ammunition and even hand grenades
can be bought cheaply at local markets.
	   Residents of the capital fire their guns at the sky during heavy
rainstorms to chase off perceived evil spirits.
	   Shooting into the air is also the accepted way to alert the fire
department of a fire, and the turning of the Cambodian new year in
April sounds like a war as thousands of gun-owners unload their
weapons into the air simultaneously.
	   Chea Sophara said the weapons searches are a part of efforts to
curb the gun culture in the city.
	   ``I cannot allow random shooting throughout Phnom Penh during
rainfall or during the Cambodian New Year. At least nine to 10
people are hit during these outbursts,'' he said.
	   As an example of the seriousness of the problem, Chea Sophara
cited a roadblock police recently set up on a major street in the
capital to search for weapons. In an hour, more than 100 weapons,
mostly registered, had been found.
	   But other announced crackdowns on unregistered weapons in the
past had little evident effect.
</TEXT>
