<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Yeltsin, 7th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin cuts short trip to Central Asia for health reasons
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; URGENT &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: COMBINES pvs, minor editing; ADDS byline. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos planned &QL; 
 &UR; By ALEXANDER ZEMLIANICHENKO &QL; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ALMATY, Kazakstan (AP) _ Doctors ordered Russian President Boris
Yeltsin to cut short his trip to Central Asia for health reasons
Monday, and he agreed to return home a day early, the Interfax news
agency reported.
	   Yeltsin's aides had said he was suffering from a cold. The
67-year-old leader has a long history of health problems, but there
was no word that he had any illness aside from the cold.
	   The announcement came shortly after Yeltsin arrived in Almaty,
Kazakstan's main city, from neighboring Uzbekistan.
	   Yeltsin's spokesman Dmitry Yakushkin said doctors insisted that
the president return to Moscow for health reasons, Interfax said.
It gave no other details.
	   Yeltsin, 67, appeared stiff and stumbled when he landed in the
Uzbek capital of Tashkent on Sunday and canceled his public
appearances. On Monday, he turned up more than an hour late for
talks with officials and abruptly cut short a scheduled news
conference.
	   The Russian leader has had a number of health problems in recent
years, including multiple heart bypass surgery two years ago,
although he insists he has no major health problems and will serve
out the remaining two years of his term.
	   Yeltsin has spent most of the last two months out of the
limelight and out of the Kremlin, holding meetings in his country
home outside Moscow. The trip to Central Asia was his first outside
of Russia since May when he went to Britain for the Group of Seven
summit of industrialized countries.
	   Yeltsin has been scheduled to hold talks in Kazakstan on Monday
and Tuesday. The Kazak presidential press service said he would
compress his entire agenda into one day and fly back to Moscow on
Monday night.
	   Yeltsin had to be supported by Uzbek President Islam Karimov
when he arrived in Tashkent on Sunday. He canceled his other public
events, saying he wasn't feeling well, but held one-on-one talks
with Karimov as scheduled.
	   Yakushkin and Yeltsin's doctor, Sergei Mironov, said the
president was feeling better Monday, the Interfax news agency
reported.
	   However, Yeltsin showed up one hour late for talks Monday
between Russian and Uzbek officials, catching only the last 20
minutes. He also cut short his scheduled 20-minute news conference
to just a few minutes.
	   He and Karimov made brief statements and walked away without
taking any questions. Yeltsin walked unaided, but was closely
flanked by bodyguards.
	   ``We had to slightly change the program because of the tight
schedule,'' Yakushkin told reporters, refusing to give any further
details.
	   Following the talks, Yeltsin and Karimov signed a package of
agreements to boost economic and other ties.
	   ``We have agreed to establish closer cooperation in the
economic, political and military fields,'' Yeltsin said in his
statement.
	   Yeltsin's talks in Uzbekistan and Kazakstan were to have focused
on economic issues as well as concerns about fighting in
Afghanistan. The former Soviet republics in Central Asia fear an
influx of drugs, weapons and refugees as well as a possible
spillover of fighting from Afghanistan.
	   (pvs/ls/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
