<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Security Law </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government critic jailed without trial: Report
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Malaysia-Politics

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ The head of an Islamic group that
had joined two new anti-government coalitions was arrested Monday
under a law that allows imprisonment without trial, a Malaysian
media report said.
	   Shaari Sungip, the president of JIM, or the Malaysian Reform
Group, was arrested under the harsh Internal Security Act, the
Bernama news agency said.
	   His arrest brings to five the number of people detained recently
under the act, including former deputy prime minister Anwar
Ibrahim. Police detained 12 other Anwar associates, who have since
been released.
	   Since Anwar's arrest on Sept. 20, two new opposition coalitions
had formed, calling for an end to the ISA and justice for the
dissident politician. JIM was a member of both coalitions, which
are comprised of political parties and non-governmental groups.
	   A spokesman from federal police headquarters, Ghazali Mohamad
Amin, said Shaari was suspected of acts considered a threat to
national security.
	   Ghazali added that police released from custody Mahinder Singh
Randhawa, an engineer who was arrested Saturday under the Internal
Security Act while attending a pro-Anwar rally.
</TEXT>
