r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-Peso     10-12 0243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Peso </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine government comfortable with current peso level
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Philippine Budget Secretary Benjamin Diokno
said Monday he is comfortable with the peso's present exchange rate
and does not believe its recent gains pose a risk to the country's
export competitiveness.
	   ``Almost all Asian currencies have recovered because of the
stronger (Japanese) yen,'' Diokno said, adding that the Philippine
government is ``comfortable'' with the exchange rate.
	   The peso has posted strong gains against the dollar in recent
days, spurred by the yen.
	   Diokno is in Singapore to attend the East Asia Economic Summit,
sponsored by the World Economic Forum, a private agency based in
Switzerland that brings political and business leaders together.
	   Diokno said fears of a devaluation of the Chinese yuan that
might set off another round of currency devaluations in the region
are ``fading fast'' due to the recent strengthening of the yen.
	   The dollar would probably have to rebound to 160 yen to 170 yen
to rekindle fears of a yuan devaluation, he added.
	   Instead, the biggest threat of a setback to the Philippine
economy is the possibility of a recession in the United States,
Diokno said.
	   The United States is the Philippines' biggest trading partner
and accounted for 34 percent of total exports last year. By
comparison, only 13 percent of Philippine exports went to other
Southeast Asian markets. 	   
</TEXT>
