<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-China, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwan expresses optimism, flexibility on eve of China visit
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS thruout; INCORPORATES BC-Taiwan-China Visit; ADDS
background in 5th graf. &QL; 
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER BODEEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ Issuing calls for ``new thinking,'' Taiwan
said Monday that its top envoy was willing to discuss any issue
that would help get talks with China back on track during upcoming
meetings on the mainland.
	   Crucial meetings in Shanghai beginning Wednesday mark the start
of a ``new stage'' in relations, frozen for three years by China's
suspension of dialogue, a smiling Premier Vincent Siew told
negotiator Koo Chen-fu and his 12-member delegation.
	   Though careful not to promise results, Taiwan has expressed
cautious hopes that Koo's visit will point ties in the right
direction. At the least, contacts should ``nurture a pleasant
atmosphere,'' relations,'' Siew said.
	   ``We hope that the two sides will use new thinking and a new
approach to face the issues (and) rebuild a framework for relations
suited to the conditions of separation between the two sides,''
Siew said.
	   Siew's comments appeared to be a final appeal for China to seize
the opportunity afforded by Koo's visit to pave the way for
restoring formal talks.
	   China has made negotiations conditional on Taiwan agreeing to
discuss political issues relating to their reunification. But the
island has urged that agreements first be reached on practical
matters to create trust.
	   However, in a sign of flexibility, Siew reiterated earlier
comments that Taiwan is open to discussion on any issue helpful to
peaceful relations and eventual reunification.
	   But he added that Taiwan would not be dictated to by Beijing,
and said the sides should regard each other as equals.
	   Taiwan has tried hard to sweeten conditions for talks, canceling
a military display and visits abroad by its vice president that
could have riled Beijing. China responded by agreeing to allow 248
illegal aliens detained in Taiwan to return home, removing a major
headache for authorities here.
	   In a further sign of warming ties, Zhang Jiakun, vice governor
of China's Fujian province, will visit business leaders in Taiwan
starting Tuesday, the highest-ranking local-level official of the
Communist regime to visit the island.
	   Zhang will lead a small delegation on a four-day visit at the
invitation of Taiwan's Chinese National Federation of Industries,
the federation said Monday.
	   Koo's first stop will be in Shanghai, where he will meet Wang
Daohan, his Chinese counterpart.
	   Jan Jyh-horng, a deputy secretary general of Koo's semi-official
Straits Exchange Foundation, departed for China's commercial
capital Monday morning to make final preparations for the visit.
	   The Shanghai meeting will be the first between the elder
statesmen since the 1993 talks in Singapore that marked the first
formal contact between the sides since they split politically amid
civil war in 1949.
	   Based on an agreement they signed, the sides held talks on
practical issues such as recognition of legal documents, until
China backed out in June 1995 in anger over Taiwan's efforts to
raise its international profile.
	   China regards Taiwan as a breakaway province with no right to
foreign relations and refuses to recognize the government in
Taipei.
</TEXT>
