<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-East Timor, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thousands of East Timorese protest for second day
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES thruout with shootings; ADDS other details. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   DILI, Indonesia (AP) _ Witnesses said police fired warning shots
at protesting prison inmates while thousands of East Timorese
demonstrated for a referendum on independence for the troubled
territory Monday.
	   Human rights activists said two prisoners at Dili's main
penitentiary were shot and wounded when they tried to escape as
protesters gathered outside.
	   Police and prison officials were not immediately available for
comment.
	   It was the second consecutive day of protest in the capital of
the former Portuguese colony.
	   As many as 15,000 demonstrators took part, demanding that a
referendum be held on East Timor's future.
	   They rejected an offer made by the Indonesian government, as
part of U.N.-sponsored talks with Portugal, to grant autonomy, not
independence, to the province.
	   The protesters were angered by a recent demand by East Timor
Gov. Jose Abilio Osorio Soares that civil servants in the province
support the autonomy proposal or be fired.
	   The protesters arrived in hundreds of cars and motorcycles from
several regencies in the morning and joined others already in the
East Timor capital, Dili.
	   Waving banners and chanting pro-independence slogans, the
protesters marched down several streets.
	   Stores, offices and schools were closed. Hundreds of riot police
blocked the crowd from entering the compound of the governor's
office. There were no reports of violence or arrests.
	   ``We will keep on protesting until the government responds to
our demands,'' said Leandro Isaac, a protest organizer.
	   He also threatened to hold a similar protest for the release of
jailed East Timorese rebel leader Xanana Gusmao, who is now serving
a 30-year prison sentence in Indonesia's capital, Jakarta.
	   East Timor's Roman Catholic Bishop Carlos Belo called for calm.
	   Belo was quoted by the official Antara news agency as saying
that people ``should respect the rights of the others ... and not
to be destructive.''
	   Indonesia annexed East Timor in 1976 after invading the previous
year during a civil war. The United Nations does not recognize
Indonesia's sovereignty over the half-island territory.
</TEXT>
