w1133 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Tanzania-Burundi     10-12 0393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Tanzania-Burundi </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Third round of peace talks postponed
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHE NKRUNZIZA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ARUSHA, Tanzania (AP) _ The third round of talks aimed at
finding a peaceful solution to ethnic and political conflict in
Burundi has been postponed for a day or two, a spokesman for
mediator Julius Nyerere said Monday.
	   ``We are waiting for other members who will arrive this
afternoon from Bujumbura. We hope to begin the talks Tuesday,''
said Gen. Hashim Mbita.
	   But since Tuesday is the 37th anniversary of the assassination
in Bujumbura of Prince Louis Rwagasore, the prime
minister-designate following elections in September 1961 that paved
the way for independence from Belgium a year later, it is unlikely
that the talks will get underway before Wednesday.
	   They were to have begun Monday, but under a veiled threat of a
government pullout if sanctions imposed by neighboring countries on
Burundi two years ago when President Pierre Buyoya seized power
were not lifted.
	   Sources close to former Tanzanian President Nyerere say he was
not keen on lifting the sanctions until he sees how Buyoya's
government performs at the latest round of talks.
	   The first round opened in June, and was followed by another in
July when a cease-fire more or less took hold in most of the
country.
	   The sanctions were imposed to force Buyoya, a retired Tutsi
military officer who had previously served as president from 1987
to 1993, to return to a constitutional regime and begin talks with
Hutu rebels.
	   Buyoya claims those conditions have been met and that the
holding of the talks in which all major political parties and rebel
groups are represented is proof.
	   Mbita said heads of delegations were holding informal meetings
with Nyerere.
	   At least 200,000 people died since October 1993 when Tutsi
paratroopers assassinated Burundi's first democratically elected
president, Hutu Melchior Ndadaye.
	   There were initial widespread reprisals by majority Hutus
against minority Tutsis, but because the Tutsis control the army,
they seized the upper hand and drove many Hutus out of Bujumbura,
the capital and largest city in the tiny central African nation.
	   Buyoya said he intervened in July 1996 to staunch the bloodshed
after a coalition government was unable to control the situation.
	   (cn/sl)	   
</TEXT>
