<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-South Africa </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAfrica stadium calls for better training after violence
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ Officials at Ellis Park
stadium on Monday called for better training of security staff
after weekend violence injured six people and caused up to 250,000
rand (dlrs 43,000) in damage.
	   The violence occurred when fans charged into the central
Johannesburg stadium to see a Premier Soccer League clash Saturday
night between arch rivals Orlando Pirates and Kaizer Chiefs.
	   The rampaging fans set fire to ticket offices, ripped down gates
and stoned security officials, filling the 60,000-capacity stadium
to about 80,000.
	   ``We have requested the PSL send their staff on better training
courses so that they know how to handle these things,'' said Louis
Luyt Jr., stadium manager and son of former South African rugby
chief Louis Luyt.
	   Security is shared between stadium and league staff, but Luyt
said many of the league security officers fled their posts in the
face of the mob.
	   Police called in to quell the disturbance used stun grenades and
rubber bullets. During the fracas two civilians and four police
officers were injured.
	   Unlike in many parts of Europe, soccer hooliganism is rare in
South Africa. Luyt said this was the worst incident of its kind in
Ellis Park's history.
	   Trouble started after ticketless fans broke into the stadium and
filled all the empty seats. Fans with tickets were then barred from
the stadium, triggering the riot as the outraged supporters broke
inside.
	   The game ended in a goal-less draw.
	   (ph/djw)	   
</TEXT>
