<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Netherlands-Steelworker Protest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hoogovens workers, fearing layoffs, stage brief walkout
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) _ About 500 Dutch steel workers
briefly walked out Monday at Koninklijke Hoogovens NV, where
hundreds of jobs depend on the company's pending decision to invest
in one unit.
	   Dutch union member Jos Duynhoven said the workers, from
Hoogovens' Lange Produkten (long products) unit, held a meeting
followed by a march from the factory to the company's headquarters
in the city of Beverwijk. They were back on the job by noon.
	   ``We demand that management makes a quick decision'' on whether
to go ahead with a new electric oven, an investment estimated to
cost 70-75 million guilders (dlrs 35-38 million), Duynhoven said.
	   The workers of Lange Produkten, which produces concrete and
malleable steel and employs around 700 people, gave Hoogovens
management a petition demanding that a final decision be made by
the end of the month.
	   The outcome and timing of that decision could trigger more work
actions, Duynhoven said.
	   Hoogovens spokesman Stefan de Krijger said the company was still
reviewing whether to buy the new equipment. Without it, union and
company officials say, hundreds of the units' employees may be out
of a job.
	   (dj/bk)
</TEXT>
