<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Oil </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Youths demand that foreign oil workers leave delta region
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Youths who have been attacking oil
installations in Nigeria's southern delta region have ordered
foreign oil workers to leave the area by Monday, according to a
Lagos newspaper report.
	   A letter sent Sunday to foreign embassies urged them to ask
their nationals to leave by Monday, saying their safety could no
longer be guaranteed, the Vanguard newspaper reported.
	   The ethnic Ijaw youths also promised to step up activities
against oil companies in the region and to ``indefinitely'' sustain
their occupation of seized oil stations until their demands were
met.
	   The letter followed a week of angry protesters by the Ijaw
youths who have been attacking Shell sites in the oil-rich Niger
River delta region, trying to use Nigeria's dependence on petroleum
exports as leverage to force the government to pay attention to
their grievances.
	   On Thursday, the Anglo-Dutch giant Shell was forced to send a
notice to its crude buyers that it could not guarantee availability
of crude because of ``the shutdown of 378,000 barrels of crude
production from 15 flow stations.''
	   On Wednesday, armed protesters seized two helicopters belonging
to Shell Petroleum Development Company _ Shell's Nigerian joint
venture _ and took control of an oil rig.
	   Although rich in oil, the Niger River delta states are among the
poorest and most neglected in Nigeria. Ijaws make up a large
portion of the people of the delta region.
	   Basic infrastructure in towns and villages is often provided by
foreign oil companies operating in the area, because the government
has failed to provide paved roads, electricity and clean water.
	   (fa-ad-tjs)
</TEXT>
