<SLUG> BC-Japan-Missing Jets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Defense Agency confirms deaths of crashed fighter pilots
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Two pilots aboard a F-4EJ fighter jet that crashed
into the Pacific Ocean have been confirmed dead, the Japanese
military said Monday.
	   The Air Self-Defense Forces said the pilots were identified
through DNA tests from pieces of their corpse found in waters where
the plane's debris was also floating.
	   Killed in the crash were 1st Lt. Tomohiro Suetake, 28, and 2nd
Lt. Masahiro Ogasawara, 26, said an official with the forces,
speaking on customary condition of anonymity.
	   The McDonnell Douglas fighter crashed into the Pacific about 50
kilometers (30 miles) northeast of Misasa, northern Japan, Friday
night, he said.
	   The fighter was flying for Misawa from Chitose on Japan's
northern main island of Hokkaido after training exercises. Misawa
is 560 kilometers (350 miles) northwest of Tokyo.
	   The official said four fighters _ two F-4EJ fighters and two
Japan-developed F-1 fighters _ have crashed into the ocean since
April this year.
	   Four pilots have been killed, including Friday's crash, and two
ejected safely, he said. Defense officials are investigating the
cause of the crashes.
