<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Korean Air </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Troubled Korean Air unveils new safety programs
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Its image and balance sheet damaged by
safety problems, Korean Air said Monday it will spend 150 billion
won (dlrs 111 million) to improve maintenance, pilot training and
navigation systems by the year 2000.
	   The announcement came three days after the government slapped
the South Korean flag carrier with a multimillion dollar penalty
for a series of recent accidents.
	   ``We'll thoroughly overhaul our safety systems,'' Lee Jong-wook,
a KAL spokesman, said. ``We accept the government's punitive action
and will do our best to dispel uneasiness among passengers.''
	   Korean Air, the world's 13th largest carrier, has come under
intense fire from the government after it has been involved in
seven accidents in just over two months.
	   As penalties, the government ordered the airliner to cut 15
percent of its domestic flights for six months beginning on Oct. 25
and suspended some of its Seoul-Tokyo flights.
	   The heaviest penalty in South Korean aviation history will cost
Korean Air dlrs 30 million to dlrs 37 million in lost revenue and
hurt the already money-losing airline's efforts to improve its
battered image and finances, analysts said.
	   Korean Air's net loss amounted to dlrs 753 million last year,
according to Barre International Ltd.
	   Korean Air said it plans to ground its airplanes beginning on
Thursday for a safety check and maintenance. About half of its 112
planes will have been grounded by year's end, it said.
	   The airline will introduce advanced management and safety
programs under a dlrs 14 million, three-year contract with Delta
Airlines of the United States beginning this year.
	   New high-tech equipment, including flight simulation and safety
alert systems, will be introduced to strengthen pilot training and
prevent more accidents, airline officials said.
	   Korean Air has had seven minor accidents since Aug. 5, when a
Boeing 747-400 passenger plane from Tokyo skidded off a rain-slick
runway in Seoul, injuring 22 people.
	   Most of the recent accidents were blamed on poor maintenance and
pilot training.
	   Disasters have plagued the airline since 1983, when one of its
747s _ Flight 007 _ was shot down after straying into Soviet air
space, killing all 269 people on board.
	   Korean Air Flight 801 slammed into a Guam hillside on Aug. 6,
1997, killing 229 people. Only 26 people aboard the Boeing 747
survived.
	   Industry analysts blame Korean Air's accident-prone records for
its lax safety programs. They also note that the carrier flies 14
different types of aircraft, more than most major carriers.
	   The latest government penalty is especially bad news for Korean
Air at a time when competition is heating up at home with an
industry newcomer, Asiana.
	   The airliner has struggled with rising fuel costs and the
decline of the value of Korean currency, the won, against the
dollar, which raises the cost of servicing the company's dlrs 4.5
billion in foreign debt.
	   Last year, Korean Air carried 46 percent of all passengers
traveling in and out of South Korea. Korean Air adopted its present
name in 1984. Until then, it was Korean Airlines, or KAL.
</TEXT>
