<SLUG> BC-India-Kashmir ,0218 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Eight soldiers, two Muslim militants killed in Kashmir violence
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAMMU, India (AP) _ An Indian army patrol jeep was blown up by a
land mine Monday in the restive Kashmir region, killing five
soldiers, near the site of a gunbattle that left dead three
soldiers and two militants, police said.
	   Police said alleged militants placed the land mine on a mountain
road in the Mughal Maidan area 225 kilometers (140 miles) northeast
of the state's winter capital of Jammu. Five wounded soldiers were
admitted to hospital, three with serious injuries.
	   Four more soldiers were injured in the gunbattle in a dense
forest near the village of Pasarkot in the Doda district, officials
said.
	   In the state's summer capital of Srinagar, suspected Muslim
militants exploded a hand grenade in a shopping center injuring at
least three people, police said. The grenade was aimed at a bunker
of paramilitary forces, but it missed the target and wounded
shoppers, police said.
	   Nearly a dozen Muslim rebel groups are fighting a secessionist
war in Jammu-Kashmir, India's northern frontier province, since
1989. They demand an independent Kashmir or choice to join
neighboring Pakistan, an Islamic state. Kashmir is the only Muslim
majority state in predominantly Hindu India.
</TEXT>
