<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Viagra </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippines approves anti-impotence drug Viagra
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ The Philippines approved the use of
the anti-impotence drug Viagra Monday, possibly helping some 2.8
million Filipinos, officials said.
	   The Bureau of Food and Drug approved the drug after its
manufacturer completed a six-month study of its effects on 500 men
from six Asian countries, including the Philippines.
	   Pfizer, the manufacturer, will be able to sell Viagra in the
Philippines for three years, said bureau Director Quintin Kintanar.
	   Carlos Gasparian, Philippine representative of Pfizer said
Viagra will be available at local drugstores nationwide in the
first week of November for 450 pesos (dlrs 10.50) for each 50
milligram (0.002 ounce) pill.
	   A doctor's prescription will be required.
	   ``Viagra is a not a sexual stimulant,'' Gasparian told reporters
after the approval was announced. ``It should not be used by
anybody without sexual dysfunction.''
	   Dr. Sandra Torres, a Pfizer consultant, said the drug showed
tolerable side-effects under controlled conditions but warned the
drug should not be taken by people using nitrates drugs for heart
problems.
	   She said that the drug was found to be effective in about 70
percent or 46 out of 66 Filipino men who took it under the study.
	   Filipino have generally relied on traditional balms, herbs,
home-made concoctions and Chinese traditional medicine to deal with
impotence.
</TEXT>
