<HEADLINE>
Cargo jet burst tires and damage runway lights
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ A cargo jet chartered by Emirates Airline that
burst two tires Monday when taking off from Hong Kong's new airport
damaged two runway lights after it was forced to return, officials
said.
	   The airport had to be shut down three times, they said. The
runway was first closed for 30 minutes after the Boeing 747 burst
its tires to check for any debris, and then again for a similar
period after the plane returned and hit two runway lights.
	   The airport was closed briefly for a third time later to inspect
the repairs.
	   The closures caused delays to 30 incoming and outgoing flights,
airport officials said.
	   An Emirates Airline employee said the cargo jet was bound for
Dubai, but it was not known what cargo it was carrying.
	   The U.S. dlrs 20.1 Chek Lap Kok airport opened in July on an
outlying island. Its opening was marred by computer and mechanical
glitches.
</TEXT>
