<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Illegal Workers </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai police deport 270,000 foreigners to create jobs for Thais
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ More than 270,000 illegal foreign
workers have been deported since January as part of an effort to
free up jobs for unemployed Thai workers, police said.
	   In addition to the deportations, 34 people have been arrested on
charges of smuggling foreigners into the country while 111 others
were arrested on suspicion of housing them, said an immigration
department news release received Monday.
	   Despite the high number of deportees, only one employer was
arrested on charges of hiring illegal workers.
	   Thailand has been an economic magnet for much of Southeast Asia,
drawing poor workers from impoverished neighbors Myanmar, Cambodia
and Laos.
	   At the end of last year, Thailand had about 1 million illegal
immigrant workers, about 90 percent of them from neighboring
Myanmar, also known as Burma.
	   Some 200,000 won temporary legal status after registering with
the government last year.
	   Thai governments had long turned a blind eye to illegal foreign
workers. Some employers favor them because they are willing to work
for low wages and are less likely to complain about abuses.
	   But in the past year, the unemployment rate has risen
dramatically as more factories have closed amid a sharp economic
downturn.
	   More than a million Thais have become unemployed since the
region's currency crisis began in July 1997.
	   Employers in some industries have sought exemptions from the
foreign worker ban because they say Thais won't do hard manual
labor. Limited exemptions have been granted for some border areas
and in the rice-milling and fishing sectors. 	   
</TEXT>
