<SLUG> BC-Russia-Yeltsin, 8th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin cuts short trip to Central Asia for health reasons
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with details on Yeltsin's condition,
Yeltsin's spokesman saying that Kosovo crisis was another motive
behind Yeltsin cutting short his visit, more details, quotes. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos planned &QL; 
 &UR; By ALEXANDER ZEMLIANICHENKO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ALMATY, Kazakstan (AP) _ Doctors ordered Russian President Boris
Yeltsin to cut short his trip to Central Asia for health reasons
Monday, and he agreed to return home a day early, the Interfax news
agency reported.
	   Yeltsin's aides said he was suffering from a respiratory
infection, had a fever and was being treated with antibiotics.
Yeltsin went ahead with talks with Kazak President Nursultan
Nazerbayev and would move up all his scheduled meetings before
returning home Monday evening, they said.
	   The 67-year-old Russian leader has a long history of health
problems, but the Kremlin said there were no plans to hospitalize
him.
	   Yeltsin's spokesman Dmitry Yakushkin said doctors insisted that
the president return to Moscow on Monday instead of Tuesday as
scheduled. The president agreed in part so that he could focus on
efforts to end fighting in the Serb province of Kosovo, Yakushkin
said.
	   ``Boris Yeltsin was against cutting short his visit to
Kazakstan, but he headed doctors' demands,'' Yakushkin said. ``The
president has a cold and a cough. You're supposed to stay in bed
when you have a cold.''
	   The announcement came shortly after Yeltsin arrived in Almaty,
Kazakstan's main city, from neighboring Uzbekistan.
	   Yeltsin appeared stiff and stumbled when he arrived in the Uzbek
capital of Tashkent on Sunday and later canceled his public
appearances. On Monday, he turned up more than an hour late for
talks with officials and abruptly cut short a scheduled news
conference.
	   The Russian leader has had a number of health problems in recent
years, including multiple heart bypass surgery two years ago,
although he insists he has no major health problems and will serve
out the remaining two years of his term.
	   Yeltsin has spent most of the last two months out of the Kremlin
despite the country's economic crisis, holding meetings in his
country home outside Moscow. The trip to Central Asia was his first
outside of Russia since May when he went to Britain for the Group
of Seven summit of industrialized countries.
	   Yeltsin was scheduled to hold talks in Kazakstan on Monday and
Tuesday. Yakushkin insisted that Yeltsin would eliminate his rest
time in Kazakstan so that he could still conduct all the meetings
on his schedule.
	   As he spoke, Yeltsin began his meeting with the Kazak president.
	   Yeltsin had to be supported by Uzbek President Islam Karimov
when he arrived in Tashkent on Sunday. He canceled his other public
events, saying he wasn't feeling well, but held one-on-one talks
with Karimov as scheduled.
	   Yakushkin and Yeltsin's doctor, Sergei Mironov, had said the
president was feeling better Monday, the Interfax news agency
reported.
	   However, Yeltsin showed up one hour late for talks Monday
between Russian and Uzbek officials, catching only the last 20
minutes. He also cut short his scheduled 20-minute news conference
to just a few minutes.
	   Yeltsin read his brief statement in a strong voice, rarely
raising his eyes from the text. He walked away unaided, but was
closely flanked by bodyguards.
	   Following the talks, Yeltsin and Karimov signed a package of
agreements to boost economic and other ties.
	   ``We have agreed to establish closer cooperation in the
economic, political and military fields,'' Yeltsin said in his
statement.
	   Yeltsin's talks in Uzbekistan and Kazakstan were to have focused
on economic issues as well as concerns about fighting in
Afghanistan. The former Soviet republics in Central Asia fear an
influx of drugs, weapons and refugees as well as a possible
spillover of fighting from Afghanistan.
	   Yeltsin's opponents, including the Communists, have long charged
that Yeltsin's condition makes him unable to work and pushed for
his resignation. Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov renewed this
call on Monday.
	   ``Yeltsin is unable to work more than two or three hours a
day,'' he said at a news conference in Moscow. ``He is even unable
to review guards of honour.''
	   (pvs/ls/gm)	   
</TEXT>
