<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Social Laws </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU warns Belgium, Luxembourg, Spain over social laws
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) - The European Commission on Monday gave
Belgium, Luxembourg and Spain two months to extend a system of
reduced railway fares to include migrant workers from other EU
countries, or face court action.
	   The Commission, the European Union's executive body, said
national law in these countries reserved reduced tariffs for large
families for people residing within their borders and denied them
to cross-border EU workers.
	   The Commission claimed such legislation violates EU law which
states that migrant workers and members of their families are
entitled to the same benefits as nationals of the country in which
they work.
	   The Commission issued a separate warning against Spain over
access to jobs in the public service.
	   Despite certain improvements in Spain's legislation, in practice
a majority of administrative jobs are reserved for Spanish
nationals, the Commission said.
	   Spain has two months to comply with EU law or the Commission
could take it to court.
	    &UR; (as-rac)
</TEXT>
