<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin cautiously optimistic about Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS TO UPDATE with Yeltsin reaxn, general saying Russia
may reconsider arms embargo; ADDS byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By LESLIE SHEPHERD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin is ``cautiously
optimistic'' that a peaceful solution can be found to the crisis in
the Serbian province of Kosovo, his spokesman said Monday.
	   But a Russian general warned that Moscow may reconsider its
support for the international arms embargo if Serb-led Yugoslavia
is targeted by NATO airstrikes, the Interfax news agency said.
	   Russia vehemently opposes airstrikes against Yugoslavia, a
traditional ally with which it shares a Slavic heritage and
Orthodox religion, and has been lobbying for a negotiated solution.
	   Yeltsin was buoyed by the fact that U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke
was still in Belgrade talking with Serb officials, said his
spokesman, Dmitry Yakushkin. Yeltsin was ``cautiously optimistic''
that chances for a peaceful solution have ``slightly increased,''
Yakushkin said, according to the ITAR-Tass news agency.
	   Yakushkin said the Kosovo crisis was one of the reasons Yeltsin
agreed to cut short his trip to Central Asia. Doctors ordered him
to return to Moscow for health reasons.
	   The ``huge responsibility in connection with the situation
regarding Kosovo weighs on the president,'' Yakushkin said.
	   The head of the international military cooperation department of
the Russian Defense Ministry said Moscow may reconsider its support
for the international arms embargo if NATO takes action without
specific approval from the U.N. Security Council.
	   ``If the North Atlantic alliance uses force against Yugoslavia
without the sanction of the U.N. Security Council, Russia will have
the right to revise its attitude to the embargo on military
cooperation with Yugoslavia,'' Col.-Gen. Leonid Ivashov said,
according to Interfax.
	   Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said the Russian government
was still considering how it would respond if NATO went ahead with
airstrikes to force Serbia, the leading republic in Yugoslavia, to
end its violent crackdown on ethnic Albanians in Kosovo province.
	   Ivanov said Sunday in Central Asia, where he is accompanying
Yeltsin on an official visit, that a Russian military response was
``out of the question.''
	   ``We continue to believe and not only to believe but also to do
everything to prevent the worst,'' he said on TV.
	   Russia has recalled its representative to NATO and its
ambassador to Belgium, where NATO has its headquarters, for
consultations. Foreign Ministry official Vladimir Chizov said their
return to Brussels will depend on developments, the Interfax news
agency reported Monday.
	   Chizov, director of the Foreign Ministry's Third European
Department, said Russia is staying in touch with Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic and members of the Contact Group on Yugoslavia.
	   (pvs/ls/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
