<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Impeachment </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Impeachment campaign against Yeltsin stalls again
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ANNA DOLGOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The impeachment campaign against Boris Yeltsin
faltered again Monday, when a parliamentary commission failed to
reach agreement on the accusation of launching the unsuccessful war
in Chechnya.
	   ``All members of the commission agreed that the president had
exceeded his powers, but as to the accusation of the killings of
people in Chechnya, that question was not supported,'' commission
chairman Vadim Filimonov said.
	   The impeachment campaign by the Communist-led opposition began
long before the current economic crisis in Russia. It appears
likely to fail, as have several previous efforts, in part because
the constitution gives Yeltsin the upper hand in dealing with
parliament.
	   The commission was to complete its work Monday, but the lack of
agreement means a further delay in putting any impeachment motion
on parliament's agenda.
	   The commission has reached a verdict against Yeltsin on the
accusations of instigating the Soviet Union's collapse and sending
troops and tanks against hard-liners in the former Russian
parliament in October 1993.
	   ``Yeltsin has committed actions that have features of a grave
crime ... that is, high treason,'' read a commission report
obtained by The Associated Press.
	   Meanwhile, Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov resumed his call
for Yeltsin to resign.
	   ``The greatest problem is that (Yeltsin) has had great
difficulty in finding his bearings for a very long time, and does
not realize what is actually happening in the country,'' Zyuganov
was quoted as saying by the Interfax news agency.
	   Yeltsin was forced to cut short a trip to Central Asia on Monday
on his doctors' orders. Presidential aides said he was suffering
from a respiratory infection, had a fever and was being treated
with antibiotics.
	   An impeachment motion requires a two-thirds majority vote in
parliament's lower house, the State Duma. If it passed there, the
motion would then need to be approved by a two-thirds majority in
three other bodies: the upper house or Federation Council, and both
the Constitutional and Supreme Courts.
	   The development would be extremely unlikely, as both bodies are
largely made up of Yeltsin supporters.
	   (ad/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
