<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Power Outage </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Power outage blacks out wide areas of main Philippine island of
</HEADLINE>
Luzon

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ A power outage blacked out wide areas
of the main Luzon island for several hours Monday, disrupting
operations at Manila's international airport and at the
presidential palace.
	   A breakdown in two power plants and a major power transmission
line south of Manila caused the outage, the state-run National
Power Corporation said.
	   A Napocor official said they were investigating the cause of the
breakdown in the plants but said they did not suspect any sabotage.
	   It took at least five hours to restore power in Manila and most
other areas, officials said.
	   At the Ninoy Aquino International Airport in Manila, emergency
power generators failed to activate for at least 15 minutes,
halting cargo conveyor belts and preventing movable passageways to
be connected to planes at the passenger terminal.
	   Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said generators provided
power at the Malacanang presidential palace but many offices were
without power for hours.
	   President Joseph Estrada is on a four-day state visit in
Singapore.
	   A power crisis in 1992 during the term of President Corazon
Aquino caused up to 12 hours of outages in most of Luzon daily,
seriously hurting Manila's economy. 	   
</TEXT>
