<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Hungary </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hungarian foreign minister meets Ukrainian officials
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo KIV101 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ Hungary's foreign minister said Monday that
the weakness of Ukrainian companies was the main obstacle to
strengthening economic ties between the two countries.
	   On the second day of his two-day visit to Ukraine, Foreign
Minister Janos Martonyi said Hungary was nonetheless interested in
expanding economic ties.
	   ``Therefore, we have to resolve the issue of government
guarantees for our investments,'' Martonyi said.
	   Trade turnover between the two neighbors stands at a low dlrs
500 million to dlrs 530 million a year, Martonyi noted at a meeting
with Ukraine's deputy parliament speaker Adam Martyniuk, according
to the Interfax news agency.
	   Martyniuk said parliament supported an expansion of ties with
Hungary and pledged speedy ratification of bilateral agreements
that Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma plans to sign during his
Oct. 27-28 visit to Budapest.
	   The Hungarian minister also met Monday with Kuchma, Prime
Minister Valery Pustovoitenko and Foreign Minister Borys Tarasiuk.
	   Tarasiuk said the two sides had discussed travel and trade
regulations that might be toughened if Hungary is accepted into the
European Union.
	   Kiev is concerned about the possible consequences of its East
European neighbors' membership in the EU and has been holding talks
with Poland, Hungary and EU member nations in an attempt to
minimize the impact.
	   (sms/ji) 	   
