w1276 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Africa-Briefs     10-12 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Africa-Briefs </SLUG>

 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 
 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Nigeria, Tanzania, Kenya, South Africa &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   --
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Retired Nigerian generals have asked the
military junta to ban current and former generals from running for
president in next year's elections, a newspaper said Monday.
	   A group of retired generals met with junta leader Gen.
Abdulsalami Abubakar last week in the capital, Abuja, ThisDay
newspaper said. The group told Abubakar that allowing generals to
run would taint Nigeria's democratization process.
	   The move would stave off the possible candidacy of Gen. Olusegun
Obasanjo, a former Nigerian military leader who is mulling a run
for the presidency. Obasanjo, who came to power in 1976 after a
failed coup attempt took the life of military leader Gen. Murtala
Muhammed, relinquished power and retired in 1979.
	   While he has yet to say whether he will run for office, Obasanjo
has met with leaders of one of Nigeria's leading party's, the
People's Democratic Party.
	   --
	   DAR ES SALAAM, Tanzania (AP) _ The government of the autonomous
region of Zanzibar has no plans to allow producers of alcoholic
beverages to sponsor sports clubs and competitions, the East
African said Monday.
	   The weekly newspaper said Minister of Information, Culture and
Youth Issa Mohammed said a ban on such sponsorships was in the best
interest of the majority of Zanzibaris, who are Muslim.
	   Some soccer clubs in Zanzibar and neighboring Pemba island had
petitioned
	   President Salmin Amour to lift the ban, which would allow them
to receive funds from breweries as do teams in mainland Tanzania.
	   The ban on advertising alcohol in Zanzibar forced the regional
government
	   to spend 50 million shillings (dlrs 66,000) to pay for the East
and Central African soccer championships last December after a
brewery was ruled out as a
	   sponsor.
	   Tanzania Breweries Ltd., which sponsors the national Union Super
League, has provided more than dlrs 200,000 worth of equipment and
cash grants to mainland clubs, the newspaper said.
	   It said negotiations were still ongoing with TBL over the
sponsorship of the third annual Zanzibar National Marathon.
	   --
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ Kenyan teachers ignored President Daniel
arap Moi's call for them to work Monday as their strike for a raise
promised but not delivered entered its second week.
	   ``Strikers do not go back to work in response to public
political pronouncements, which are distinct from return-to-work
formulas,'' the Daily Nation on Monday quoted Kenya National Union
of Teachers official Mureu Kamau as saying.
	   KNUT officials were to meet Monday and Tuesday to discuss Moi's
request.
	   ``The strikers will remain out of class until they receive
official communication from the union's head office,'' KNUT
officials told the East African Standard newspaper.
	   The government has locked the union out of its headquarters.
	   It had promised raises of up to 200 percent last year when
teachers went on strike before general elections.
	   On Saturday at a ceremony marking Moi's 20 years in office, the
president
	   called on teachers to return to work Monday without conditions.
	   Education Minister Kalonzo Musyoka has said if the raises agreed
on last year were put into effect, 80 percent of his ministry's
1998-99 budget of 44 billion shillings (dlrs 733 million) would go
to pay salaries.
	   The strike by about 260,000 teachers has idled 7 million
students in primary and secondary school students.
	   --
	   DURBAN, South Africa (AP) _ A pipeline carrying petrol burst
outside Durban on Monday, spilling at least 250,000 liters of fuel.
	   Repairs were underway and the line _ between Durban and
Johannesburg _ was expected to be running again by Tuesday, said
Petronet spokeswoman Sanet Knoetze. The cause of the break was not
yet known.
	   Environmentalists were called to help assess the damage.
	   (var-djw-aos)
</TEXT>
