<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Syria </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Egypt relays message from Syria to Turkish president
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ Egypt pursued its efforts Monday to cool
off a crisis between Syria and Turkey over Kurdish rebels, as
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa held talks with Turkish
officials.
	   Moussa will relay a message from Syrian President Hafez Assad to
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel, Turkish officials said.
	   The daily Sabah claimed Monday that Syria had given in to
Turkish demands and agreed in the message to end its alleged
support of Kurdish rebels fighting for autonomy in Turkey's
southeast.
	   But Foreign Minister Ismail Cem insisted that Turkey was
awaiting concrete steps from the Syrians rather than promises,
independent NTV television reported.
	   Iran is also trying to mediate in the crisis.
	   Ankara stepped up its rhetoric against Syria two weeks ago,
accusing Damascus of harboring Kurdish rebels and providing them
with financial and logistics support. It has demanded that Damascus
end its support and extradite their leaders. Syria has denied the
accusations.
	   Some 37,000 people have died in the Kurdish rebel war against
Ankara since 1984.
	   Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz raised the stakes in Ankara's
face-off with its southern neighbor on Sunday, saying: ``If Syria
does not come to its senses, it is our incumbent duty to bring the
world down on them ... It is our incumbent duty to poke out the
eyes of those who have eyes on our territory.''
	   Defense Minister Ismet Sezgin said Sunday that Turkish forces
would conduct maneuvers along the Turkish-Syrian border in
November. There have been unconfirmed reports of a Turkish troop
buildup along the Syrian border.
	   Meanwhile, Tunisian Foreign Minister Said Bin Mustafa is
expected to hold talks with Assad in Damascus Monday.
	   (ht/vls)
</TEXT>
