<HEADLINE>
U.S. mountaineer dies on Himalayan slopes
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) _ An American alpinist died on the slopes
of Mt. Baruntse, the Nepalese tourism ministry said Monday.
	   Raoul Willie, a 45-year-old businessman from Aspen, Colorado,
died on Sunday after suffering from acute high altitude pulmonary
and cerebral edema near the base camp at 4,300 meters (14,200
feet).
	   Willie was part of a 12-member group led by Richard Jackson, 48,
of Basalt, Colorado, that was attempting to climb the 7,129 meters
high (23,525 feet) Mt. Baruntse.
	   Last week, a Greek mountaineer was reported missing on Mt.
Dhaulagiri.
	   The autumn mountaineering season on the Himalayas began Sept. 1.
</TEXT>
