<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP Europe Advisory </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   EDITORS: The following stories have moved or will move on the
European circuits of The Associated Press by 1600 GMT unless
otherwise noted:
	   BELGRADE _ With NATO warplanes shifted closer for possible NATO
airstrikes, a U.S. envoy described the Kosovo standoff as an
``emergency'' Monday and demanded the Yugoslav leader end his
crackdown. YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO.
	   BRUSSELS _ The NATO nations awaited word from Monday's Kosovo
talks in Belgrade before deciding whether to take a vital military
step that would bring airstrikes against the Serbs ominously close.
NATO-KOSOVO.
	   (Full NATO council tentatively scheduled to meet at 1500 GMT).
	   WITH:
	   _ KOSOVO-PRISTINA MOOD. Fear grips Kosovo capital as
negotiations drag on.
	   _ BALKAN SUMMIT. Turkey and Greece, traditional enemies, join
forces on Kosovo.
	   _ BOSNIA-US. Americans ordered out of Serb-held half of Bosnia.
	   _ US-KOSOVO. Intimidation of Slododan Milosevic said to be first
aim of allied attacks.
	   _ RUSSIA-KOSOVO. Boris Yeltsin ``cautiously optimistic'' about
Kosovo.
	   _ FRANCE-KOSOVO. French defense minister says NATO strikes on
Yugoslavia could be lengthy.
	   _ GERMANY-KOSOVO. Germany backs airstrikes in Kosovo.
	   _ BRITAIN-KOSOVO. Britain closing embassy in Yugoslavia.
	   _ ITALY-KOSOVO. Italy authorizes the use of its military bases
for possible NATO air raids.
	   ALMATY, Kazakstan _ Doctors ordered Russian President Boris
Yeltsin to cut short his trip to Central Asia for health reasons
Monday, and he agreed to return home a day early, the Interfax news
agency reported. RUSSIA-YELTSIN.
	   WITH:
	   _ RUSSIA-IMPEACHMENT. Impeachment campaign against Yeltsin
stalls again.
	   _ RUSSIA-ECONOMY. No long-term strategy yet for Russian economy,
finance minister says.
	   _ RUSSIA-REGIONAL ELECTIONS. Nizhny Novgorod, Lipetsk get new
mayors; runoffs expected in Kaliningrad.
	   _ RUSSIA-CHECHNYA. Chechen leader again criticizes generals
calling for his ouster.
	   STOCKHOLM _ Three Americans won the Nobel Medicine Prize on
Monday for discovering new properties of nitric oxide, which is key
to the anti-impotence drug Viagra and has other applications
ranging from treating heart disease to shock. NOBEL-MEDICINE.
	   WITH:
	   _ NOBEL-MEDICINE-LIST. Past winners.
	   _ NOBEL-MEDICINE-NITRIC OXIDE. What it does.
	   LUXEMBOURG _ The turmoil on world markets, a battle over the
European Union's budget and the economic impact of Italy's
government crisis dominated Monday's meeting of EU finance
ministers. EU-FINANCE.
	   WITH:
	   _ EU-GREEK ECONOMY. EU gives cautious approval to Greek economic
plans.
	   SINGAPORE _ Central bank governors, finance ministers and stock
exchange chiefs meet for the World Economic Forum's East Asian
conference, seeking solutions to the region's economic crisis.
ASIA-ECONOMIC CONFERENCE.
	   WITH:
	   _ JAPAN-BANK BILLS. Japan's parliament on Monday passed a plan
to use taxpayer money to clean up the country's troubled banks.
	   _ ASIAN MARKETS. Asian stock markets rose Monday in response.
	   TEHRAN _ An Iranian foundation has added dlrs 300,000 to the
reward for ``Satanic Verses'' author Salman Rushdie's death, just
weeks after the Iranian government tried to distance itself from
the bounty. IRAN-RUSHDIE.
	   WITH:
	   _ IRAN-US. Iran accuses United States of trying to increase Gulf
tension.
	   ROME _ Three days after the collapse of Premier Romano Prodi's
center-left government, Italy's president began calling in
political leaders Monday to try to reach a consensus on a new
government. ITALY-POLITICS.
	   THE HAGUE _ A Bosnian Muslim war crimes suspect should get a
milder sentence because he suffers from mental problems worsened by
the war, his lawyer told a U.N. tribunal Monday. YUGO-WAR CRIMES.
	   AMSTERDAM _ Prime Minister Wim Kok, his finance minister and the
Dutch central bank chief were rebuked Monday for buying a dlrs 40
million abstract painting with taxpayers' money and donating it to
a museum. NETHERLANDS-MONDRIAN FLAP.
	   BONN _ Germany's Social Democrats and Greens bog down over plans
to raise energy taxes and scrap nuclear power, two of the toughest
topics in talks on forming a new center-left government.
GERMANY-COALITION TALKS.
	   BAKU, Azerbaijan _ With opposition groups boycotting the vote,
Azerbaijan's authoritarian leader looked certain to be re-elected
president by voters seeking stability and long-elusive prosperity
for their oil-rich country. AZERBAIJAN-ELECTION.
	   JERUSALEM _ A senior Palestinian negotiator says the success of
a peace summit in Washington depends on a clear-cut ``yes'' from
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to a U.S. initiative.
ISRAEL-PALESTINIAN.
	   PARIS _ Thirty Muslim leaders from around the world have
appealed to Islamic insurgents in Algeria to join a truce called a
year ago, saying blind violence by fighters was helping to pervert
Islam. ALGERIA-TRUCE.
	   CANBERRA _ Foreign Minister Alexander Downer on Monday won one
of the tightest contests of Australia's election, after being
targeted by a right-wing populist party for attacking its leader's
criticism of Asians. AUSTRALIA-FOREIGN MINISTER.
