<SLUG> BC-Croatia-Politics,0155 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Croatian defense minister resigns, signifying government rift
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) _ Defense Minister Andrija Hebrang resigned
unexpectedly Monday, signifying a rift within President Franjo
Tudjman's ruling party.
	   Hebrang, who has been a devoted Tudjman supporter, also said he
would no longer head the medical team taking care of the
76-year-old Tudjman. In addition, he resigned the position of the
vice president of Tudjman's Croatian Democratic Union.
	   In his letter to Tudjman, released by the state-run news agency
HINA, Hebrang made it clear that Tudjman's failure to uphold his
attempts to replace two of his associates prompted him to resign.
	   Hebrang did not name the two, although it has long been known
that Hebrang wanted to get rid of Markica Rebic, head of military
counter-intelligence, and Vlado Zagorac, who leads the ministry's
firm for arms purchases.
</TEXT>
