<HEADER>
w1301 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Azerbaijan-Election 3rdLd-Writethru   10-12 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Azerbaijan-Election, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Azerbaijani president expected to win re-election
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Aliev's rival accusing government of rigging
ballot in new grafs 5-6. Trims. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos BAK101-105 &QL; 
 &UR; By MISHA DZHINDZHIKASHVILI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAKU, Azerbaijan (AP) _ With leading opposition groups
boycotting the vote, Azerbaijan's authoritarian president looked
certain to be re-elected by voters seeking stability and
long-elusive prosperity for their oil-rich Caspian Sea nation.
	   Voters on Sunday chose between President Geidar Aliev, 75, and
five other candidates, most of whom were widely believed to be
running only to make the election appear competitive.
	   A spokesman for Aliev's campaign headquarters said that while
ballots were still being counted, ``it's already clear that
President Geidar Aliev has won,'' the Interfax news agency
reported.
	   Turnout was high, with 78 percent of eligible voters casting
ballots, easily surpassing the 25 percent minimum turnout required
to validate the election, the Central Electoral Commission
reported.
	   Aliev's leading rival, Etibar Mamedov, accused the government
Monday of rigging the ballot and said he would go to court to
protest the results of the vote.
	   ``According to my information, Aliev got no more than 60
percent, but they are going to announce that he got 75,'' Mamedov
said at a news conference.
	   Other opposition leaders also cried foul. They said that the
electoral commission's announcement that results would not be known
for four days suggested Aliev's government would tamper with the
outcome.
	   Commission member Fuad Agayev said there were reports of
violations in several regions. In some cases, ballots were kept
outside polling stations and in Aliev's home Nakhichevan region,
the turnout was 100 percent, an impossibly high showing, Agayev
said.
	   Other commission members disagreed with Agayev, who represents
Mamedov, saying there were no serious violations. International
observers said they had noticed only a few minor technical
problems, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported. More than 200
observers monitored the vote.
	   Voting was peaceful in the former Soviet republic of 7.5
million, which was once plagued by war and political chaos.
	   The stability that has taken hold in recent years appeared to be
working in favor of Aliev, who was Azerbaijan's KGB chief and then
Communist Party boss during the Soviet era and retook power in a
bloodless 1993 coup.
	   Aliev has overseen the development of Azerbaijan's Caspian Sea
oil fields, but chronic corruption and sagging world oil prices
have meant that the country has yet to enjoy the economic windfall
Aliev has been predicting for years.
	   The main opposition leaders decided to boycott the election,
saying that Aliev would stack the ballot in his favor.
	   If no candidate wins at least two-thirds of the vote, a second
round must be held. In the last elections that followed the 1993
coup, Aliev won with 98 percent support.
	   (pvs/vi/ji/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
