<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Balkan-Summit,0567 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkey and Greece join forces on Kosovo, but unable to talk about
</HEADLINE>
own disputes &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos Available &QL; 
 &UR; By SUZAN FRASER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ANTALYA, Turkey (AP) _ Traditional enemies Greece and Turkey
united Monday to pressure Yugoslavia into making concessions on
Kosovo, but the two neighbors have so far been unable to make any
headway on their own disputes such as Cyprus.
	   Solving their own disputes is important if the two countries
hope to set an example for other leaders gathered in this
Mediterranean resort and help the turbulent region realize their
dream of European Union and NATO membership. Prime ministers from
Bulgaria, Macedonia and Romania are at the two-day summit as are
the foreign minister of Albania and observers from Bosnia and
Croatia.
	   ``Considering the recent history of our region, a gathering of
all heads of state and government and of their ministers ... is an
achievement by itself,'' said Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz.
	   Although Greek Premier Costas Simitis agreed that ``it is highly
encouraging to meet and agree on further action,'' he added that
summits between Balkan leaders can ``only prove successful in the
long run if we also tackle difficult problems which affect all of
us.''
	   All have joined to persuade Yugoslavia to accept a reference to
Kosovo in their joint statement and avert its political ouster from
the Balkan initiative, but Greece and Turkey have been unable to
see eye-to-eye on their own disputes in the Aegean and war-divided
Cyprus. They have nearly gone to war three times in the past 24
years over those disputes.
	   War may be likely if Greek Cypriots go ahead with plans to
deploy Russian-made S-300 missiles next month. Turkey has said it
will use military force to prevent their installation. Athens has
said such an action would mean war between the two NATO allies.
	   Yilmaz and Simitis plan to meet on the sidelines and hold their
first meeting in nearly one year, and hopefully find a way to ease
tensions. A conflict between the region's two most powerful
countries would make the Kosovo crisis pale by comparison.
	   Cyprus is an issue on which Turkey does not fool around. It
invaded and occupied its northern third in 1974 in the wake of an
abortive Athens-backed coup by Greek-Cypriot supporters of union
with Greece. It retains more than 30,000 combat troops in the
Turkish Cypriot breakaway state, recognized only by Ankara.
	   Turkey's apparent determination to start a war with military
powerhouse Syria over its harboring of Turkish Kurdish insurgents
is indicative of the no-nonsense approach taken by its military,
which essentially pulls Ankara's foreign policy strings.
	   During the first Balkan summit on the Greek island of Crete last
year, Greece and Turkey agreed to revive a long-dormant
American-backed nonaggression pact. But in the 11 months that
followed, relations between European Union-member Greece and Turkey
hit rock bottom after the EU refused to consider Turkey for
membership.
	   ``None of us has the intention to insist on a bilateral dispute
or difference as a matter to dominate our consultations. On the
other hand, I believe we all agree that any problem affecting peace
and stability in our region or any issue which deeply affects any
one of us has to be discussed,'' said Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Turkey-Balkan-Summit; CT:i; 
