w1338 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-ChechnyaHostag     10-12 0303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Chechnya Hostages </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chechen official: No trace found of British, New Zealand hostages
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Chechnya's security service is conducting a
round-the-clock search for three Britons and a New Zealander
kidnapped in the breakaway republic, but no trace of the hostages
has been found, the service's chief said Monday.
	   No ransom demands have been made for the four hostages,
Chechnya's acting Security Minister Aslambek Arsayev said.
	   Arsayev said that investigators believe the four may be held by
the same gang that kidnapped another high-profile hostage, Russian
presidential envoy Valentin Vlasov, the ITAR-Tass news agency
reported.
	   Vlasov, kidnapped on May 1, remains missing.
	   Chechnya's security forces launched a 10-day crackdown last
week, seeking to capture rebel armed groups and possibly find leads
to the hostages. A particularly thorough search is being conducted
in Chechnya's mountainous regions, where hostages are usually held,
Arsayev said.
	   Several suspects in other cases have been detained during the
operation, and dozens of firearms and more than 18 kilograms (about
40 pounds) of marijuana have been seized, he said. However, no
leads to the hostages have been found, Arsayev said.
	   The hostages _ Britons Peter Kennedy, Darren Hickey, and Rudolf
Petschi, and New Zealand's Stanley Shaw _ were kidnapped on Oct. 3.
They were working for Granger Telecom, a British telephone company,
installing 300,000 telephone lines across Chechnya.
	   Arsayev said previously that investigators believe the Britons
and the New Zealander are being moved from place to place by their
captors.
	   Hostage-takings, usually for ransom, have become common in
Chechnya since the end of its two-year war for independence from
Russia in 1996.
	   (ad/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
