w1339 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Netherlands-MondrianF 1stLd-Writethru   10-12 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Netherlands-Mondrian Flap, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ministers chastized for purchase of dlrs 40 million painting
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with angry reaction from political
opposition. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo AMS101 &QL; 
 &UR; By WILLIAM J. KOLE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) _ Prime Minister Wim Kok, his
finance minister and the Dutch central bank chief were rebuked
Monday for buying a dlrs 40 million abstract painting with
taxpayers' money and donating it to a museum.
	   In a draft report, the national Court of Audit _ an independent
body that investigates government spending _ said the three
overstepped their bounds with the purchase of Piet Mondrian's
``Victory Boogie Woogie.''
	   Some art experts praise the painting as the pinnacle of the
Dutch master's career. But in a brief statement Monday, the Court
of Audit said it wasn't impressed that the government saw fit to
acquire it with public funds.
	   It did not give details of the draft report, which was to be
released Tuesday and presented to parliament for debate later this
week.
	   The high-profile purchase jolted the usually tranquil Dutch art
world and drew the ire of ordinary citizens when it was revealed
early last month that the private National Art Collection Funds
purchased the work with part of a donation of 110 million guilders
(dlrs 55 million) from the 1998 profits of the Central Bank.
	   At 80 million guilders (dlrs 40 million), the most expensive art
purchase ever funded by the Dutch state quickly aroused the
curiosity of the Court of Audit, which launched a preliminary
investigation.
	   Auditors since have concluded that the Central Bank may only
turn over excess cash to the state, and not directly to private
institutions, Dutch media reported Monday.
	   Kok, Finance Minister Gerrit Zalm and Dutch Central Bank
president Nout Wellink were singled out as responsible for what the
auditors characterized as an unauthorized and inappropriate
purchase.
	   Kok's office and the Finance Ministry were preparing official
responses to the report Monday and had no immediate reaction. The
Netherlands' political opposition, meanwhile, responded with anger.
	   ``As far as I'm concerned, parliament has to say that this must
never happen again,'' Kees Vendrik, a noted economist and member of
the environmentalist Green Left party, told the daily Het Parool.
	   Vendrik said the affair was ``extra spicey'' because the
purchase was authorized in August, while Kok was still forming a
new Cabinet, by a government that was technically in limbo after
spring elections.
	   In addition to their indignation over how it was bought, many
Dutchmen believe the 127-by-127-centimeter (51-by-51-inch)
unfinished painting simply wasn't worth the price tag.
	   The art fund that bought it calls it one of the most important
artworks of the 20th century, a rare expression of carefree joy to
emerge from the gloom of World War II.
	   The diamond-shaped collage of small squares in bold blues, reds
and yellows, was done in oil and black crayon with pieces of paper
and plastic. The Dutch master created it in New York between 1942
and his death in 1944.
	   ``Victory Boogie Woogie,'' which belonged to American magazine
publishing magnate S.I. Newhouse Jr. and had hung in a New York
apartment, has been added to the permanent collection of The Hague
Municipal Museum, already home to the largest Mondrian collection
in the world. It goes on display there Oct. 29.
	   (bk)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Netherlands-Mondrian Flap, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
