<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Scotland-Leighton Retires </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Veteran goalkeeper resigns after Scotland win
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) _ Veteran Scotland goalkeeper Jim
Leighton retired from international soccer Monday, two days after
Scotland's come-from-behind 3-2 Euro 2000 win over Estonia.
	   Leighton, who turned 40 days after Scotland's France '98 World
Cup campaign ended with a 3-0 loss to Morocco, is the most capped
Scotland goalkeeper with 91 international matches to his credit.
	   Scotland manager Craig Brown announced Leighton's retirement at
a press conference Monday.
	   Leighton was involved in a series of mix-ups with veteran
defender Colin Hendry which led to Estonia's shock first goal at
Tyneside on Saturday.
	   The Aberdeen veteran, who reportedly wears glasses and false
teeth off the field, gave no reason for his decision to retire.
	   Leighton became the first Scot to appear in four World Cup
finals campaigns when he was selected for France '98. He played in
all Scotland's first-round World Cup matches, including a 2-1 loss
to 1994 champions Brazil, a loss to Morocco and a 1-1 tie with
Norway.
	   Leighton made his Scottish league debut with Aberdeen in 1978.
He moved into the Premier League with Manchester United from 1988
to 1991 and had stints with Arsenal, Dundee and Sheffield United
before returning to Scotland to play with Hibernian. He is now back
playing for Aberdeen.
	   (jp)
</TEXT>
