<SLUG> BC-Bulgaria-Mrs Clinton, 1st Ld-Writethru,0461 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. first lady encourages businesswomen in Bulgaria
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: SUBS 8th graf to CORRECT year college was shut down to 1942
sted 1948; ADDS more on Prague stop, schedule for Tuesday; TRIMS.
No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; By VESELIN ZHELEV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) _ Hillary Rodham Clinton praised Bulgarians
on Monday for their reform efforts and encouraged women who are
trying to help create a new business culture in this former
communist country.
	   Mrs. Clinton met with businesswomen at a Sofia bakery and
discussed the challenges of running a business in Bulgaria before
leaving for the Czech Republic on the second day of a four-day trip
to promote women's rights in Eastern Europe.
	   ``We're very impressed by the reform effort and the difficult
decisions that your government is making on behalf of the future,''
the U.S. first lady told the women.
	   Mrs. Clinton also accepted an offer to let her book ``It Takes a
Village'' be translated and published into Bulgarian.
	   After talking Monday with students at the American College of
Sofia, the first lady flew later to Prague to meet with Czech
leaders and speak at a conference organized by President Vaclav
Havel and Nobel laureate Elie Wiesel.
	   Mrs. Clinton met with some 500 students at the American College
of Sofia, where she also toured the school, talked to teachers and
alumni and looked at their computer laboratory.
	   ``I saw the future of Bulgaria in the eyes of the brilliant and
dynamic students I met at the American College of Sofia,'' she
said.
	   The college, established in 1860 while Bulgaria was still under
Turkish rule, was closed down in 1942 and turned into a police
training academy after the communists came to power. College alumni
were persecuted, but the school's book collection was preserved at
the local monastery and the college was resurrected in 1992.
	   Mrs. Clinton presented the college with 100 volumes of the
Library of America, containing the best works of famous American
writers, historians, philosophers and statesmen.
	   The students presented her with a book entitled ``Heroines of
History'' that contains a chapter about her.
	   In Prague, she met separately with Prime Minister Milos Zeman
and President Havel's wife, Dagmar, then was scheduled to meet the
Havels together, go to church and attend a gala dinner.
	   On Tuesday, she was scheduled to deliver a keynote speech at the
Forum 2000 conference before returning to Washington the same day.
	   The prestigious gathering of over 50 thinkers and political and
religious activists includes former U.S. Secretary of State Henry
Kissinger, former Polish Premier Hana Suchocka and the chief rabbi
of Israel, Meir Lau.
</TEXT>
