Explosion at shipyard injures three
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Three workers were injured Monday in a gas
explosion at a Russian shipyard and officials believe there could
be more victims buried under the debris.
	   The blast at the Admiralty Shipyard in St. Petersburg also
sparked a blaze that took more than two hours to extinguish. Rescue
teams are still searching for victims, the ITAR-Tass news agency
reported, quoting local emergency officials.
	   Meanwhile, city prosecutors on Monday were carrying out a probe
into another explosion that occurred in St.Petersburg over the
weekend.
	   Dmitry Filippov, the head of the financial company Rosko, was
badly wounded by a bomb explosion at the entrance of his apartment
building on Saturday. He is in critical condition in a city
hospital.
	   His predecessor in the job was shot and killed two years ago.
	   Contract shootings and bombings have become customary in Russia
as mobsters wage turf battles and fight for control over profitable
businesses.
