<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-Foreign Investment </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Poland expecting record foreign investment level in 1998
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Direct foreign investment in Poland since
the end of communist rule is expected to reach the dlrs 30 billion
mark by the end of the year, a government official said Monday.
	   According to Wojciech Dziemanowicz of the Polish Foreign
Investment Agency, corporate investors brought about dlrs 6 billion
in the first nine months of 1998. An additional dlrs 3.4 billion
was expected by the end of the year, he said, which would make 1998
a record year for foreign investment.
	   While Dziemanowicz noted the pace of direct investment slowed in
recent months compared to earlier in the year, he said the pace was
unrelated to the Russian economic crisis that caused market
volatility in the region.
	   ``Interest among investors remains strong,'' he said.
	   Corporate investors distinguish Poland from Russia, unlike
portfolio investors who fled Polish holdings when the Russian
crisis began, said agency vice president Barbara Jarzembowska. She
said corporate investors view Poland as stable in political and
economic terms.
	   Last year, Poland received dlrs 6.6 billion in direct foreign
investment, which was the most for a single year among former
Soviet satellite countries in central and eastern Europe.
	   In a survey of 110 foreign investors conducted in June, foreign
companies gave Poland high marks for rapid economic growth, a
skilled and relatively inexpensive labor force, and good relations
between investors and local authorities, agency officials said.
	   They gave poor marks for the high level of payroll tax, the
state of roads and railways, and the customs service, according to
the survey.
	   (ajs-tsc)
</TEXT>
