<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Finland </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU sues Finland for ignoring 1995 habitats law
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) - The European Commission said Monday it
will take Finland to court for failing to apply 1995 European
legislation on habitats for endangered animals and plants in its
province of Aland.
	   The Commission, the European Union's executive body, said
Finland is over three years late in implementing the EU law on
habitats in Aland, an island in the Baltic Sea between Finland and
Sweden.
	   Finland should have adopted the proper legislation when it
joined the EU on January 1, 1995, the Commission said.
	   ``With the exception of some hunting legislation, Finland has
not formally communicated any implementing legislation for (Aland),
which has legislative autonomy,'' the Commission noted.
	   The Swedish-speaking island of Aland belongs to an archipelago
of about 7,000 islands in the Baltic Sea. The group of islands is
part of Finland.
	    &UR; (as)
</TEXT>
