<SLUG> BC-Middle East Business Briefs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Egypt, Iraq.
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Jordan, Lebanon, Emirates, Saudi Arabia,

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Some 25 foreign firms are vying in Baghdad
for deals to sell agricultural machinery and implements to Iraq
under its oil deal with the United Nations.
	   The firms, exhibiting combine harvesters, tractors, sprayers,
seeders, planters, diggers and fertilizers, are hoping to win some
of the dlrs 250 million Iraq has earmarked to rehabilitate its
agriculture under the current phase of the oil program.
	   Waleed Abdulhadi of Iraq's Trade Fairs Directorate told The
Associated Press that ``ambitious deals'' were being struck during
the week-long exhibition, which started Thursday.
	   Finland's Valtra Valmet won a contract to sell 150 of its
combine harvesters to Iraq. Germany's Claas will sell 40 others.
	   Organizers said the current deals were exploratory and the firms
taking part will be given preferential treatment.
	   Four Italian firms were present. Their offer was a deal for the
export of 30,000 seeders and 100 tractors to Iraq.
	   Iraq sells the machines at a subsidized price to its farmers.
	   ___
	   RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) _ The Saudi French Bank, partly owned
by the Paris-based Banque Indosuez, made a profit of 364.2 million
riyals (dlrs 97 million) for the first nine months of this year,
the bank said in a statement Monday.
	   The profit was a 12 percent increase over profits of 324.9
million (dlrs 86.6 million) over the same period last year.
	   The statement said the increased profits were due to growth in
deposits and loans and the good performance of investments in Saudi
Arabia, the United States and Europe.
	   The Saudi French Bank, in which Banque Indosuez owns a 30
percent stake, is a leading commercial bank in Saudi Arabia. It is
listed on the local stock market.
	   ___
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Jordan and Egypt will discuss the
feasibility of supplying the kingdom and the Palestinian
territories with natural gas through a pipeline, a senior Jordanian
Energy Ministry official said Monday.
	   Talks on the estimated dlrs 500 million pipeline and the gas
supply is expected to be discussed by Energy Minister Hani Mulqi
and his Egyptian counterpart during annual Jordanian-Egyptian
cooperation talks scheduled for next week in Amman.
	   The official said a foreign feasibility study presented to both
governments this year has said the plan is workable.
	   Details of the project have yet to be finalized.
	   Jordan produces natural gas from a al-Risheh field on the
eastern border with Iraq. But the gas generated covers only 30
percent of the country's needs.
	   ___
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ The United States agreed Monday to give
Lebanon dlrs 130,000 to help finance a feasibility study for a
national center for a geographic information system.
	   The agreement was signed by Nabil al-Jisr, chairman of Lebanon's
state-run Council for Development and Reconstruction, and J. Joseph
Grandmaison, director of the U.S. Trade and Development Agency, a
council statement said.
	   The council is a government agency that coordinates
reconstruction projects in Lebanon, which is rebuilding from the
devastating 1975-90 civil war.
	   To be completed within 10 months, the study will cost about dlrs
260,000, the statement said.
	   Half of the cost will be covered by the USTDA's gift and the
other half by a U.S. consulting agency, Geographic Planning
Collaborative, and the CDR, it added.
	   ___
	   DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) _ The Emirates telecom giant
Etisalat will increase its GSM capacity to 1 million subscribers by
mid-1999 and to 1.6 million by 2000, the company's chief executive
said in remarks published Monday.
	   Etisalat has 437,000 GSM subscribers and a capacity for a total
of 800,000, Ali al-Owais told the monthly Update magazine.
	   The GSM, or Global System for Mobile Communications, is the most
widely used mobile phone system around the world. It was introduced
in the Emirates in September 1994.
	   Al-Owais also said that the number of internet subscribers in
the country stands at 48,000, up from 218 in August 1995.
	   The present capacity is for 100,000 dial-up users and expansion
is under way for a capacity of 200,000 by 1999, he said.
	   Etisalat is the sole provider of mobile phone and internet
services in the Emirates.
	   The company is 60 percent owned by the government and 40 percent
by private investors.
	   ___
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Lebanon exported 255.7 billion Lebanese
pounds (dlrs 170.4 million) in industrial goods in the first nine
months of the year, a 9.2 percent drop from the same period last
year, published reports said Monday.
	   No reason was mentioned for the drop that came despite a 100
percent jump in capital investment in the same sector, statistics
published by the Beirut daily newspaper An-Nahar showed.
	   The main exports were chemical products, ready-made garments and
paper products.
	   Saudi Arabia was the major importer of Lebanese industrial
goods. It bought dlrs 36.8 million _ or 21.6 percent of the
exports, followed by France at dlrs 24.1 million, or 14.1 percent,
and Syria at dlrs 17.4 million, or 12 percent.
	   ___
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ India is to supply Iraq with agricultural
machinery and improve the country's power plants, the Nabdh
al-Shabab weekly reported Monday.
	   The agreement was signed in Baghdad during a visit by
Agriculture Minister Som Pal, the weekly said. It did not specify a
date nor did it say when India will begin exporting the equipment
to Iraq which is under an eight-year U.N. sanctions.
	   The weekly said the two countries also agreed to exchange
scientific experts in the fields of research and studies.
	   ``Indian engineering groups will conduct agricultural studies in
order to be involved in further cooperation in the fields of
advanced technology for the agricultural sector,'' the weekly
quoted Pal as saying. It gave no further details.
 &UR; ___
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Some 216.5 billion pounds (dlrs 63.7
billion) were deposited in Egyptian banks in the 1997-98 fiscal
year, an increase of 7.9 percent, the Central Bank said in its
annual report released Monday.
	   Last year's deposits totaled 200.6 billion pounds (dlrs 59
billion).
	   Egypt's fiscal year starts July 1.
	   Some two-thirds of the deposits were at the four
government-owned banks, an increase of 5.4 billion pounds (dlrs 1.6
billion) or 4.3 percent from the previous year.
	   In the previous year, deposits at the four state-owned banks
rose 12.3 percent.
	   Foreign currency deposits in the same banks have risen by 1
percent to dlrs 7.8 billion compared to a drop of 7 percent last
year, the report said.
	   Loans extended by all banks in Egypt totaled 172.4 billion
pounds (dlrs 50.7 billion). The share of the four banks from these
loans was 81 billion pounds (dlrs 23.8 billion) with a growth rate
of 6.4 percent, compared to last year's growth rate of 11.4
percent, the report said.
