<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Rapes, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rights group calls for protection for Indonesian rape counselors
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with suspect saying motive was theft, victim's sister
denying threats in 5th-6th grafs. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ A New York-based human rights group
Monday called on the Indonesian government to protect those trying
to help rape victims following the murder of a counselor.
	   The body of Martadinata Haryono, 17, a counselor with the
Volunteers for Humanity group, was found in her home Friday night,
with stab wounds and a slashed neck.
	   Haryono, a member of the ethnic Chinese minority in Indonesia,
had been helping other ethnic Chinese women who had been raped
during the riots in May.
	   Police have arrested a 20-year-old male neighbor on suspicion of
murder during a bungled burglary.
	   With police permission, the suspect appeared with his lawyers at
a news conference where he denied any political motive behind the
killing. He said that he intended to steal money or jewelry but
that she had caught him red-handed.
	   Haryono's older sister, Evy Suryadinata, told reporters that her
family had not received any threats.
	   Women activists, however, believe the killing is part of a
campaign of intimidation by those responsible for the May rapes.
	   Human Rights Watch, a New York-based group, said the Indonesian
government should provide ``better protection'' for members of
Volunteers for Humanity.
	   It also said the government ``has an obligation to conduct fully
transparent investigations'' into the murder as well as a series of
threats made against other rape counselors and activists.
	   Indonesian media reports have said that activists including
Haryono's mother received threats demanding them to stop counseling
rape victims or investigating their cases.
	   Many ethnic Chinese homes and businesses were targeted by mobs
that killed about 1,200 people during the widespread unrest, which
led to the resignation of authoritarian President Suharto.
	   Human rights groups say at least 168 women, mostly ethnic
Chinese, were raped during the riots.
	   The government has confirmed that rapes occurred, but doesn't
know how many. The military and police have repeatedly said they
have no hard evidence that sexual assault was widespread. 	   
