 &UR; With Yugoslavia-Kosovo
 &UR; By TONY CZUCZKA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Outgoing Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Cabinet
agreed Monday to allow German warplanes to take part in any
airstrikes in Kosovo and backed a NATO order authorizing alliance
military commanders to launch an attack.
	   However, actual deployment must be approved by the sitting
parliament, which won't meet until Friday to approve Germany's role
in NATO action in the Yugoslav province.
	   Germany's role in any airstrikes has been in question since the
left's Sept. 27 election victory. But Kohl and Chancellor-elect
Gerhard Schroeder met Monday and agreed that the old government
should take the initiative, Kohl's chief of staff Friedrich Bohl
said.
	   Parliamentary approval seems assured because both major parties,
the Social Democrats and Kohl's Christian Democrats, largely
support committing German troops.
