<SLUG> BC-Russia-Yeltsin's Health-Box </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With BC-Russia-Yeltsin
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   A look at President Boris Yeltsin's health problems over the
past decade:
	   November 1987 _ Hospitalized for several days with chest pains
after his ouster as Moscow Communist Party boss.
	   September 1991 _ Heart trouble forces Yeltsin to stop work for
two days and later to recuperate for two weeks by the Black Sea.
	   September 1994 _ Yeltsin fails to get off plane during stopover
in Ireland for meeting with Irish prime minister and later says he
overslept.
	   December 1994 _ Retreats to Kremlin hospital for two weeks for
minor nose surgery.
	   July 11, 1995 _ Hospitalized for two weeks with acute heart
trouble, then recuperates for two weeks at a government sanitarium.
	   Oct. 26, 1995 _ Hospitalized for nearly a month with heart
problems, then spends another month recuperating at a government
rest home.
	   June 1996 _ Disappears from public view for final week before
the July 3 election. Aides cite a sore throat, his wife blames a
cold but his doctor later acknowledges it was a heart attack.
	   Nov. 5, 1996 _ Undergoes quintuple heart bypass surgery at the
Moscow Cardiological Center.
	   Jan. 8, 1997 _ Hospitalized for 12-day treatment of what doctors
describe as ``double pneumonia,'' then spends a month recuperating
at his country residence.
	   Dec. 10, 1997 _ Hospitalized at a government rest home for two
weeks for what is described as a respiratory infection.
	   March 13, 1998 _ Suffers from what is described as acute
laryngitis, an inflammation of the larynx and trachea resulting in
a bad cough and hoarse voice. Doctors advise him to stay in bed and
speak as little as possible.
	   Oct. 7, 1998 _ In a magazine interview, Naina Yeltsin says
doctors pronounce her husband's health ``more or less normal.''
	   Oct. 11, 1998 _ Yeltsin cancels a welcoming ceremony in
Tashkent, Uzbekistan, because he's not feeling well.
	   Oct. 12, 1998 _ Cuts short his trip to Kazakstan, heading home a
day ahead of schedule, because of bronchitis.
	   (ji/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
