<HEADLINE>
Swaziland, Malaysia want to up cooperation: Report
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS three final grafs to UPDATE with banquet. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Swaziland and Malaysia have agreed
to increase economic cooperation between the two nations, the
national Bernama news agency reported Monday.
	   The agreement came after King Mswati from the southern African
nation, who arrived here Sunday for a six-day visit, met with
Malaysian Prime Minister Minister Mahathir Mohamad, the report
said.
	   Mahathir and Mswati attended a signing ceremony on agreements on
trade and scientific, technical and cultural cooperation, it said.
	   At a palace banquet in his honor, Mswati said in a speech that
although Malaysia was not spared in the Asian economic downturn, he
was confident it will manage a turnaround.
	   ``We feel that in a matter of time, Malaysia will return to the
pattern of its strong economic growth. These are examples of
confidence, not despair and they point clearly to a future full of
optimism,'' he said.
	   The Malaysian king, Tuanku Ja'afar, said the two nations should
work together to overcome challenges and increase exchanges in
culture and sports.
