<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan-UN,0479 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN envoy agrees to travel to Afghanistan to meet Taliban leader
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By KATHY GANNON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ After receiving a promise from the
Taliban religious army that it will investigate the killing of a
U.N. worker, the U.N. special envoy agreed Monday to travel to the
Taliban headquarters in southern Afghanistan.
	   Envoy Lakhdar Brahimi is in the region to ease tensions between
the Taliban army and neighboring Iran, which has deployed more than
200,000 soldiers, hundreds of tanks and scores of jet fighters on
its border with Afghanistan.
	   The promise to visit the religious militia's Kandahar
headquarters came after a two-hour meeting in Pakistan, said
Saeed-ur Rehman Haqqani, the Taliban ambassador to the neighboring
nation.
	   Haqqani said the Taliban promised Brahimi ``they would carry out
an investigation ... and further details would be given during his
visit to Kandahar.''
	   Iran's troop deployment followed the killings of its diplomats
in the northern Afghan city of Mazar-e-Sharif in August by invading
Taliban soldiers.
	   Tehran is demanding an apology from the Taliban and forces who
killed the diplomats. So far the Taliban has refused both requests.
	   The Taliban has accused Iran of arming and financing the Afghan
opposition, while Pakistan is believed to be supporting the
Taliban.
	   Brahimi's promise to visit Afghanistan on Wednesday is seen as a
major breakthrough for the Taliban who have been pressing the U.N.
envoy to meet them on their home ground.
	   Brahimi initially refused because U.N. headquarters in New York
has forbidden its international staff from traveling to Afghanistan
for security reasons.
	   An Italian U.N. worker was shot to death in Kabul on Aug. 21, in
apparent retaliation for U.S. missiles attacks on suspected
training camps in eastern Afghanistan the day before. The United
Nations has been demanding the assassins be arrested and punished.
	   Brahimi is expected to hold face-to-face talks with the
Taliban's reclusive leader Mullah Mohammed Omar, who in the past
has refused to meet U.N. envoys.
	   The United Nations also is pressing the Taliban for security
guarantees that would let its international staff return to
Afghanistan and restart stalled humanitarian programs. The United
Nations is also demanding the Taliban ensure access to programs for
women and girls and freedom to carry out programs in line with U.N.
policies.
	   In areas it controls, the Taliban has imposed a strict version
of Islamic law, barring women from work outside the home, banning
most art and music and forcing men to grow beards.
	   Haqqani said the Taliban promised Brahimi they would send a
delegation to Pakistan to discuss the resumption of U.N. programs.
	   There was no immediate comment from the United Nations.
</TEXT>
