<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OAU-Refugees </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Refugees burden Africa, official says
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) _ More than 27 million Africans have
been driven from their homes by violence, worsening the continent's
economic problems, an African leader said Monday.
	   ``Today, there is not a country in Africa that has not played
host to refugees,'' said Ahmed Haggag, acting secretary-general of
the Organization of African Unity.
	   ``Many of the host countries have themselves been faced with
major economic problems and are not able to absorb the extra burden
of refugees,'' he said. The development of those countries is
impeded.
	   Haggag spoke at the opening session of a four-day OAU seminar
aimed at alleviating the plight of African refugees, especially
women and children, and to reintegrate them into their societies.
	   ``In any refugee or internally displaced community, women are
the life-sustaining force, they play a central economic and social
role, they have the power to nurture future generations and
reestablish the family and culture in exile or in displacement,''
Haggag said.
	   The number of Africans living in neighboring countries has
soared to 7 million, and is rising, Haggag said.
	   Another 20 million Africans are displaced within the borders of
their own countries, ``deprived of their livelihoods, dignity and
home,'' he said.
	   The seminar was attended by representatives of African
governments, U.N. agencies, donors and aid groups.
	   (aa-kjd)
</TEXT>
