<HEADLINE>
Russian delegation travels to The Hague for chemical weapons talks
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A Russian delegation traveled to The Hague,
Netherlands on Monday for talks on inspections of Russian
facilities producing or storing substances that could be used for
chemical weapons, a news agency said.
	   The Russian delegation was to meet with international
specialists from the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical
Weapons, and will pave the way for a later delegation to sign
agreements on inspecting the Russian chemical sites, the ITAR-Tass
news agency said.
	   Representatives from the Russian ministries of health, defense,
economics and foreign affairs were to attend the meetings, the
ITAR-Tass news agency said.
	   The talks are pursuant to the 1993 Paris Convention on Chemical
Weapons, which calls for Moscow to destroy its huge Soviet-era
arsenal by 2005. Russia's parliament ratified it last year.
	   Russian officials say they are fully complying with the treaty,
but work has been slow and plagued by funding shortages. Many
western lawmakers say Russia cannot afford the huge costs of
dismantling its chemical arsenal.
	   Russian officials say they expect foreign money to cover about
dlrs 1 billion of the estimated dlrs 6 billion cost of destroying
some 40,000 metric tons (44,000 tons) of chemical weapons.
