w1426 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EU-Finance 2ndLd-Writethru   10-12 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Finance, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0658 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU finance ministers look to contain financial turmoil
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with British proposals for overhauling international
finance; fresh quotes from British, German ministers; EDITS to
conform. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos staffing &QL; 
 &UR; By PAUL AMES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LUXEMBOURG (AP) _ European Union finance ministers struggled
Monday to produce a strategy for containing the global market
crisis and prevent further outbreaks of such highly contagious
financial turmoil.
	   Britain's Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown said he was
seeking EU support for strengthening international financial
institutions.
	   ``I am determined that Europe plays its full part in addressing
the weaknesses of the international financial system and
contributing to growth and stability around the world,'' Brown told
reporters as he arrived for the one-day meeting.
	   Outlining what he called a ``three-point action plan,'' Brown
called for a ``crisis prevention mechanism'' to ensure greater
openness in financial market so potential dangers could be detected
early. He also urged reinforcing the International Monetary Fund so
it can quickly to tackle emerging crises and suggested enhanced
supervisory regulation of the global finance system.
	   The EU meeting came as slower growth rates and fears of more
gloom spreading from Asia, Russia and South America take some of
the shine off preparations for the launch of the euro as the common
currency of 11 EU nations on Jan. 1.
	   So far, Europe has avoided the worst of the global crisis,
something German Finance Minister Theo Waigel put down to
confidence in a strong and stable euro and the strict budget
discipline nations must follow to join the euro-bloc.
	   ``In spite of all the problems in the world, the euro-zone is an
island of stability,'' Waigel told reporters. ``This is clear proof
that this process has been the right one.''
	   The EU's Finance Commissioner Yves-Thibault de Silguy predicted
at the start of the meeting ``in 1999 Europe will have the best
growth among the industrial powers.''
	   However, ministers face mounting pressure for action to halt any
further decline in growth, including calls for interest rate cuts
to help business.
	   Last week, the Spanish, Irish, Portuguese and British central
banks eased rates, but EU central bankers and a number of ministers
believe rates are low enough in core European economies such as
Germany and France.
	   ``The problem of bringing down rates is not one for Europe,''
said Irish Finance Minister Charlie McCreevy.
	   The ministers were likely to reject a proposal for the EU to
back loans to Russia by the Union's lending arm, the European
Investment Bank.
	   ``In the present situation in Russia ... it would not be serious
to give the EU budget guarantee to an EIB intervention in Russia,''
De Silguy told reporters.
	   The one-day EU meeting was the last for Waigel. Defeat in last
month's elections means the Bavarian conservative is stepping down
after almost 10 years at the helm of the EU's biggest economy.
	   As a parting shot, Waigel knocked home Germany's tough line over
plans to overhaul the EU's dlrs 100 billion budget from 2000 so the
Union can pay for its planned expansion into eastern Europe.
	   Germany, along with Austria, Sweden and the Netherlands, says it
pays too much into EU coffers and gets too little back in return.
Waigel insist any reform correct the imbalance.
	   ``There is a lack of burden sharing in the budget,'' he told a
news conference. ``This is something that cannot continue.''
	   Italian Treasury Minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi assured other
ministers the Friday's government collapse in Rome would not weaken
Italy's determination to cut debt and budget deficit. ``I have no
reason to believe that Italy won't continue to honor its pledges,''
De Silguy said.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-EU-Finance, 2nd Ld-Writethru; CT:f; 
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:ASIA;)
