<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Salinas </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Swiss to give more information in Salinas case in late October
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BERN, Switzerland (AP) _ Swiss authorities will give more
information later this month on their investigation into the
brother of former Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gortari, an
official said Monday.
	   Swiss Federal Attorney General Carla Del Ponte is currently
deciding whether the evidence collected by the 2 1/2-year Swiss
inquiry is sufficient to prosecute Raul Salinas.
	   More details will be given ``in the second half of October,''
Dominique Reymond, spokesman for the Federal Prosecutor's Office,
said. He didn't elaborate.
	   Reymond declined to comment on a report in The New York Times
Monday that the Swiss report on the case suggests prominent
businessman Carlos Peralta Quintero helped hide protection money
paid to Raul Salinas by drug traffickers.
	   In July, Switzerland's anti-narcotics police chief said he had
wrapped up his investigation into bribery allegations against
Salinas.
	   ``We have a case against Raul Salinas that he got the money from
drug traffickers,'' Valentin Roschacher said then.
	   Folco Galli, spokesman for the Swiss Office of Police Affairs,
also declined to comment on Monday's report. Roschacher, who is
abroad, couldn't be contacted.
	   The Swiss have been investigating whether Raul Salinas helped
launder drug money while his younger brother was president from
1988 to 1994.
	   Authorities seized Swiss bank accounts belonging to Raul Salinas
in 1995.
	   Swiss court documents have said U.S. officials alleged he
deposited dlrs 132 million in drug-trafficking bribes in Swiss
banks.
	   If Del Ponte decides to prosecute, the defense attorneys will
have the right to appeal, which would immediately send the case to
the highest Swiss court, the Federal Tribunal.
	   Raul Salinas is in prison in Mexico pending completion of his
trials in a political assassination and on a charge of illegal
enrichment.
	   He has denied any links to drug traffickers and said the money
in the Swiss accounts was an investment fund pooled by several
wealthy friends.
 &UR; (gm)
