<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Croatia-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Croatia's moderate defense minister quits; likely setback for
</HEADLINE>
reforms &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES and RECASTS with analysis, background, parliament
commission examining allegations against military
counter-intelligence &QL; 
 &UR; By SNJEZANA VUKIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) _ Croatia's moderate defense minister
resigned unexpectedly Monday, signifying that hardliners have
prevailed in a rift in President Franjo Tudjman's ruling party and
within his government.
	   The move by Andrija Hebrang is the second high-level resignation
in four days by a political moderate in the government. Another
close aide to Tudjman, Hrvoje Sarinic, quit Friday as his Cabinet
chief.
	   Both cited Tudjman's failure to support them in their conflicts
with hardliners.
	   Hebrang, considered a devoted Tudjman supporter, also said he
would no longer head the medical team caring for the 76-year-old
president. In addition, he resigned as vice president of Tudjman's
Croatian Democratic Union.
	   A split has existed for years in Tudjman's ruling party between
pro-Western moderates and hard-line nationalists who oppose broader
democratic reforms.
	   Tudjman evidently has now chosen to back the hardliners, who
control the army and much of the police force. Such a choice could
lead to even more rigid rule in a country criticized by the West
for failing to promote democracy.
	   Last month, Sarinic charged in an interview that military
counter-intelligence was behind a media campaign against the more
liberal members of the ruling party. He said their actions were
likely commanded by another Tudjman aide, hardliner Ivic Pasalic.
	   Sarinic's claims highlighted Tudjman's opponents' claims that
his party, or some of its members, use state institutions for
political or personal gains.
	   Hebrang replaced the late Gojko Susak as defense minister in May
and vowed to reorganize the army according to NATO standards.
	   It has long been known that in the process, Hebrang wanted to
dump military counter-intelligence chief Markica Rebic and Vlado
Zagorac, who leads the ministry's firm for arms purchases. Both men
were protegees of Susak, a hard-liner, and they reportedly opposed
Hebrang's planned reforms.
	   In his letter to Tudjman, released by the state-run news agency
HINA, Hebrang said Tudjman's failure to uphold his attempts to
replace the two prompted him to resign.
	   ``Without your support, all my attempts to carry on the complex
programs which are also crucial for our country become futile,''
Hebrang wrote, adding: ``May God help you in recognizing good from
evil.''
	   Meanwhile, Rebic appeared before the parliamentary commission
which is to examine Sarinic's claims that counter-intelligence was
implicated in the media attacks.
	   Sarinic and Pasalic also were summoned for the closed-door
hearings.
	   (sv/dc)
</TEXT>
