<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nobel-Medicine, 10th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Three Americans win Nobel Medicine Prize
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs: Leads throughout to recats, trim, change byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By MATTI HUUHTANEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) _ Nitric oxide doesn't just pollute the
air: it also saves lives and enhances men's sexual performance.
Unlocking its secrets won three American researchers the Nobel
Medicine Prize on Monday.
	   The 7.6-million-kronor (dlrs 978,000) award is divided equally
between Robert F. Furchgott, Louis J. Ignarro and Ferid Murad, who
discovered new properties of the gas, which helped in developing
the anti-impotence drug Viagra.
	   In 1977, while at the University of Virginia, Murad was
researching how nitroglycerin _ often given to heart patients to
dilate blood vessels _ releases nitric oxide. In 1980, Furchgott
concluded that blood vessels dilate because cells in their inner
lining produce a signal molecule. Ignarro, working on his own and
with Furchgott, proved this molecule was nitric oxide.
	   The conclusions of Furchgott and Ingarro, published in 1986,
opened up a new field of medical research based on the properties
of nitric oxide, and led to studies on a wide range of new drugs.
	   ``It was a sensation that this simple common air pollutant ...
could exert important functions'' in animals and people, said the
Karolinska Institute, which awards the prize.
	   Furchgott, 82, is a pharmacologist at the State University of
New York in Brooklyn. Ignarro, 57, is at University of
California-Los Angeles and Murad, 62, now is at the University of
Texas Medical School in Houston.
	   Furchgott, reached at his Long Island home, said ``I'm very
pleased. I truly wasn't sure I'd ever get an award like this. I
wasn't sure that I deserved it.''
	   Nitric oxide, which can ease chest pains, has been used to find
stronger and more selective drugs to treat cardiovascular
conditions.
	   Scientists are now testing to see whether the colorless gas can
be used to stop the advance of cancer because of its ability to
defend against tumors and kill infectious bacteria, fungi and
parasites.
	   Patients in intensive care often are made to inhale the gas,
which has provided ``good results and even saved lives,'' the
Karolinska Institute said.
	   It is also being used to fight bacterial infections, as well as
diagnoze lung conditions, including asthma.
	   Nitric oxide can trigger erection of the penis by dilating blood
vessels. The wildly popular Viagra is based on this effect.
	   ``This is a new general principle ... which will help us to
develop lots of new medicines, for example ones that directly relax
or retain tension in muscles, as in the new impotence drug,
Viagra,'' said Hans Joernvall, professor of medical chemistry at
the Karolinska Institute.
	   The studies on nitric oxide touch on the personal life of Alfred
Nobel, the Swedish industrialist and inventor of dynamite who
established the prizes in his will.
	   In later life, Nobel's physician told him to take nitroglycerin
_ one of the ingredients in dynamite _ to combat heart trouble. But
it took 100 years before science clarified that nitroglycerin acts
by releasing nitric oxide gas, the Karolinska Institute said.
	   ``This year's Nobel prize goes to the body's own
nitroglycerin,'' said Goeran Hansson, professor of experimental
cardiovascular research at Karolinska Institute.
	   The announcement is ``great news,'' said Dr. Gerald Levey, dean
of the UCLA School of Medicine. ``We were hoping he (Ignarro) would
win it. We thought he had a strong chance to win. It's well
deserved.''
	   The medicine prize was the second of the six Nobels to be
announced this year. Last week, the literature prize went to
Portuguese novelist Jose Saramago.
	   The physics and chemistry prizes will be announced Tuesday, the
economics prize on Wednesday and the peace prize on Friday. All the
announcements are in Stockholm, except for the peace prize which is
given in Oslo, Norway.
	   The prizes are presented on Dec. 10, the anniversary of Nobel's
death.
	   (mhh-mt-jh) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Nobel-Medicine, 10th Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
