<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Zimbabwe-Corruption </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Magazine had the right to report on corruption by army leader,
</HEADLINE>
court rules.
 &UR; By ANGUS SHAW &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ The nation's highest court threw out a
damage claim by the former guerrilla leader and retired army
commander against a magazine that accused him of corruption.
	   The monthly Horizon magazine made fair comment that was in the
public interest when it reported on the business activities of Gen.
Solomon Mujuru in late 1991, Judge Nick McNally ruled.
	   Mujuru, who at an earlier hearing threatened to shoot dead the
magazine's editor, had sued for a record 250,000 Zimbabwe dollars
(then worth dlrs 30,000) in damages.
	   The Supreme Court, after an appeal by Horizon, said Monday there
was no merit in Mujuru being awarded 40,000 Zimbabwe dollars (dlrs
5,000) in damages by the high court in 1996 and granted the appeal,
with Mujuru paying all costs.
	   President Robert Mugabe has been accused of failing to curb
corruption in his government, though such allegations are rarely
reported in the dominant state-controlled media.
	   McNally said Mujuru acquired business interests in ways that
``could reasonably be regarded as morally questionable or
improper'' after independence in 1980.
	   The magazine argued Mujuru bought farms, a store chain and a
hotel despite rules prohibiting public officials and political
leaders from becoming rich.
	   The magazine had also questioned how Mujuru financed the
purchase of properties and businesses worth millions of dollars
while he was head of the Zimbabwe army.
	   McNally said Mujuru admitted he breached the rules limiting
public officials to owning two modest homes and prohibiting them
from running businesses when in office.
	   Horizon editor Andrew Moyse described the ruling as a victory
for press freedom in a nation where the state controls all
broadcasting and five main newspapers and frequently harasses
independent journalists.
	   ``We believed in what we had to say. We have been totally
vindicated. I hope this will keep the door open for freedom of
expression in the scary and threatening environment we work in,''
Moyse said.
	   Mujuru led the Marxist guerrilla army that helped end white rule
in the former British colony of Rhodesia. He retired as army
commander in 1992 after leading the force of mainly ex-guerrillas
for 12 years.
	   Mujuru remains a ruling party legislator and a member of its
politburo, the party's top policy-making body.
	   (as/djw)	   
</TEXT>
