<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Netherlands-Indonesian Activist </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Exiled Indonesian activist calls for pro-democracy support
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Single name Mugiyanto is cq. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo AMS102 &QL; 
 &UR; By KATHRYN MASTERSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) _ An exiled student activist who
says he was kidnapped and tortured by the Indonesian military
appealed to the international community Monday to support the
democratic movement in his troubled homeland.
	   Mugiyanto, the international officer for the People's Democratic
Party (PRD), called on other countries to pressure the new
Indonesian government to sever its military ties and to release
protesters held illegally.
	   ``The struggle for democracy in Indonesia needs support from
people abroad,'' Mugiyanto said. ``It is not only a struggle for
Indonesian people.''
	   Mugiyanto is traveling throughout Europe asking for financial
and political support for the pro-democracy movement. His stay in
the Netherlands, which has a large Indonesian community and
longtime ties to its former colony, was coordinated by the Dutch
group Supporting Movement for Democratization in Indonesia.
	   Mugiyanto is the second prominent Indonesian dissident to take
his case to Europe. Earlier this year, well-known student activist
Pius Lustrilanang _ also based in the Netherlands _ launched a
similar awareness campaign.
	   Mugiyanto's appeal for aid comes as new elections approach in
Indonesia. Parliamentary elections have been promised for next
year, and a presidential election is scheduled for December 1999.
	   Widespread rioting triggered by the economic crisis and
oppression under military rule prompted former President Suharto to
resign in May.
	   Without international intervention, Mugiyanto sees the upcoming
elections as having the dangerous potential for another massive
uprising.
	   ``If this force is not led, there will be anarchy,'' he said.
``This will not bring a solution to Indonesia.''
	   An Indonesian court lifted a ban against the PRD in August, but
many of the party's leaders have been imprisoned for subversion.
	   The PRD believes its challenge is to cobble together the various
and unorganized protest groups into a unified movement for
democracy, Mugiyanto said.
	   Mugiyanto said he was abducted from his home March 13 by the
military and tortured for two days. He was blindfolded and tied to
a bed wearing only his underpants, he said. While he was
interrogated, he was beaten and electrically shocked.
	   He was held in prison until June 5, when B.J. Habibie replaced
Suharto as president.
	   His captors warned him not to speak of his abduction, he said.
Though he may be in danger when he returns, he is speaking out
about the human rights violations he says are still occurring under
the new leadership.
	   Fourteen activists still remain missing, he said.
	   ``It is not because I am brave but because this is the only
choice I have,'' he said of his campaign. ``I have friends who are
missing. We must make sure this does not happen again.''
	   (km/bk)
</TEXT>
