<SLUG> BC-Croatia-Dubrovnik </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tudjman's party loses majority in Dubrovnik local elections
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DUBROVNIK, Croatia (AP) _ A united opposition beat out President
Franjo Tudjman's ruling party in local voting, unofficial results
showed Monday. The result signaled trouble ahead for the government
for next year's scheduled parliamentary elections.
	   Although Tudjman's Croatian Democratic Union won 13 seats in
Dubrovnik County elections, for the best showing of any individual
party, the opposition alliance together took the remaining 27
seats.
	   The town of Dubrovnik, a famed tourist attraction, is already
run by the opposition.
	   Final unofficial results showed the Social Democrats and the
Peasants' party with 10 seats each and their junior coalition
partners, the Social Liberals and Liberal Party, with a total of
five seats. The Independent List won two seats.
	   Despite his most recent loss, Tudjman's party still holds a
majority in 18 of 21 counties.
	   But the party's once unchallenged popularity is steadily fading,
amid growing suspicions of financial and political corruption. The
loss of the potentially highly prosperous tourist and agricultural
region of Dubrovnik was particularly galling.
	   (str/sv/gj)
</TEXT>
