<SLUG> BC-Norway-Plane Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Charter airplane crashes in Norway; nine Danes killed
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with nine confirmed dead and all victims being Danes. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   OSLO, Norway (AP) - A small charter airplane crashed short of a
runway in western Norway Monday, killing all nine of the Danish
citizens on board, police said.
	   The aircraft, a twin-engine Cessna 402 propeller plane, was on
its way from Aalborg, Denmark to Stord, Norway, when it crashed and
caught fire at about 12:30 a.m. (2230 GMT Sunday), some 200 meters
(yards) short of the runway. The cause of the crash was not known.
	   ``Everything seemed normal, and we had visual contact with the
plane,'' said Jan Morten Myklebust, head of the Stord local
airport. ``It was dark and raining, but there as a high cloud
ceiling and little wind. The plane just suddenly went down.''
	   Rescuers immediately found the bodies of eight victims, but it
took until mid-afternoon to find the ninth victim in the charred
wreckage.
	   Stord Sheriff Reidar Faerestrand said it took several hours to
determine how many people had been aboard.
	   ``Now we can confirm that we have found nine dead,'' he said.
	   The plane had been chartered to fly Danish employees of the
Alteck Isolering company to the Aker Stord shipyard, about 500
kilometers (300 miles) west of Oslo, after a weekend off. The
identities of the victims were not immediately released.
	   Danish police claimed the pilot had been facing charges for
flying paying passengers without commercial certification, Danish
and Norwegian news reports said. However, Palle Jensen of Altek
Isolering told the Norwegian news agency NTB that the pilot's
papers were in order at the time of the crash.
	   (dm-jh)
</TEXT>
