w1468 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslav-Forces     10-12 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslav-Forces,0494 </SLUG>

 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   In launching an air attack on Yugoslavia, NATO could face an
armed force that is still the largest in the region despite the
crippling effects of years of embargo.
	   NATO planners are aware that their technological superiority
does not mean a risk-free operation to force President Slobodan
Milosevic to curb attacks by Serb security forces against ethnic
Albanians in Yugoslavia's Kosovo province.
	   ``The Yugoslavs have formidable air defenses and are not going
to be a pushover,'' said Dana Alenn of the International Institute
for Strategic Studies in London.
	   Serb forces have a history of fierce resistance to outside
attack. In response to NATO strikes in 1995, Bosnian Serbs shot
down one French Mirage 2000 with a single SA-7 missile and an
American F-16 with a direct hit by SA-6.
	   The first target for NATO, the analysts said, likely would be
Yugoslav surface-to-air systems, which could challenge NATO
warplanes, but would pose less of an obstacle to Tomahawk cruise
missiles.
	   Years after the disintegration of former socialist Yugoslavia,
Serbia and Montenegro still have a sizable air force, consisting of
260 aircraft, divided into five fixed-wing brigades and three
helicopter regiments.
	   The fixed wing element include 16 MiG-29 fighters, of which two
are MiG-29 UTI training two-seaters unsuitable for combat. These
planes, purchased from the former Soviet Union in the early 1980s,
are based at Batajnica Airfield near Belgrade.
	   The Yugoslav versions of the MiG-29 carries aging electronics
and radar, but their superb maneuverability and APHID and ACRID
air-to-air missiles could threaten incoming aircraft.
	   In addition, there are about 60 aging MiG-21 FT and BIS
interceptors that also can be thrown into the fray. This model
dates from the Vietnam and the Mideastern conflicts, and likely
would not mount serious opposition to NATO warplanes.
	   The Yugoslav air force also has about 65 close-support ORAO and
80 GALEB G4 and G2 aircraft, and other utility planes of various
kinds.
	   Perhaps the most serious threat to NATO warplanes would comes
from 60 self-propelled surface-to-air SA-12b missile systems, along
with SA-6 missiles upgraded with new warheads, seeking devices and
proximity fuses.
	   At airfields and other strategic points, Yugoslav air defense
deploys large numbers of SA-2, 3, 9, 10, 11 and 13 missile systems.
They also field man-portable, shoulder launched SA-7, 14 and 16
missiles.
	   It is still uncertain whether Yugoslav armed forces have been
able to purchase the Russian S-300 anti-aircraft, anti-missile
system, Moscow's answer to the American Patriot missile system.
	   Some analysts claim Belgrade tried to buy this equipment, but
failed because of its chronic lack of hard currency. If the
Yugoslavs have purchased S-300s, there are no more than two or
three units, which likely would be positioned to defend the
capital. 	   
</TEXT>
