<SLUG> BC-NATO-Kosovo, 2nd Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO ready to approve order to bring air strikes closer
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Council starting meeting. Holbrooke debriefing
Solana over phone &QL; 
 &UR; With Yugoslavia-Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo BRU101 &QL; 
 &UR; By RAF CASERT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ NATO nations began assessing a report
from special U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke on Monday's Kosovo talks
in Belgrade before deciding whether to take the last military step
needed to launch airstrikes against the Serbs.
	   NATO Secretary General Javier Solana talked ``at length'' over
the phone with Holbrooke to be briefed on his latest attempts to
persuade Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to abide by U.N.
Security Council demands in Kosovo, a NATO official, who demanded
anonymity, said.
	   No details of the discussions were available.
	   If the Holbrooke talks fail, NATO is expected to approve an
activation order later on Monday, a vital step before airstrikes
can be launched.
	   A NATO, 4th graf
</TEXT>
