<SLUG> BC-EU-Finance, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU finance ministers look to contain financial turmoil
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with meeting over; no agreement on details of measures
for countering market turmoil; fresh quotes from meeting chairman;
EDITS to conform; no pick up &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos Covering
 &UR; By PAUL AMES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LUXEMBOURG (AP) _ European Union finance ministers were unable
Monday to agree details of a common strategy for containing the
global market crisis and preventing further outbreaks of such
highly-contagious financial turmoil.
	   ``It's clear we need a form of crisis management. These
questions need to be solved urgently,'' said Austrian Finance
Minister Rudolf Edlinger, who chaired the day-long EU meeting.
	   There was broad backing for British and French proposals to
strengthen international financial institutions, but Edlinger
acknowledged ``we have not yet come up with a clear position.''
	   Outlining what he called a ``three-point action plan,'' British
Chancellor of the Exchequer called for a ``crisis prevention
mechanism'' to ensure greater openness in financial market so
potential dangers could be detected early.
	   He also urged reinforcing the International Monetary Fund so it
can quickly to tackle emerging crises and suggested enhanced
supervisory regulation of the global finance system.
	   ``I am determined that Europe plays its full part in addressing
the weaknesses of the international financial system and
contributing to growth and stability around the world,'' Brown told
reporters.
	   Although slower growth rates and fears of more gloom spreading
from Asia, Russia and South America are taking some of the shine
off preparations for the launch of the euro as the common currency
of 11 EU nations on Jan. 1, ministers insisted Europe would
continue to escape the worst of the global crisis.
	   ``In 1999 Europe will have the best growth among the industrial
powers,'' the EU's Finance Commissioner Yves-Thibault de Silguy
predicted.
	   German Finance Minister Theo Waigel said Europe was sheltered by
confidence that the euro will be a strong and stable currency.
	   ``In spite of all the problems in the world, the euro-zone is an
island of stability,'' Waigel told reporters. ``This is clear proof
that this process has been the right one.''
	   However, the ministers face mounting pressure for action to halt
any further decline in growth, including calls for interest rate
cuts to help business. But EU central bankers and a number of
ministers believe rates are low enough in core European economies
such as Germany and France.
	   ``The problem of bringing down rates is not one for Europe,''
said Irish Finance Minister Charlie McCreevy.
	   The ministers rejected an Austrian proposal for the EU to back
loans to Russia by the Union's lending arm, the European Investment
Bank. ``The overall conditions for such a commitment are still not
met,'' Edlinger acknowledged.
	   The one-day EU meeting was the last for Waigel. Defeat in last
month's elections means the Bavarian conservative is stepping down
after almost 10 years at the helm of the EU's biggest economy.
	   As a parting shot, Waigel knocked home Germany's tough line over
plans to overhaul the EU's dlrs 100 billion budget so the Union can
pay for it's planned expansion into eastern Europe.
	   Germany, along with Austria, Sweden and the Netherlands, says it
pays too much into EU coffers and gets too little back in return.
Waigel insist any reform correct the imbalance.
	   ``There is a lack of burden sharing in the budget,'' he told a
news conference. ``This is something that cannot continue.''
	   Italian Treasury Minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi assured other
ministers the Friday's government collapse in Rome would not weaken
Italy's determination to cut debt and budget deficit. ``I have no
reason to believe that Italy won't continue to honor its pledges,''
De Silguy said.
 &UR; (pa)
</TEXT>
