<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Austria-Presidents </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Central European presidents call for end to fighting in Kosovo
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   VIENNA, Austria (AP) _ The presidents of six Central European
nations appealed Monday for Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
to meet the demands of the Contact Group and end the fighting in
the troubled province of Kosovo.
	   ``General historic experience, and the history of Central
European nations, shows that there is less suffering and fewer
human lives sacrificed the sooner we combat evil,'' the presidents
of Austria, Germany, Poland, Hungary, Slovenia and the Czech
Republic said in a statement.
	   The leaders called on Milosevic to fullfill the conditions set
out by the six-nation Contact Group in an attempt to end the
violence in Kosovo, which has left hundreds dead and an estimated
275,000 homeless.
	   Czech President Vaclav Havel criticized the international
community for ``notoriously repeating the mistakes of the past'' by
failing to prevent conflicts and only responding after the fact.
	   He called for representatives from Yugoslavia and Kosovo _ which
is dominated by ethnic Albanians _ as well as Albania, Macedonia,
the European Union and NATO, to sit down together at the
negotiating table.
	   But he didn't rule out the possibility of NATO airstrikes
against Yugoslavia.
	   Havel and the other heads of state gathered in Vienna for a
one-day summit to discuss issues affecting the region.
	   One of the key issues for Central Europe is EU expansion.
	   ``Austria would like to make expansion a priority of its
presidency,'' said Austrian President Thomas Klestil, whose country
currently holds the rotating EU presidency.
	   Germany will take over the presidency Jan. 1, and the other four
summit participants are front-runners to join the EU early next
century.
	   (scl)
</TEXT>
