<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Antelope Killed,0405 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indian super star charged with killing endangered antelope
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo BOM103 &QL; 
 &UR; By NEELESH MISRA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ One of India's most popular movie stars
was arrested Monday on charges of hunting three rare antelope
during a break from filming in a wildlife preserve.
	   Police investigators arrested Salman Khan, who allegedly killed
two black bucks and a chinkara in a restricted wildlife preserve in
the western Rajasthan state, after a judge rejected his request for
bail, said Alka Kala, the state's highest forest official.
	   The charges carry a maximum imprisonment of seven years, she
said.
	   Members of the local Bishnoi tribe who worship the endangered
black bucks and chinkaras alerted forest officials to the hunt.
	   Another popular actor Saif Ali Khan and actresses Sonali Bendre,
Tabu and Neelam _ who were present at the killing in fort town of
Jodhpur _ were granted bail, officials said. Tabu and Neelam use
only their first names.
	   The other actors will still be tried, Kala said.
	   ``All were involved but the judge found that it was Salman who
pulled the trigger,'' Kala said, speaking from the state's capital
city of Jaipur.
	   Salman Khan, who has a reputation for being brash and rude, has
been the heartthrob of Indian women for almost a decade. He is seen
as a macho romantic, who fights for love in gut-wrenching fight
scenes and action sequences, and is compared in the Indian press to
U.S. actor Sylvester Stallone.
	   Wildlife organizations criticized the killings, and an attorney
of the Wildlife Protection Society of India helped the prosecution
at the court hearing.
	   More than 100 people _ including the driver whose jeep
transported one of the bleeding black bucks and the chef who cooked
it to the actors' specifications _ gave evidence against the film
stars, officials said.
	   The film stars were shooting a film near Jodhpur, a tourist hub
in the Thar desert that was once part of the medieval kingdom of
Rajput dynasty warriors. Jodhpur is 500 kilometers (300 miles)
southwest of New Delhi.
	   Members of the deer-worshipping Bishnoi tribe said they heard
gunshots and rushed to the site, where they found the two actors
and three actresses with the dead animals. The movie stars quickly
drove away with one black buck, tribe members said.
	   Tribe members buried the other two animals.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
