<SLUG> BC-Greece-Elections </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Run-off local elections needed in most regions
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ Although conservatives celebrated election
gains against the governing Socialists, near complete results
Monday showed most races must be decided at next week's run-off
ballots.
	   The elections are considered a key referendum on the
government's policies, which include unpopular austerity programs
aimed at qualifying Greece for the European Union's single currency
club.
	   Athens' Mayor Dimitris Avramopoulos was one of the few
candidates winning an outright majority in Sunday's elections with
a landslide 57.7 percent, returns said.
	   Other conservative candidates in Salonica and Piraeus also
gained majorities with 44.4 percent and 42.8 percent, respectively.
But they must face run-offs against Socialist candidates on Sunday.
	   The Socialists struggled to hide their dismay.
	   ``The course of the government ... will be judged at the end of
its term at the national elections of 2000,'' said acting
government spokesman Yiannis Nikolaou.
	   Local elections cannot change the socialists' grip on
parliament. But the outcome _ two years before the general
elections _ is widely interpreted as a test for Premier Costas
Simitis.
	   Of the 50 regional governor races across the country, 14
rendered winners through absolute majorities in the first round _
seven conservatives and seven Socialists.
	   Most of the 900 mayoral seats will also be decided in the
run-off vote.
	   (tt-eb-bm) 	   
