<SLUG> BC-Iran-Rushdie, 2nd Ld,0320 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iranian foundation raises reward for killing Rushdie
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: INSERTS new grafs 7-8 to UPDATE with reaction from Rushdie
foundation. Pick up 8th graf pvs &QL; 
 &UR; By AFSHIN VALINEJAD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ An Iranian foundation has added dlrs 300,000
to the reward for Salman Rushdie's death, just weeks after the
Iranian government tried to distance itself from the bounty.
	   The move was a striking show of the infighting within Iran's
fractured government between hard-liners and moderates gathered
around President Mohammad Khatami, who has sought to improve ties
with the West since he assumed office last year.
	   ``I, as the head of the Khordad Foundation, add dlrs 300,000 to
the reward for implementing the edict,'' Ayatollah Hassan Saneii
was quoted as saying by Jomhuri Islami newspaper Monday.
	   The semiofficial foundation had initially offered dlrs 2.5
million to anyone who killed the British author, whose book ``The
Satanic Verses,'' Iran claimed, was blasphemous to Islam.
	   The comments by Saneii were the first by the foundation since
Iran's government distanced itself last month from the death edict,
helping improve relations with Britain. Saneii is the
representative of Iran's supreme leader, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, in
the foundation.
	   ``To set a reward for killing Salman Rushdie has been a great
honor for this foundation and we will keep this honor. We should
not let this issue be forgotten,'' Saneii said.
	   On Saturday, a hard-line Iranian student group offered 1 billion
rials (dlrs 333,333) to anyone who kills Rushdie.
	   In London, the chairwoman of the Rushdie defense committee said
the development was ``extremely serious.''
	   ``There is no way that the organization is a private one,'' said
Frances D'Souza. ``It is undoubtedly sanctioned by the
government.''
