<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Portugal-Mad Cow </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Portugal prepares new measures against ``mad cow'' disease
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ The government is drawing up new
measures to stem a sharp rise in cases of ``mad cow'' disease in
Portugal after the European Commission threatened to ban Portuguese
beef exports, an official said Monday.
	   ``The government will unveil the measures soon, possibly by the
end of this week,'' Agriculture Ministry spokesman Augusto Vilela
said. He declined to give any details about the measures.
	   Earlier this month, the European Commission threatened a
Europe-wide ban on beef exports from Portugal unless the government
tightened controls on bovine animal remains used in cattle feed.
	   Spain banned the import of Portuguese beef last month.
	   Portugal has reported 60 new cases of ``mad cow'' disease in the
past five months, compared with a total of cases 94 for all
previous years. In addition, there are at least 28 suspected but
unconfirmed cases.
	   The disease's incubation period is long, and the recent rise in
cases has sparked fears that the scale of the problem in Portugal
is only now beginning to emerge.
	   Once the animal has been infected, it takes up to eight years
before the first symptoms of the disease _ bovine spongiform
encephalopathy, or BSE _ are detected.
	   (cp/bh/jt)	   
</TEXT>
