r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EU-Fraud     10-12 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Fraud </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bonino eyes legal action against FT over EU fraud story
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) - EU Humanitarian Aid Commissioner Emma
Bonino said Monday she considered sueing the Financial Times of
London over an article which she said damaged her good name by
implicating her in a fraud case.
	   The article, published Monday, claimed that at a meeting last
week of the 20-member EU executive Commission, Bonino's colleagues
``castigated (her) over allegations of fraud and mismanagement'' at
the EU's humanitarian aid office for which she is responsible.
	   In a letter to the Financial Times, Bonino termed the report
``patently false.''
	   ``At no time during the Commission meeting referred to, or at
any time, have I been the subject of criticism or even critical
remarks by colleagues in relation to matters of mismanagement and
fraud,'' she wrote.
	   Speaking to reporters Monday she said, ``this article damaged my
reputation. Freedom of the press does not signify the freedom to
write just anything.''
	   The Commission has been the target of late of allegations of
fraud and irregularities in spending.
	   Its humanitarian aid office, known by its acronym of ECHO, has
come under particular scrutiny in a case involving the
disappearance of 540,000 ecu (dlrs 594,000).
	   Last month, Bonino acknowledged the funds had gone missing and
that one ECHO official was suspended. The funds were part of four
aid contracts earmarked for ex-Yugoslavia and Rwanda in 1993-1994,
totaling 2.4 million ecus (dlrs 2.6 million). At that time, Bonino
was not responsible for ECHO.
	   Separately, EU anti-fraud officials are investigating the use of
funds in contracts between ECHO and three unnamed organizations.
	   Bonino's office would not give details on this affair.
	   The European parliament will vote this month whether to freeze
ECHO funds for next year until the fraud allegations have been
cleared up.
	   Bonino has repeatedly defended the integrity of her office and
said on Monday she feels bitter about being personally targeted.
	   ``I would have expected a paper as reputed as the Financial
Times to be more rigorous and to check the accuracy of its
reports,'' she said.
	   In her letter to the daily, she wrote she had instructed her
lawyers ``to take all necessary legal redress against the Financial
Times in respect of the injury caused to my good name, personal
dignity and political reputation as a result of the publication of
this article.''
	   One option under consideration, she said, was asking the paper
to publish a formal correction of Monday's article.
 &UR; (as-rw)
</TEXT>
