<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Balkan Summit-Yugoslavia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yugoslav premier rails against NATO as alliance warship heads for
</HEADLINE>
his country &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Turkey-Balkan Summit &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ANTALYA, Turkey (AP) _ As Yugoslav Premier Momir Bulatovic
Monday railed against NATO, international criminals and foreign
intervention in his country, he failed to look out the window and
see what was coming.
	   ``Threats of military intervention are unacceptable, absolutely
counter-productive and can not resolve anything but can only
contribute to destabilization of the region with unforeseen
consequences,'' Bulatovic told Balkan leaders assembled in this
seaside resort.
	   In the distance the French aircraft carrier Foch was building up
steam and moving across this picturesque bay, with most of its 40
planes, on a journey towards the Adriatic Sea and the Yugoslav
coast to join an assembling NATO armada.
	   Earlier in Paris, French Defense Minister Alain Richard said his
country would provide around 40 aircraft for possible airstrikes,
which could last ``several days.''
	   Bulatovic failed to see the ship as he addressed a near hostile
crowd of prime ministers from Bulgaria, Greece, Macedonia ,
Romania, Turkey, the foreign minister of Albania, and observers
from Bosnia and Croatia.
	   Railing against ``international criminals and terrorists,'' out
to get Yugoslavia, he said his country was ``striving to fully
contribute to the vision of a new, integrated, open and developed
Balkans.''
	   But with NATO airstrikes near imminent, some diplomats here were
trying to envision Yugoslavia after air strikes. Although many
countries, including alliance members Greece and Turkey, will
probably contribute to possible ground troops in the
Albanian-dominated province, some were trying to find alternatives
acceptable to the Yugoslavs.
	   Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic has fought a request By
U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke that he agree to an expanded
international monitoring mission in Kosovo to verify compliance
with demands of the U.N. Security Council.
	   One idea thrown around here was the possibility of using a
Balkan multinational force that was agreed upon during a meeting in
Macedonia on Sept. 26, although it is still in the planning stages.
	   The agreement was signed by three NATO countries - Italy, Turkey
and Greece - and five prospective alliance members in the Balkans -
Macedonia, Slovenia, Bulgaria, Romania and Albania.
	    &UR; pq
</TEXT>
