<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Fashion </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fresh New Offerings from Vuitton for Spring
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos PAR101-5
 &UR; By SUZY PATTERSON &QC; 
 &UR; AP Fashion Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Fresh as a spring day was Marc Jacobs's second
luxury ready-to-wear collection for Louis Vuitton. It was shown
Monday in a sun-filled glass box called a ``greenhouse'' at Andre
Citroen Park west of the Eiffel Tower.
	   The American designer's line for spring was ready for April
showers, too, with terrific rain gear in heavy cottons and
plastified fabrics.
	   He led off with a cream bonded (heavy) cotton poncho over
polyester stretch T-shirt and teeny shorts, later going into a
see-through poncho that could double as a shower curtain.
	   It all looked very modern, especially the pale chartreuse simple
brushed cotton blouse-jacket with little sleeves or khaki cotton
shorts, sported by Naomi Campbell.
	   Wrapped skirts, long or cropped lean cotton trousers and cotton
sweaters with cowl collars came out with plenty of class - as did
the double-faced wools, tunics and skirts below the knee, but not
too long.
	   Clever little velvet swimsuits, great soft color combinations
like grape and cyclamen or subtle flesh tones, the
mirror-sequin-embroidered tops all had a young look with quality
attention to detail: things like apron-tied tops gave the
collection originality, taking it away from strict minimalism.
	   The one spring print in bubbles was original and fun: on a
knee-length cotton dress or handsome rubberized cotton poncho.
	   Vuitton, best known for its great luggage and handbags, only
showed a few little pochette-belts with the collection. As if to
say ``look at the other garments!''
	   Some luxury houses are starting to feel the financial crisis
pinch.
	   But Bernard Arnault, head of LVMH (Louis Vuitton Moet Hennessy),
who controls several other fashion houses, including Givenchy and
Dior, looked serene as he progressed through an enthusiastic crowd
with his wife, Helene, to salute Jacobs.
	   Among other young designers who lit the fashion scene Monday,
Jean-Luc Amsler has a kind of funky Seventies look with long coats,
backless wrapped dresses, swimsuits and shorts. They're matched to
coats and pants in blue-jeans tones of synthetics and cottons.
	   His silvery mesh ponchos over silver pants and a bra for evening
and the fake leather looks, layers of color and hip huggers had a
very trendy-nostalgic look from the Age of Aquarius.
	   Jerome L'Huillier was on a more sophisticated trail, with a lot
of wet-look clingy fabrics - draped onto the body at times,
criss-cross wrapped and draped blouses, and many sweet knit
outfits.
	   His good square jackets in silky fabrics with split longer
skirts, glitter in the fabric, should help the junior set dress up
- along with a few classically-cut coats.
	   While nude-tan seems to be a favorite color for spring, the
clothes so far are not giving the paparazzi posse much of a sexy
look-see.
	   (sp-cb)
</TEXT>
