<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Jehova's Witness </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German exhibit on fate of Jehova's Witness members under Nazis
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ An exhibit on the fate Jehova Witness
followers in Germany opened in Dresden Monday, showing that some
2,000 of the religious group's members lost their lives under the
Nazis.
	   About 300 Jehova's Witness believers were executed by the Nazis,
while 1,700 died in concentration camps, said Martin Jahn, an
exhibit organizer for the group. A total of 6,000 were jailed, he
said.
	   The Christian group was persecuted by the Nazis because they
followed the the biblical motto, ``Thou shalt not kill,'' said
Jahn. At least some were condemned for refusing to fight in
Hitler's army.
	   The persecution continued after the war, with communist
authorities in East Germany jailing about 5,000 members of the
group, Jahn said.
	   East Germany banned the group after the communist-ruled nation's
highest court ruled in October 1950 that Jehova Witness teachings
incited boycotts of the military, the exhibit shows.
	   The exhibit, titled ``Steadfast despite Persecution,'' is to run
to the end of the month.
 &UR; (dkt-gb)
</TEXT>
