<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Holbrooke, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Holbrooke departing for Brussels
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; URGENT &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: LEADS with Interfax report that Milosevic agreed to monitoring
force &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke will
leave Belgrade on Monday for Brussels to brief NATO envoys on the
results of his talks with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, a
U.S. source said.
	   In Moscow, Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev told Russia's
Interfax news agency said Milosevic agreed to allow a 1,500-member
international observer force in Kosovo to verify compliance with
U.N. Security Council demands to end the crackdown in the majority
Albanian province.
	   Interfax said Russia was prepared to provide aircraft to the
force. The verification force was believed to have been the major
obstacle to a deal to prevent NATO airstrikes.
	   The U.S. source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Holbrooke wanted to brief NATO ambassadors on the results of his
talks with Milosevic aimed at convincing him to accept U.N. demands
for ending the crackdown in Kosovo.
	   Ambassadors from the 16 NATO members were meeting Monday at
headquarters in Belgium, Belgium to consider whether to approve an
activation order, the last military step before airstrikes can be
launched.
	   The source indicated Holbrooke had made enough progress that he
needed to update NATO personally.
	   A NATO official who spoke on condition of anonymity said an
activation order would show NATO's resolve to end the violence in
Kosovo, where hundreds of people have been killed and an estimated
275,000 uprooted since February's crackdown on ethnic Albanian
rebels.
	   The order would transfer the command over the airplanes and
military equipment necessary for an airstrike to Supreme Allied
Commander Wesley K. Clark and authorize its deployment over
Yugoslavia.
	   end
	   rr/ds
</TEXT>
