<HEADLINE>
Holbrooke to debrief NATO on Milosevic talks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Holbrooke flyiing to brussels, talk of progress &QL; 
 &UR; With Yugoslavia-Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo BRU101 &QL; 
 &UR; By RAF CASERT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke was to
brief NATO late Monday on his talks with Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic before the alliance will decide whether to take
the last military step needed to launch airstrikes against the
Serbs.
	   ``Apparently he got enough concessions from Milosevic to brief
the (NATO) ambassadors,'' said a NATO official, who demanded
anonymity.
	   NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana talked ``at length'' over
the phone with Holbrooke about his latest attempts to persuade Serb
leader Milosevic to abide by U.N. Security Council demands in
Kosovo, the official said.
	   Holbrooke left Belgrade and was to meet Solana around 8 p.m.
(1800GMT), the official said.
	   If the Holbrooke talks fail, NATO was expected to approve an
activation order later on Monday, a vital step before airstrikes
can be launched.
