<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-Basque Truce </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Security remains tight for city councilors despite ETA cease-fire
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ Governing party town councilors are still
being provided with bodyguards and told to check under their cars
for bombs despite the truce declared by the armed separatist group
ETA, a newspaper reported Monday.
	   Nearly four weeks since the cease-fire was announced security
measures remain tight because the government believes the
separatists are still monitoring the movements of governing party
town councilors as potential targets, leading daily El Pais
reported.
	   Prior to the cease-fire local-level representatives of Prime
Minister Jose Maria Aznar's Popular Party had become ETA's main
targets.
	   Five of the seven people killed over the last year by ETA _ an
acronym standing for Basque Homeland and Freedom in the Basque
language _ were Popular Party councilors.
	   Interior Minister Jaime Mayor Oreja refused to confirm or deny
the El Pais report that ETA was still monitoring councilors as
possible victims.
	   But Mayor Oreja, the minister responsible for security in Spain,
did affirm that security measures for these politicians had not
been relaxed, national Spanish radio reported.
	   ETA has killed nearly 800 people in its 30-year campaign for an
independent Basque homeland covering a small part of northern Spain
and southern France.
	   On Sept. 18 the group called its first ever indefinite
cease-fire, seeking to set in motion a peace process that would
produce a negotiated end the conflict.
	   The Spanish government reacted suspiciously to the truce,
rejecting the idea of political negotiations on the issue of Basque
self-determination and demanding that ETA prove it intended to lay
down its arms forever.
	   All political parties in the northern Basque County _ from
Aznar's Popular Party to the ETA-linked political coalition Herri
Batasuna _ are currently immersed in campaigning for regional
elections set for Oct 25.
	   (jt)
</TEXT>
