<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Italy-Doping, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italian Olympic Committee antidoping prosecutor resigns
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with players deciding against strike, edits to
conform &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MILAN, Italy (AP) _ The chief antidoping prosecutor of Italy's
Olympic Committee resigned Monday, the latest victim of a doping
scandal that has shaken Italian soccer.
	   But professional soccer players dropped the threat of a strike,
agreeing instead to measures designed to safeguard their health.
	   The players' association had threatened a six-month walkout to
protest the handling of the inquiries, which it claims violate
players' privacy.
	   Ugo Longo, the antidoping prosecutor, said ``difficult work
conditions'' motivated his decision.
	   Since the summer, Longo had been conducting one of four
inquiries into the use of banned substances by Italy's first
division soccer players. Investigators have reportedly discovered
that some tests were not complete and results of others might have
been hidden.
	   The doping debacle has already seen CONI president Mario
Pescante resign and the chief of CONI's Acqua Acetosa laboratory,
Emilio Gasbarrone, fired.
	   The Acqua Acetosa lab was shut down after an International
Olympic Committee (IOC) official deemed the facility
unsatisfactory.
	   AS Roma coach Zdenek Zeman sparked the investigations in July
when he raised questions about the sudden muscular development of
certain players.
	   (vg/vls/pv) 	   
