w1590 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 10thLd   10-12 0229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 10th Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. bombers prepare for airstrikes amid marathon Kosovo talks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Holbrooke leaving to brief NATO envoys, Russian
defense minister saying Milosevic has agreed to allow international
observers in Kosovo, no confirmation &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By KATARINA KRATOVAC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke wrapped
up marathon talks with President Slobodan Milosevic on Monday and
left for Brussels to brief NATO officials amid indications of
progress toward a deal aimed at evading airstrikes.
	   Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev told journalists in
Moscow that Milosevic has agreed to allow the deployment of 1,500
observers in Kosovo _ a move that would be a key concession by the
Yugoslav leader.
	   Sergeyev expressed optimism that a political settlement could be
reached on the crisis, even as NATO was positioning itself for
airstrikes, preparing to authorize an attack should the
Milosevic-Holbrooke talks fail.
	   There was no immediate confirmation of Milosevic's reported
concession. But a statement from Milosevic's office said Holbrooke
would return and hold more talks Tuesday.
	   It said Milosevic ``has concluded that undoubtably, necessary
conditions exists for peaceful, political solution to the Kosovo
problem.''
	    &UR; MORE
	   dc/rr
</TEXT>
