<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
President appeals to parliament over government's fate
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ President Leonid Kuchma asked the Ukrainian
parliament on Monday not to launch a vote of no-confidence against
his struggling government.
	   Such a step would only ``aggravate the situation in the
country'' and could negatively affect Ukraine's already battered
economy, Kuchma said at a Cabinet meeting.
	   ``Nobody would win, no political force would benefit from that,
and ordinary people would suffer, as usual,'' the president said.
	   The dominant centrist and leftist opposition legislators in the
Verkhovna Rada are insisting that parliament consider the fate of
Prime Minister Valery Pustovoitenko's government.
	   About 200 lawmakers in the 450-seat Rada voted last week to
include the issue of a possible no-confidence vote in parliament's
session agenda.
	   But parliament speaker Oleksandr Tkachenko and his deputies
argue that the government should first be allowed to present its
1999 budget and implement a series of planned steps to battle
Ukraine's deepening economic crisis.
	   The matter of no-confidence should be postponed at least until
November, Tkachenko said Monday, according to the Interfax news
agency.
	   Kuchma, meanwhile, lashed out at his centrist and Socialist
opponents for trying to bring down Pustovoitenko's Cabinet at a
difficult time for Ukraine, yet stressed that he would be prepared
to make ``serious changes'' in the government if his parliamentary
foes make such proposals.
	   Kuchma also said he would ``officially'' offer Communist leader
Petro Symonenko the chance to head the Cabinet if his faction,
which holds about a quarter of parliament seats, votes against the
current government.
	   The president has made such offers before, trying to show that
Communists were not ready to assume responsibility for leading the
nation.
	   Pustovoitenko gave the Cabinet a grim account of Ukraine's
economic situation, saying he feared the ``wave of the world
financial crisis that is approaching Ukraine.''
	   The former Soviet republic of 50 million people already has
suffered badly from the consequences of world economic
developments, notably the crisis in neighboring Russia.
	   Pustovoitenko reported a 0.3 percent drop in industrial output
since the start of the year and said prices for industrial goods
had grown by 9.4 percent in September alone.
	   The turmoil in Russia also has pushed the national hryvna
currency to lose 71 percent of its value so far this year,
including a 51 percent drop last month, Pustovoitenko said. The
hryvna traded at 3.42 to the U.S. dollar on Monday, down from about
2.1 before the Russian crisis.
	   (sms/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
