<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Canada-Indians,0217 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Study finds Canada's Indians don't share high living standards
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   OTTAWA (AP) _ Though Canada is No. 1 in a United Nations
quality-of-life ranking, a new government study suggests Indians on
reserves have living conditions lower than those in Mexico or
Thailand.
	   For the past six years, Canada has topped a human-development
index compiled by the United Nations on the basis of per capita
income, education levels and life expectancy.
	   Canada's Department of Indian Affairs, applying the index
specifically to aboriginals for the first time, found that the
380,000 Indians living on reserves in Canada would rank 63rd among
the 173 countries in the U.N. index _ about the same level as
Brazil.
	   Indians living off reserves came in 35th, equal to Russia,
according to the study, which was made public Monday.
	   ``This is not a surprise for us,'' said Phil Fontaine, head of
the national assembly of Indian chiefs. ``We live this every day.
People have to be cautious about using the fact that we're No. 1,
that Canada is the best place in the world to live.''
	   According to recent government statistics, the life expectancy
of Indians on reserves is seven years less than the national
average, and income levels are about half the national average.
</TEXT>
