</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Algeria-Truce, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Muslim leaders worldwide urge armed groups to join truce
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. UPDATES with Salvation Front reaction; rewrites; TRIMS
 &UR; By ELAINE GANLEY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Muslim leaders around the world have appealed to
Islamic insurgents in Algeria to lay down their arms and urged
authorities to seek reconciliation in a conflict in which more than
75,000 people have died.
	   The statement, dated Sunday and received here Monday, said blind
violence that kills women, children and the elderly _ which has
been widespread in the nearly 7-year-old insurgency _ is contrary
to Islam.
	   Hailing a truce called a year ago by the Islamic Salvation Army,
an insurgency faction, the statement said other insurgents should
join in and Algerian authorities should use it to ``strengthen the
bases for national global reconciliation.''
	   The statement was signed by 30 Muslim leaders and intellectuals
from Malaysia to Morocco, from the head of Egypt's banned Muslim
Brotherhood to university professors.
	   The signatories ``consider the truce ... a good work and a bold
patriotic position that has contributed in an appreciable manner to
diminishing the level of killings, destruction and attacks on
sacred laws,'' the statement said.
	   Accusations of apostasy by armed groups concerning fellow
Muslims are an ``ignominy,'' leading to ``great evil.'' Blind
killings, likewise, give ``the enemies of Islam the occasion to
deform'' the religion, the statement said.
	   Algerian Foreign Ministry spokesman Abdelaziz Sbaa, in a dry
comment, said authorities ``have long waited'' for such a
statement.
	   There was no immediate reaction from the Armed Islamic Group,
the radical insurgency movement held responsible for numerous
massacres.
	   The Islamic Salvation Army, the military wing of the banned
Islamic Salvation Front, called the truce in part to ``unmask the
enemy hiding behind the abominable massacres.''
	   But the truce has been belittled by some as a unilateral
cease-fire by a poorly equipped force. It even divided the Islamic
Salvation Front, some of whose members consider the truce a virtual
surrender.
	   The insurgency erupted after the army-backed government canceled
January 1992 legislative elections to thwart a likely victory by
the Islamic Salvation Front.
	   A spokesman for the Salvation Front's headquarters-in-exile,
Abdelkrime Ould Adda, said the Front hoped the statement ``can help
in finding a peaceful political solution to the crisis.''
	   Among signatories were: Mustapha Mashhour, leader of Egypt's
Muslim Brotherhood; Ahmed Yassine, spiritual leader of the
Palestinian movement Hamas; Tunisian Rachid Ghannouchi, living in
exile in London; and Ghulam A'dham Amir of the Jamaat Islami group
in Bangladesh.
	   Others included Qadi Hussein of the Jemaat Islami in Pakistan;
Fadel Nour, president of the Islamic Party of Malaysia; and Dr.
Azzam Tamimi, head of the British-based Liberty organization.
	   (eg-cb)
</TEXT>
