<SLUG> BC-Germany-Jehovah's Witnesses, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German exhibit on fate of Jehovah's Witnesses under Nazis
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS to Jehovah's Witnesses sted Jehova Witness
throughout. RECASTS and edits to tighten &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ Jehovah's Witnesses opened an exhibit
in the eastern city of Dresden on Monday focusing on the
persecution of its members under the Nazis.
	   About 300 Jehovah's Witnesses were executed by the Nazis and
another 1,700 died in concentration camps, said exhibit organizer
Martin Jahn. More than 6,000 were jailed or sent to concentration
camps.
	   Jehovah's Witnesses were persecuted by the Nazis largely because
of their opposition to military service, Jahn said.
	   The persecution continued after the war in communist East
Germany, where authorities banned the group in 1950 because of its
pacifist views, and jailed about 5,000 members of the group, Jahn
said.
	   The exhibit, including 500 documents and diagrams, is being
displayed in a former courthouse where the Nazis executed more than
1,300 people.
 &UR; (dkt-gb-cb)
