w1661 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UN-Kosovo     10-12 0337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Kosovo,0336 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN chief phones Milosevic, Yugoslav leader says he's trying to
</HEADLINE>
comply &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan phoned
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic on Monday to urge him to
comply with U.N. resolutions calling for a cease-fire and political
settlement in Kosovo, a spokesman said.
	   Milosevic responded that he was ``in the process of complying,
or trying to come into full compliance with the Security Council
resolutions,'' spokesman Fred Eckhard said.
	   Annan's call came hours before NATO began considering whether to
authorize military strikes against Serbs, who are trying to quash
an independence movement by Kosovo's ethnic Albanian majority.
	   It also came as U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke wrapped up marathon
talks with Milosevic and prepared to brief NATO ambassadors on his
efforts to reach an agreement allowing for international observers
to oversee a cease-fire in the southern Serb province.
	   Annan and Milosevic discussed some of the details of the
Holbrooke talks, Eckhard said without elaborating.
	   The U.N. chief met Friday with Yugoslavia's acting U.N.
ambassador, Vladislav Jovanovic, and called for ``every effort to
be made'' to reach a political settlement, Eckhard said.
	   Ethnic Albanians, who make up about 90 percent of Kosovo's
population, have been fighting since February for independence from
Serbia. Hundreds have been killed and over 270,000 have fled their
homes in the wake of Serb reprisals.
	   The West doesn't support independence for Kosovo, but wants
Milosevic to restore the broad autonomy he stripped from the
province in 1989.
	   In a Sept. 23 resolution, the 15-member Security Council
demanded a cease-fire, the withdrawal of special Serb police units
from the province, and movement toward a negotiated settlement. It
demanded the safe return of refugees and humanitarian access to
them.
	   The council threatened unspecified action if both sides failed
to comply.
</TEXT>
