<SLUG> BC-Poland-Orthodox Church,0217 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Orthodox leader visits Poland
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Archbishop of Constantinople and
Ecumenical Patriarch Bartholomew I awarded Poland's prime minister
a medal Monday for good cooperation with the Orthodox church.
	   Jerzy Buzek, who became prime minister after last year's
parliament elections, is a member of the Solidarity party in the
ruling coalition. He also is Protestant, which is considered
unusual in the predominantly Roman Catholic country.
	   In 1991, the Solidarity government passed a law giving the
Orthodox church in Poland the same rights as the Catholic church,
according to Interior Ministry official Krzysztof Wiktor.
	   Bartholomew I, the spiritual leader of nearly 300 million
Orthodox Christians, also met Monday with Cardinal Jozef Glemp, the
leader of Poland's Roman Catholic Church.
	   At a religious ceremony Sunday after his arrival on a week long
trip to Poland, Bartholomew I appealed for more dialogue and
cooperation between churches. He also met with President Aleksander
Kwasniewski and awarded him a medal for helping ensure equal status
of churches in Poland.
	   Bartholomew I also will visit Krakow, the Auschwitz Nazi death
camp and Bialystok, the center of Poland's 550,000-strong Orthodox
community.
</TEXT>
