<SLUG> BC-Jordan-Arafat, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Arafat says summit should lead to further Israeli withdrawal
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with quotes, departure, ADDS byline
 &UR; AP Photo AMM-101
 &UR; By JAMAL HALABY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat said on
Monday that he hoped that an upcoming Palestinian-Israeli summit
meeting in Washington would set the ground for a further Israeli
pullback from the West Bank.
	   ``We hope it will not only be talk, talk, talk,'' Arafat told
reporters after a two-hour meeting with Crown Prince Hassan. The
crown prince is acting as regent while King Hussein is abroad.
	   ``We hope that this round will lead to concrete results on
Jerusalem ... and to the implementation of the U.S. proposal,''
Arafat said before returning home.
	   The U.S. proposal calls for Israel to withdraw from another 13
percent of the West Bank.
	   Israel earlier had given the Palestinians full or shared control
of about 27 percent of the land.
	   Arafat has called repeatedly for an end to the expansion of
Israeli settlements in Jerusalem. Peace talks broke down in March
1997 after Israel began a housing project for Jews in traditionally
Arab east Jerusalem.
	   The four-day Palestinian-Israeli summit is set to begin Thursday
outside the U.S. capital.
	   In his brief remarks, Arafat accused Israel of ``intransigence''
and said it had not yet announced acceptance of the U.S. proposal,
which he described as a catalyst to ``save the peace process and
push it forward.''
	   He said he was confident that President Clinton ``will ... make
the effort to arrive at a positive conclusion and positive
results'' at the Washington meeting.
	   Hassan said he was equally optimistic because ``it is imperative
to arrive at a visible threshold of achievement and this is what we
expect.''
