<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Antigua-Clapton's Crossroads,0473 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Addiction recovery center created by rock star opens in Caribbean
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROBERT HOFFMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ST. JOHN'S, Antigua (AP) _ A dlrs 6.5 million addiction recovery
center completely underwritten by British rock star Eric Clapton
will accept its first patient Tuesday and promises to turn away no
one who needs treatment.
	   Clapton, himself once addicted to drugs, built the 36-bed
Crossroads Centre of Antigua over the past five years. It will
offer intensive, 29-day recovery programs to people addicted to
drugs or alcohol at a cost of dlrs 9,000.
	   For those unable to pay, foundations have been formed in
Antigua, the United States, Canada and the United Kingdom to offer
financial aid.
	   ``No one will be turned away,'' said administrator Anne Vance,
who for 11 years worked at the Betty Ford Center in Southern
California. It was Vance who met Clapton in 1994 in London and
eventually persuaded the singer and virtuoso guitarist to provide
the financing for the Caribbean's only such facility.
	   But there is no free ride. ``For those who cannot pay the full
fee, we will expect some kind of voluntary contribution in the form
of work after the patient has recovered,'' Vance said.
	   Clapton, who maintains a residence here on a bluff overlooking
the Atlantic not far from the center, has said he will work
directly with patients from time to time, drawing on his own
experiences.
	   The idea of the facility was conceived in St. John's more than
five years ago by Antiguan residents Hans and Nancy Smit, along
with Dr. Tom Martin, now the resident physician.
	   ``This is a wonderful day for us,'' Nancy Smit said as she and
her husband toured Crossroads on Sunday with members of the
nonprofit Hourglass Foundation they established to help bring the
project to fruition. ``Dreams do come true.''
	   Set on the edge of breathtaking Willoughby Bay on the southeast
side of this tiny island some 300 miles (480 kilometers)
east-southeast of Puerto Rico, the entirely new campus provides
spartan yet modern accommodations. Each room has two or three
single beds.
	   ``Part of the basic therapy is that a patient is never left
alone,'' said admissions counselor Kim Chapman said. ``But this is
not to say they won't have any privacy.''
	   A swimming pool, massage room and small gymnasium are available
to patients. The hospital also offers a week-long non-resident
``family program'' that counsels relatives or friends of addicts at
a cost of about dlrs 200 per person, Vance said.
	   Vance said most of the center's patients are expected come from
the United States and Britain, but at least one-third of the beds
are to be reserved for clients from the Caribbean. By the end of
the week, at least six patients were expected to be in residence.
</TEXT>
