r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Lithuania-Lileikis     10-12 0346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lithuania-Lileikis,0345 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lithuanian doctors say alleged Nazi fit to testify
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   VILNIUS, Lithuania (AP) _ A 91-year-old former Lithuanian
security chief is fit to stand trial on genocide charges, a
court-appointed panel of doctors said Monday, but they warned that
the stress of court proceedings could endanger his life.
	   The ruling leaves in doubt whether Aleksandras Lileikis, a
former U.S. resident, will be brought to trial. Attempts to start
proceedings against him on war crimes charges have repeatedly been
delayed and many critics contend Lithuanian authorities are hoping
Lileikis will die before a trial starts.
	   The trial was supposed to begin in mid-September, but Lileikis'
legal team said he was too ill to appear in court. Lithuanian law
does not allow trial in absentia for medical reasons and the court
ordered a panel of doctors to assess his health.
	   Lileikis was head of the security police in the Lithuanian
capital during the 1941-44 Nazi occupation. He is charged with
ordering the arrests of scores of Jews and turning them over to a
Nazi execution squad. About 90 percent of Lithuania's 240,000 Jews
were killed during World War II.
	   ``The current state of Lileikis' health does allow him to take
part and testify in the trial, but any stress could lead to a
health condition hazardous to his life,'' the doctors' panel said
Monday.
	   But the panel chairman, Henrikas Ulevicius, refused to be
comment on whether the trial should go ahead, saying only that
``the judge has do decide whether to bring Lileikis to the
courtroom.''
	   Lileikis' lawyer reacted angrily to the ruling.
	   ``I am deeply shocked by the news that physicians have allowed a
subpoena to be issued,'' Algimantas Matuiza said. ``His health is
getting worse every day.''
	   Lileikis emigrated to the United States in 1955, and lived in
Norwood, Massachusetts, where he worked for a Lithuanian publishing
house.
	   He returned to Lithuania more than two years ago as the United
was undertaking efforts to revoke his citizenship and deport him.
</TEXT>
