<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Southern Africa-Peacekeeping Exercise </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Amid fighting and interventions, African peacekeeping exercise
</HEADLINE>
postponed &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ With half its member nations
either participating in foreign military interventions or hosting
them, a southern African alliance postponed a joint peacekeeping
exercise on Monday.
	   ``Due to recent events in the sub-region, it has become
necessary to postpone exercise Blue Crane,'' the South African
government _ which was to have hosted the Nov. 3-21 exercise
involving 13 countries _ said in a statement.
	   The exercise was to have been held under the auspices of the
Southern African Development Community.
	   Troops from SADC member countries Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia
are in Congo _ also an SADC member _ fighting rebels on behalf of
Congo President Laurent Kabila.
	   Soldiers from South Africa and Botswana, meanwhile, are in
Lesotho to quash an army mutiny and end other unrest. All three
countries are also SADC members.
	   Other countries in the 14-member regional group are Malawi,
Mauritius, Mozambique, Seychelles, Swaziland, Tanzania and Zambia.
	   Officials will discuss next month when to reschedule exercise
Blue Crane, the statement said.
	   (aos)
</TEXT>
