<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-SAmerica Roundup,0472 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Boca Juniors widen lead in Argentina; Rio's Flamengo and Vasco win
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By KEVIN GRAY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) _ Argentina's Boca Juniors
distanced themselves from the pack over the weekend, stretching
their first-division lead to six points with a 3-0 victory over
Ferro.
	   Martin Palermo leaped between two Ferro defenders and hit a
driving header to give Boca a 2-0 lead in the first half.
	   Palermo continued his scoring frenzy that has him leading the
league. In 10 games, the 25-year-old striker, expected to make the
jump to the Italian leagues next year, has scored 11 goals.
	   After meeting Brazil's Flamengo Wednesday in a Copa Mercosur
match, Boca will play Velez Sarsfield on Sunday. Velez, last
season's champion, is seven points back in the standings.
	   The Velez game will be Boca's biggest test this season. Facing
the former team of new Boca coach, Carlos Bianchi, is expected to
give an added dose of energy and emotion to an already heated
rivalry.
	   And recent disparaging comments by Velez's always controversial
goalkeeper, Jose Luis Chilavert, should also help raise the
temperature of the match.
 &UR; BRAZIL &QC; 
	   Rio's top two teams, Flamengo and Vasco de Gama, used weekend
victories to help gain ground on Sao Paulo's leading clubs,
currently holding top places in the standings.
	   Flamengo defeated Corinthians, and new Brazil manager Wanderely
Luxemburgo, 4-1.
	   Vasco outpaced second-placed Santos 3-1.
	   Flamengo's fourth consecutive victory moved them into 11th
place, tied with crosstown rival Vasco. But it came at a price:
star striker Romario limped off the field in the first half with a
thigh injury. He's likely to return next week but will miss
Wednesday's matchup against Argentina's Boca Juniors.
	   Sao Paulo's Palmeiras beat Internacional 1-0 to hold on to the
league's top spot with 38 points after 17 games.
	   In the weekend's most exciting game, Botafogo scored three goals
in the final nine minutes to draw Atletico-Minas Gerais 5-5. The
tie keeps Botafogo out of the league's basement.
 &UR; CHILE &QC; 
	   Led by Argentine striker Leonardo Rodriguez, Universidad de
Chile defeated Concepcion 3-0 to grab second place in the league,
five points below Colo Colo.
	   The two teams are the top contenders for the championship, with
Universidad's remaining schedule giving them a slight advantage.
Universidad will play four of the remaining nine games away, while
Colo Colo will have five.
	   Many fans will be focused on next week's Italian league matchup
featuring two of Chile's biggest stars: Internazionale's Ivan
Zamorano and Lazio's Marcelo Salas.
	   It will be the first meeting of the two dangerous goal scorers
who helped lead Chile in its successful World Cup '98 appearance.
</TEXT>
