<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Vienna </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sampras clears first-round hurdle
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING to fix typo in overline &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   VIENNA, Austria (AP) _ Top-ranked Pete Sampras, who got into the
event thanks to the generosity of Boris Becker, advanced to the
second round of the ATP Vienna tournament Monday.
	   Sampras beat qualifier Jan Kroslak 6-2, 7-5 in the opening round
of the dlrs 800,000 indoor tournament that has seven of the top 10
players.
	   After his early exit from the Swiss indoor last week in Basel,
Sampras asked for a wild card from the organizers in Vienna. But
they turned him down because all wild cards already had been
allocated.
	   Sampras then asked Boris Becker if he could have his wild card
and Becker agreed.
	   ``Pete needs it much more than I do,'' said Becker, who is in
semi-retirement and only plays selected tournaments.
	   Sampras said it was an ``incredible gesture'' by Becker. ``I
don't think you'd find another guy doing that,'' he said. ``I was
practically already on the way home.''
	   The American wants to become the first player to finish the
season as No. 1 for six consecutive years and desperately needs to
increase his margin over No. 2 and U.S. Open champion Patrick
Rafter.
	   In other matches Monday, Cedric Pioline defeated Richard
Fromberg 6-3, 7-6 (9-7), Magnus Norman edged Daniel Vacek 7-5, 6-4,
and Jonas Bjorkman beat David Prinosil 6-4, 7-6 (7-1).
	   (ns)	   
</TEXT>
