<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Primakov confers with executives on economic plans
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. RECASTS, UPDATES thruout with new details. Trims. CHANGES
byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By ANNA DOLGOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov huddled with top
Russian executives Monday to discuss the government's economic
plans, but no comprehensive, long-term strategy was expected to
materialize.
	   The Finance Ministry said Monday it would present a draft of an
emergency budget for the rest of the year to the Cabinet early next
week. But Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov said Sunday that the
government has no comprehensive strategy for rescuing Russia's
economy, and does not even plan to draft one this year.
	   The Russians got more bad news Monday, when the Finance Ministry
announced that the emergency budget will not adjust wages and
pensions to compensate for inflation.
	   Russian consumer prices jumped by 38 percent in September,
following the the effective devaluation of ruble in mid-August.
Inflation was only 0.2 percent in July.
	   Primakov, meanwhile, was to continue his closed-door
consultations on Tuesday, before outlining the government's
economic plans before the upper chamber of Russia's parliament on
Wednesday.
	   Details of the plan are not expected to be made public before
Oct. 20. Zadornov has said the plan would only set out immediate
tasks for the government to implement.
	   Primakov maintains that the government's plans _ and therefore
the future of Russia's economy _ hinge on whether the country gets
foreign aid.
	   But the Russian government's failure to spell out its plans has
forced the International Monetary Fund to postpone a visit by its
delegation to Moscow, said Deputy Finance Minister Oleg Vyugin. The
visit was to have begun Monday.
	   Primakov has made only general statements about his Cabinet's
plans, saying that its priorities are paying off huge backlogs of
state workers' wages and pensions, propping up the banking system
and stabilizing prices.
	   His government has not confirmed reports from the European Union
that Russia is seeking food and medical aid. But former Deputy
Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov said Monday that U.S. officials had
told him the Russian government was also seeking humanitarian aid
from the United States.
	   Deputy Prime Minister Gennady Kulik tried to assuage Russians'
worries about possible food shortages, saying that the country
would continue the food imports that make up nearly half the food
in Russia's stores.
	   ``As to humanitarian aid, it may be extended to the regions....
Government and international organizations are free to hold talks
directly with the regions concerned,'' the Interfax news agency
quoted him as saying.
	   In other economic news Monday:
	   _ The Central Bank ordered private banks to suspend dollar sales
to foreign investors at previously agreed rates until the end of
the year. Because the deals were arranged before the ruble was
effectively devalued on Aug. 17, they would have meant big losses
to Russian banks.
	   _ The ruble closed down against the dollar in slow trading
Monday, in part because of worries over President Boris Yeltsin's
health. Yeltsin cut short his visit to Central Asia on Monday due
to a respiratory infection. On the Moscow Interbank Currency
Exchange, the ruble closed at 16.1 to 16.15 to the dollar, down
from 15.8-16 on Friday.
	   (ad/ji)
</TEXT>
