<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Germany backs airstrikes in Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs; RECASTS and adds defense and foreign ministry comment. &QL; 
 &UR; With Yugoslavia-Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; By TONY CZUCZKA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ In a show of national unity, Chancellor
Helmut Kohl's outgoing Cabinet on Monday committed 14 German jet
fighters to possible NATO strikes in Yugoslavia's Kosovo province
with the approval of Chancellor-elect Gerhard Schroeder.
	   Germany's role in any airstrikes has been in question since the
left's Sept. 27 election victory. But Kohl and Schroeder agreed
during a meeting Monday that the old government should take the
initiative.
	   Deployment of the Tornado fighters must be approved by the
sitting parliament, which will meet Friday. Parliamentary approval
seems assured because both major parties, the Social Democrats and
Kohl's Christian Democrats, largely support committing German
troops.
	   The emphasis on a unified German position that will span the
transition to Schroeder's government was an important signal to
Germany's allies as NATO decides whether to go ahead with strikes.
	   ``There was a desire for political unity by the United States,''
said Schroeder, who is expected to be sworn in as chancellor Oct.
27. Until then, Kohl remains in power.
	   Gaining approval by the sitting parliament allows Germany's
future governing partners _ Schroeder's Social Democrats and the
Greens party _ to skirt a potentially divisive issue.
	   Though the Greens approve of NATO airstrikes, they have rejected
German participation without a clear U.N. mandate. And Schroeder
hinted that a number of Greens members were expected to vote
against participation.
	   But he emphasized after coalition talks with Greens leaders that
both sides broadly agreed on continuity in foreign policy,
including a commitment to NATO that the Greens have rejected in the
past.
	   Schroeder said ``there are absolutely no doubts about the
Greens' reliability in foreign policy.''
	   Schroeder was accompanied in the meeting with Kohl by his likely
foreign minister, Greens' leader Joschka Fisher, a party moderate
who has given his backing to the airstrikes.
	   ``I have to say that in general there was an excellent climate
and awareness of the responsibility both for our country and for
German soldiers during this last phase, when no wrong signals can
be given,'' Defense Minister Volker Ruehe told a press briefing.
	   Ruehe said he believed the deployment would be ``the most
dangerous'' foreign assignment for the German military under NATO
deployment. The Tornados' job would be to take out the
``sophisticated'' Yugoslav air defenses, he said.
 &UR; (tc-cb)
</TEXT>
