<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Debts </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pension, wage debts in Ukraine reach nearly dlrs 2.5 billion
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ Despite government efforts to reduce wage
and pension debts in Ukraine, the debts still amount to nearly dlrs
2.5 billion, Prime Minister Valery Pustovoitenko said Monday.
	   Ukrainian enterprises owe their workers 6.5 billion hryvna (dlrs
1.9 billion) in back wages, with 42.8 percent of the sum owed by
government-run companies and institutions, Pustovoitenko said.
	   The government also owes nearly 2 billion hryvna (dlrs 585
million) to millions of pensioners throughout Ukraine, and the
pension situation remains ``extremely complex,'' he said.
	   At the same time, companies and institutions, including various
state-run companies and ministries, owe the state Pension Fund as
much as 3.1 billion hryvna (dlrs 906 million), Pustovoitenko told a
Cabinet meeting.
	   In recent months, Pustovoitenko has launched a crackdown on
biggest tax dodgers and Pension Fund debtors, including such
measures as bringing the top debtor executives to a tent camp for
purported civil defense training.
	   The crackdown, however, has yielded little result, only
underlining the government's chronic inability to collect taxes and
other budget payments.
	   (sms/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
