<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Accident </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ex-Soviet defense minister injured in car crash
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Former Soviet Defense Minister Sergei Sokolov was
injured Monday when his Volga sedan collided with another vehicle.
	   Sokolov, 88, suffered multiple injuries to his head, chest and a
leg, and was hospitalized in ``moderately serious condition,'' said
a Defense Ministry spokesman who refused to give his name.
	   Police were still investigating who was at fault for the
accident, the spokesman said. It was not known whether anybody else
was injured.
	   Sokolov had been fired as defense minister over a highly
embarrassing incident in 1987, when West German pilot Mathias Rust
entered Soviet airspace in a small plane and flew all the way to
Moscow's Red Square.
	   In 1994, Sokolov headed the 50th Anniversary of Victory Fund _ a
non-government organization that prepared anniversary celebrations
of the Soviet victory over Nazi Germany in World War II.
	   Russian President Boris Yeltsin awarded Sokolov a medal for
``Contribution to the Fatherland'' in 1996.
	   (ad/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
