<SLUG> BC-India-Power Shutdown,0277 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Electricity company shuts down power supply to Indian state
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ An electricity company owned by the
Indian government cut off power to one province that was behind in
paying its bills, and similarly threatened two other states.
	   Residents in the West Bengal state were girding for power
outages after the National Thermal Power Corporation suspended its
supplies from the Farakka power plant in the eastern Indian
province because of arrears of 7.1 billion rupees (dlrs 170
million), The Statesman newspaper said.
	   Indian states currently are between nine and 17 months behind in
payments.
	   The provincial governments buy electricity from the national
utility and sell it to individuals and companies. Rather than
paying their bills, many use the money from consumers' electricity
tariffs to shore up budget deficits.
	   The utility has also threatened to similarly shut down power to
neighboring Bihar, one of India's poorest states, and the coastal
province of Orissa. In all, outstanding dues in eastern India stand
at over 30 billion rupees (dlrs 714 million), The Times of India
reported.
	   Despite the suspension of power supply, West Bengal was nowhere
near a crisis, said officials who hope to overcome the shortfall
from a new unit of a provincial government-owned power station
commissioned Sunday.
	   West Bengal draws over 430 megawatt of power each day from the
NTPC power plant of the 2,000 megawatt needed during peak supply
hours. Officials said there would be a shortage of between 150 and
200 megawatts even after utilizing all electricity sources in the
state.
</TEXT>
