<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Fire,0360 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Forest fires rage for second day in Israel
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos TLV101-102 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Forest fires raged Monday for a second day in
northern Israel, in what are believed to be the largest blazes in
recent history. No fatalities or serious injuries were reported
from those fires or smaller ones burning in central Israel.
	   Firefighters found that one of the fires was started
deliberately but most were caused by carelessness on the part of
picnickers.
	   The biggest blaze was on the slopes of the northern Carmel
range, south of Haifa, Israel's third-biggest city. Firefighters
said it was even bigger than Sunday's blaze in the Carmel Forest
below the neighborhood of Deniya on the outskirts of Haifa.
	   With hot weather and high winds, the flames spread to the
picturesque artists village of Ein Hod, the nearby Arab village of
Ein Chud and the communal village of Nir Etzion. All three villages
were evacuated.
	   Fourteen houses in Ein Hod were destroyed or damaged. Some
historic homes were damaged in Zichron Yaacov.
	   Air force helicopters and civilian crop-spraying aircraft were
brought in to help the firefighters.
	   Smaller fires broke out again in the Carmel Forest below the
Haifa neighborhood of Deniya, where thousands of residents were
evacuated Sunday during what was described then as the country's
biggest fire ever.
	   Forest fires also started in the Jerusalem area, Western Galilee
and around the Arab towns and villages of central Israel. Two
hotels and a number of picnic sites were evacuated.
	   That fire set off some mines in an old minefield but nobody was
hurt. Firefighters believed one of the fires in that area was
started deliberately, Israel radio reported.
	   However investigations so far showed that most of Monday's fires
were caused by picnickers leaving embers smoldering from their
barbecues, Firefighting Commissioner Moshe Vardi said.
	   In central Israel, four Israeli Arabs were arrested on suspicion
of starting fires in the past two weeks in the Wadi Ara area,
Israel radio reported. Police and Arab residents recently clashed
in Wadi Ara over a land dispute.
</TEXT>
