</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Moon Exploration </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian scientists propose Moon exploration project
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russian scientists have designed a plan for
studying the Moon by putting a space station in lunar orbit, but
the project is likely to be grounded by a lack of funding, a
researcher said Monday.
	   The plan calls for putting a small space station in orbit around
the Moon, and using the station to send probes, seismic stations
and other equipment to the Moon, said Erik Galimov, director of
Russia's Vernadsky Institute for Geochemistry and Analytical
Chemistry.
	   A major goal of the experiment would be finding whether there is
water or ice on the Moon, Galimov said, according to the ITAR-Tass
news agency. The question has divided scientists for years, he
said.
	   The project will also focus on collecting information on the
Moon's interior, helping scientists to establish how and when it
was formed.
	   But the project would cost dlrs 50 million, and chances that
Russia's government will agree to finance it are next to nil.
	   The government has repeatedly failed to make its payments for
construction of the international space station, forcing the
project to be delayed several times.
	   (ad/ji)
</TEXT>
