</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Sudan,0460 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sudan, rebels agree to 3-month extension of cease-fire
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ The Sudanese government and rebels have
agreed to extend a cease-fire in a southern province for another
three months to allow humanitarian aid to get to famine-stricken
Sudanese, officials said Monday.
	   The cease-fire in Bahr el-Ghazal will enable the United Nations
and other international aid organizations to feed suffering
Sudanese even after the end of the rainy season, when fighting in
the province usually heats up, the U.N. humanitarian aid
coordinator, Sergio Vieira de Mello, said in a statement.
	   The Sudan People's Liberation Army had said Friday that the
cease-fire _ which will go into effect Wednesday when the previous
one expires _ would cover the provinces of Bahr el-Ghazal and
Western Upper Nile.
	   There was no immediate comment from the SPLA on Monday and no
word on why the cease-fire was confined to only Bahr el-Ghazal.
	   The Sudanese government has said the current cease-fire covers
all of southern Sudan. But a statement from the Foreign Ministry,
faxed to Nairobi, Kenya, from Khartoum, said the extension only
covered Bahr el-Ghazal.
	   The government said it would have preferred a lasting solution
to the 15-year civil war, but settled for a three-month cease-fire
so that badly needed aid could be provided.
	   The rebels, mostly Christian and animist southern Sudanese, have
fought the mainly Arab and Islamic government for 15 years to gain
greater autonomy.
	   The civil war often has led to famine because both rebels and
government-backed militia burn or steal crops to deny food to their
enemies. About 1.5 million people have died in the fighting and
famines.
	   The SPLA has been engaged in a new offensive with government
forces in the southern province of East Equatoria since Sept. 14
and made repeated advances around the town on Juba in recent weeks.
Juba, the second largest town under government control in the
south, is 1,200 kilometers (740 miles) south of Khartoum.
	   De Mello, the U.N. humanitarian coordinator, said he was
particularly concerned about the humanitarian situation in Western
Upper Nile, Bor County and East Equatoria ``and over the need for
the intensive relief operation to continue until next year's
harvest.''
	   Carl Tintsman, coordinator for Operation Lifeline Sudan, a
consortium of aid groups based in Nairobi, welcomed the extension
for Bahr el-Ghazal.
	   ``The cease-fire that has been in effect in Bahr el-Ghazal the
past three months has been critical to stepping up the humanitarian
response in southern Sudan,'' he said. Operation Lifeline Sudan,
however, wanted to see the cease-fire cover a broader area, he
said.
</TEXT>
