<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Mood </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mood is grim as Yugoslavs prepare for the worst
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; By JEFFREY ULBRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ The mood is grim, in Kosovo and
across Yugoslavia.
	   Embassies are closing. Diplomats are fleeing. Observers are
packing up and leaving. Humanitarian organizations await the word
to pull out. And Yugoslavs in Kosovo, Albanians and Serbs, are
loading their guns and waiting for the worst.
	   All eyes were fixed on Brussels on Monday, where NATO
ambassadors were poised to authorize airstrikes, and on Belgrade,
where Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic was deliberating
concessions in talks aimed at halting Serb repression against
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, Serbia's poor southern province.
	   The Serbs here are angry. And they like to carry guns. Not only
do they hate the Albanians for having got them into this fix, they
hate the foreigners whose nations are preparing to pound them with
missiles and bombs.
	   In the hinterlands, where hundreds of ethnic Albanians have been
killed over the past seven months and hundreds of thousands driven
from their homes, forcing many to live in the open under plastic
sheets, the fear is palpable. Though many would welcome NATO
airstrikes, they also are afraid Serb police will exact a terrible
vengeance upon them.
	   Some people, however, just think the West is after the wrong
target.
	   ``I hate Americans,'' said Ljubisa, a civil servant from Pec who
didn't want to give his last name. ``If they have anything against
Slobo, why don't they just shoot him? I have three little kids and
I didn't hurt anybody.''
	   Jasna, 30, who also declined to give her last name, was talking
tough.
	   ``If they bomb, I told my husband to send the kids and me to
Serbia,'' she said. ``Then I'm coming back and we're going to get
even with the Albanians.''
	   The last American, European Union and Russian diplomats from the
Kosovo Diplomatic Observer Mission, sent here in July at the
suggestion of Russian President Boris Yeltsin to monitor the
situation on the ground, pulled out of Kosovo Monday and headed
south for safety Macedonia.
	   In Belgrade, the British, German and Danish embassies closed and
their staffs began the drive to Budapest, Hungary. The American
Embassy was down to 12 people, mostly in support of the Holbrooke
mission.
	   ``For God's sake, let's get it over with, one way or another,''
said anguished Belgrade housewife Milena Popovic, adding that the
uncertainty was worse than anything else.
	   In some districts of the capital, mailboxes were stuffed with
leaflets instructing people on how to recognize air raid sirens by
the length and type of sound and what to do in case of air raids.
	   The independent daily Blic published a poll on where various
politicians intend to be if the bombs start falling.
	   ``If the bombing actually happens, I'll be at the Students
Square,'' Blic quoted Democratic Party leader Zoran Djindjic as
saying. ``Let NATO and Clinton explain to their people how and why
they killed a democrat.''
	   Social Democrat leader Vuk Obradovic said he planned to be in
uniform, serving his country by ``defending the dignity and honor
of its people.''
	   Near the ethnic Albanian village of Gollubovic, west of
Pristina, 66-year-old Qazim Berisha stood outside his temporary
shelter made of dried cornstalks. He and 27 of his relatives have
been on the move for the past four months. Two of his sons have
been abducted by Serbs.
	   ``If Milosevic comes to his senses, it will be good,'' said
Berisha. ``We'd all like to have peace. But if he doesn't want to
come to his senses, we would like NATO to help us because we are
dying.''
	   Back in Pristina, Afrim Jerlliu, 42, an ethnic Albanian
schoolteacher, said somebody has to stop the bloodshed.
	   ``No one can do it in Pristina and Belgrade,'' he said. ``No one
has done it since 1989 when Kosovo's autonomy was suspended. The
international community and NATO can do it. Only a tough lesson
like that will be able to stop Serb brutality in Kosovo.''
	   One focus of Serb anger is the Grand Hotel in Pristina, where
journalists from several NATO countries are staying: Italians,
Britons, Americans and others.
	   Every night, a crowd of drunks gathers outside, screaming
obscenities at the reporters inside, threatening to kill them and
smash their cars. Eventually they are chased away by official and
secret Serb police, stationed at the hotel to keep an eye on the
foreigners.
	   (av/ih/bel/ju/dc)
</TEXT>
