<SLUG> BC-Czech-Refugees </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Afghan refugees get into Prague onboard of a Moldavian plane
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) _ More than 100 Afghan refugees were
detained by Czech police Monday after they flew into the country
illegally aboard a Moldavian Airlines plane, TV Nova reported.
	   According to police sources quoted by the station, 52 men, 22
women and 31 children arrived onboard of an Moldavian Airlines
flight in the morning and tried to enter the country without travel
documents.
	   The refugees reportedly paid dlrs 5,000 per adult and dlrs 2,500
per child to unspecified organizers just to get to Prague.
	   After Czech authorities refused to allow them into transit, the
passengers forced a 7-year old child out of the plane in protest.
	   They were all then escorted out of the plane and will be offered
a place in a refugee camp in northern Bohemia, the television said.
	   Czech republic is a busy transit country for refugees from Asia
and the Balkans usually looking for ways to penetrate the border
into neighboring Germany and continue their journey into western
Europe in search of a better life.
	   (oh/reid)
</TEXT>
