<HEADLINE>
Greenpeace activists block ships bound for Turkish chemical
</HEADLINE>
factory &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   IZMIR, Turkey (AP) _ A boat loaded with Greenpeace activists
blocked ships bound for a Turkish chemical plant Monday, leaving
only when Turkey's coast guard allegedly threatened to open fire.
	   The activists were trying to interrupt production of polyvinyl
chloride, better known as PVC, at the Petkim factory near the
Aegean port city of Izmir.
	   Twenty-two protesters sank concrete blocks at the entrance of
the port and circled the docks of the plant, Petkim said in a
statement.
	   After an eight-hour standoff, the Greenpeace vessel Sirius was
forced to leave when the coast guard threatened to open fire,
Greenpeace activist Tolga Temuce said.
	   Temuce, speaking from the Sirius, said the ship was currently
being forced to sail to Izmir by the coast guard, where the
activists expected to be detained.
	   Petkim is Turkey's largest producer of PVC.
	   Greenpeace has been protesting its use in children's products,
saying it is a danger to health and to the environment.
	   (sh-ht)
</TEXT>
