<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Syria, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkey cautiously welcomes Syrian efforts over Kurdish rebel
</HEADLINE>
crisis &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo IST101 &QL; 
 &UR; EDs: RECASTS to UPDATE with quotes from Turkish leaders, Egyptian
foreign minister, Kurdish rebel leader, ADDS photo line, byline &QL; 
 &UR; By HARMONIE TOROS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ Turkey said Monday that Syria appeared to
have moved toward meeting its demands in a confrontation over
Kurdish rebels _ the first sign of a breakthrough in a 2-week-old
crisis that has threatened war between the two neighbors.
	   According to Foreign Minister Ismail Cem, Syria relayed a
message Monday through Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, whose
government has been trying to mediate the crisis.
	   Cem said the message ``indicates that there is an effort on the
Syrian side to meet the concerns that we have raised.''
	   ``We have regarded this with a positive interest and we are
pursuing it,'' Cem said, adding that ``based on past experiences
with Syria we have to be cautious. We have to see the
implementation.''
	   Turkey accuses Syria of sheltering and supporting Kurd rebels
responsible for cross-border attacks. Two weeks ago, saying its
patience had run out, it suggested it might carry out an
unspecified military operation.
	   Syria denies the accusations. Its leaders have had little to say
about the negotiations, other than that they believe the dispute
can be resolved peacefully.
	   Turkey's Sabah daily claimed Monday that Syria had given in to
Turkish demands and agreed to end its alleged support for the
Turkish Kurd rebels.
	   The rebels are fighting for autonomy for Kurds in Turkey's
southeast. The conflict has killed 37,000 people since fighting
started in 1984.
	   The German-based Kurdish news agency, DEM, quoted rebel leader
Abdullah Ocalan as saying Turkey has stepped up its attacks on the
Kurds during the dispute.
	   ``It is our patience that has run out,'' DEM quoted Ocalan as
saying.
	   Turkish officials said they were planning maneuvers along its
Syrian border in November. There have been unconfirmed reports of a
Turkish troop buildup along the border.
	   (sh-sf)
</TEXT>
