w1768 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Tennis-Europea     10-12 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-European Championships </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Davenport ousts Hingis from world No. 1 spot
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ERICA BULMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) _ A new era in women's tennis dawned on
Monday, and Lindsay Davenport, the new world number one, missed it
by sleeping in.
	   The 22-year-old American officially took over as the world's top
player from Martina Hingis on Monday morning at the European
Championships, but wasn't motivated to get up and play tennis.
	   ``I woke up late this morning and I didn't feel like hitting a
ball,'' said Davenport, the winner of five titles this season,
including the U.S Open. ``That was my first though as No. 1.''
	   But Davenport's thoughts will soon turn to defending her
European title and solidifying her place atop the rankings.
	   The soft-spoken American, who climbed to the top almost
unnoticed until she was at the summit, will not play her first
match until Wednesday, when she faces French qualifier Julie
Halard-Decugis.
	   The modest American is quickly discovering the demands placed on
the number one player, holding audience with a room full of
reporters and TV crews Monday afternoon before rushing off to a
photo shoot.
	   Although comfortable with the media, Davenport cherishes her
time out of the limelight, but will have to get used to the
attention and the thrill attached to her new status.
	   ``It's one of those things you feel deep in your stomach and it
makes you a little emotional,'' said Davenport. ``But you have to
move on. You've got to play tennis day in and day out and you have
to keep trying to improve.''
	   Even though Davenport began her reign on the Swiss star's home
turf, she won't have the opportunity to face the 18-year-old in
Zurich, with Hingis pulling out due to a strained ankle.
	   Davenport brought to an end Hingis's 80 week stay at the top of
the rankings, which dated back to March 1997, when she became the
youngest player ever to hold the position.
	   Davenport's task at the dlrs 1 million European Championship has
been made even easier with world No.3 Jana Novotna and No.6 Monica
Seles also pulling due to injury. World No. 4 Arantza
Sanchez-Vicario will also be absent.
	   As a result, Davenport's main opposition will come from
compatriot Venus Williams, seeded second, who also has her sights
sets on the No. 1 spot.
	   France's Sandrine Testud, who beat out Davenport in the final at
Filderstadt on Sunday, will be looking for a second consecutive
title.
	   Fifth-seed Patty Schnyder, who won five title this season and
reached the final of the Grand Slam Cup, will carry Swiss hopes in
Hingis's absence.
	   Regardless of Davenport's result in Zurich, Hingis's withdrawal
means the American cannot be overtaken and is guaranteed at least
another week as the No. 1.
	   ``I'm very disappointed,'' said Hingis, who fell from the top
spot after a quarterfinal loss to Dominique Van Roost in
Filderstadt. ``But I consulted the doctor, and he advised me not to
play this week.''
	   Davenport holds a 396 point lead over Hingis, who plans only to
compete in two more tournaments this season, Philadelphia and the
season-ending Chase Championships. The American, on the otherhand,
plans to play in Moscow, Philadelphia and New York.
	   Davenport is only the eighth player to attain the number one
ranking since the inception of the WTA rankings in 1975.
	   ``You always look up to the No.1 players in the world and think
what great players they are or were,'' said Davenport. ``I'm very
honoured to be a part of that. I hope to continue a bit longer at
No. 1 and will keep trying to stay at the top.''
	   Davenport is the third American-born player to join the
exclusive club, and the first since Chris Evert in 1985.
	   Martina Navratilova and Monica Seles, who both took American
citizenship, are also part of the club, as well as American Tracy
Austin, Germany's Steffi Graf, Hingis, and Sanchez-Vicario of
Spain.
	   ``Making it to the top was never really an obsession of mine and
I never thought I'd get to number one in the world,'' said
Davenport. ``I've definitely been criticized for that with people
calling it lack of drive and confidence.
	   ``But to get to No.1 and be in the top-10 for four of five years
now, obviously there's some competitiveness and drive in me,''
reasoned Davenport. ``I just don't think you have to come out and
say I'm the greatest, no one can beat me, I'm going to be here a
long time.''
 &UR; (eb)	   
</TEXT>
