<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-East Europe-Mrs Clinton </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mrs. Clinton encourages Bulgarian businesswomen, meets Czech
</HEADLINE>
leaders &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: AMs. INCORPORATES Bulgaria-Mrs Clinton, reflecting move to
Prague &QL; 
 &UR; By NADIA RYBAROVA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) _ Touring Eastern Europe on Monday,
U.S. first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton started the day with a pep
talk to Bulgarian businesswomen and spent a rainy afternoon
debating world affairs with Czech political leaders.
	   Avoiding the press as she has throughout the brief overseas
tour, visited President Vaclav Havel and his wife Dagmar at their
private villa and spent a quiet hour chatting by the fireplace,
ahead of a final day of speeches and public appearances.
	   Before arriving in the Czech Republic on the second day of the
four-day trip to promote women's rights and civil society, Mrs.
Clinton met with businesswomen at a Sofia bakery and discussed the
challenges of running a business in the new Bulgaria.
	   ``We're very impressed by the reform effort and the difficult
decisions that your government is making on behalf of the future,''
she told the women.
	   Mrs. Clinton also accepted an offer to allow her book ``It Takes
a Village'' to be translated and published into Bulgarian.
Businesswoman Iren Komitova suggested the proceeds go to the
American University in Bulgaria's southwestern city of Blagoevgrad.
	   Mrs. Clinton met with some 500 students at the American College
of Sofia, where she also toured the school, talked to teachers and
alumni and looked at their computer laboratory.
	   ``I saw the future of Bulgaria in the eyes of the brilliant and
dynamic students I met at the American College of Sofia,'' she
said.
	   ``That school is but one example of the ties of trade,
investment, culture and friendship between our two countries.''
	   The college, established in 1860 while Bulgaria was still under
Turkish rule, was closed down in 1942 and turned into a police
training academy after the communists came to power. College alumni
were persecuted, but the school's book collection was preserved at
the local monastery and the college was resurrected in 1992.
	   The first lady flew later Monday to Prague to meet with Czech
leaders and speak at a conference organized by President Vaclav
Havel and Nobel laureate Elie Wiesel.
	   She is scheduled to deliver a keynote speech on the future of
civil society at the conference Tuesday morning before leaving for
Washington later in the day.
	   After her arrival in Prague, Mrs. Clinton met briefly with Czech
Premier Milos Zeman.
	   Czech television reported the first lady discussed economic
issues with Zeman and thanked his government for allowing
U.S.-funded Radio Free Europe-Radio Liberty to broadcast from Czech
territory.
	   Together with the Havels, she then attended a
multi-denominational service at Prague's gothic St. Vitus
Cathedral.
	   She and the Czech president were among those who lit ``candles
of hope'' at the end of the prayers before departing for a gala
dinner at the Prague Castle.
	   (oh/vz/dc)
</TEXT>
