<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Italy-Doping, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Players decide against strike but call for stiffer anti-doping
</HEADLINE>
measures &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS, ADDS byline &QL; 
 &UR; By PIERO VALSECCHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MILAN, Italy (AP) _ Italian professional soccer players on
Monday called for random blood tests to protect their health _ and
their reputations, jeopardized by a spreading doping scandal.
	   At the same time, the players associations, representing players
from the three major divisions, dropped the threat of a strike to
protest the handling of the doping investigations, which it claims
violates the players' privacy.
	   A player walkout _ which has happened only once before in
Italy's soccer history _ could have stopped the Serie A and second
and third division matches for weeks.
	   Lawyer Sergio Campana, president of the players association,
strongly protested media leaks about alleged involvement of some
players and clubs in the scandal.
	   ``Until the conclusion of the investigations, it's unfair of the
media to name players as doping suspects,'' Campana said.
	   He added the association decided to give priority to stiffer
anti-doping measures intended to protect players from
administration of forbidden substances.
	   Several clubs have admitted use of creatine and other
supplements, which are legal but whose long-term effects are
uncertain.
	   ``There could be drug abuse without the players knowing of it,''
said Dr. Piero Volpi, physician for Internazionale of Milan, who
attended the association meeting in a Milan hotel.
	   Campana said the Association will urge establishment of random
blood tests during the week and tests of urine and blood at the end
of matches.
	   ``The Italian (soccer) federation could enforce our demands in
the short term,'' said Campana, who also made public the request of
the association for a medical case sheet for each player including
all medicines given by team doctors.
	   The Milan meeting, attended by leading association members such
as internationals Demetrio Albertini of AC Milan and Inter-Milan
captain Giuseppe Bergomi, capped weeks of allegations about a
doping scandal involving some prestigious players and clubs.
	   It started in summer, when Roma's Czech coach Zdenek Zeman
suggested systematic drug abuse by some clubs and expressed
amazement at the muscle growth of some past and present players of
rival club Juventus of Turin.
	   Since then, magistrates in Rome, Turin and other cities have
been investigating the matter.
	   Ugo Longo, the chief anti-doping prosecutor of Italy's Olympic
Committee resigned Monday, citing difficult work conditions
following the closure of the committee's laboratory.
	   The lab was shut, and its chief Emilio Gasbarrone fired, after
the International Olympic Committee deemed the facility
unsatisfactory.
	   Mario Pescante, president of Italy's Olympic Committee, resigned
in the wake of the scandal.
	    &UR; (pv)
</TEXT>
