<SLUG> BC-Israel-Fire, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Forest fires rage for third day in Israel
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS to clarify third sted second day, ADDS quote from police
chief, UPGRADES attribution for arrests, ADDS byline &QL; 
 &UR; By JACK KATZENELL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 
 &UR; AP Photos

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Forest fires raged for the third consecutive
day Monday in northern and central Israel. One of them was
described as the biggest in the country's history, but no
fatalities or serious injury were reported.
	   Firefighters suspected that one of the fires was started
deliberately but most were caused by carelessness on the part of
picnickers.
	   No official count was issued of the number of fires but at least
ten big ones were reported.
	   The biggest blaze was on the slopes of the Carmel range south of
Haifa. Firefighters said it was even bigger than Sunday's blaze in
the Carmel Forest below the neighborhood of Deniya on the outskirts
of Haifa, Israel's third-biggest city. However no large towns were
threatened in Monday's fires.
	   With hot weather and high winds, the flames spread to the
picturesque artists village of Ein Hod, the nearby Arab village of
Ein Chud and the communal village of Nir Etzion. All three villages
were evacuated.
	   Fourteen houses in Ein Hod were destroyed or damaged. Some
historic homes were damaged in Zichron Yaacov.
	   Air force helicopters and civilian crop-spraying light aircraft
were brought in to help the fire-fighters.
	   Smaller fires broke out again in the Carmel Forest below Deniya,
where thousands of residents were evacuated Sunday during what was
described then as the country's biggest fire ever. About 5,000
dunams (1,250 acres) of natural vegetation were destroyed in
Sunday's fire but no figure was available for Monday's.
	   Forest fires also started in the Jerusalem area, Western Galilee
and around the Arab towns and villages of central Israel. Two
hotels and a number of picnic sites were evacuated.
	   In the Jerusalem area one fire set off some mines in an old
minefield but nobody was hurt. A second fire in the Jerusalem hills
was started deliberately, police and firefighters believed, but the
others were probably caused by carelessness on the part of
picnickers who left embers smoldering after their barbecue.
	   ``So far we believe most of the fires were caused by negligence.
We suspect that the fire in the Jerusalem hills was caused by
arson,'' said Police Commissioner Yehuda Wilk.
	   Firefighters said a long spell of dry weather also contributed
to causing the fires.
	   In central Israel four Israeli Arabs were arrested on suspicion
of starting fires over the past two weeks in the Wadi Ara area,
Wilk said. Police and Arab residents recently clashed in Wadi Ara
over a land dispute.
 &UR; jk 	   
