<HEADLINE>
More than 100,000 left homeless by flooding in Nigeria
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ More than 100,000 people have been left
homeless in western Nigeria after torrential weekend rains
overwhelmed two dams, the Nigerian news agency said Monday.
	   Dozens of villages were submerged by the flooding and bodies
could still be seen floating Monday in flood waters in western
Kwara state, some 375 kilometers (225 miles) northeast of Lagos,
the news agency said.
	   The chairman of the local government, Yahaya Yusuf, called for
urgent financial and material assistance, saying authorities were
struggling to find housing for the displaced people.
	   There were no immediate reports of serious injuries or death,
though two people died in Lagos on Sunday because of heavy
downpours there and hundreds of homes were destroyed. The two
people were killed when a mud home collapsed over them, the agency
reported.
