<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Auto Racing-San Remo Rally </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Makinen leads after first stage
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SAN REMO, Italy (AP) _ Defending world champion Tommi Makinen
led his top rival Carlos Sainz by 30.7 seconds after the first
stage of the San Remo auto rally on Monday.
	   The Finnish driver, in a Mitsubishi, completed the first day of
the 11th World Championship event in one hour, 22 minutes, 45.6
seconds, beating Piero Liatti's Subaru by 3.7 seconds.
	   France's Didier Auriol drove his Toyota to third place, with a
gap of 21.1 seconds.
	   Sainz, who leads Makinen and Britain's Colin McRae 47 to 38
points in the championship standings, came in fourth, in a Toyota.
	   McRae was a distant ninth in a Subaru, more than one minute
behind Makinen.
	   While the battle for the world title still was wide open with
three races left, Gustavo Trelles of Uruguay clinched the Group-N
FIA title for the third straight year as his closest rival, Manfred
Stohl, withdrew shortly after the start Monday.
	   The Italian race ends in this riviera resort Wednesday.
Tuesday's second stage of 173 kilometers includes 10 special
trials.
	   The rally of Australia on Nov. 5-8 and Britain's RAC on Nov.
21-24 will complete the championship round.
 &UR; (pv)
</TEXT>
