w1794 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Kosovo 4thLd-Writethru   10-12 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Kosovo, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Primakov warns NATO against airstrikes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS, UPDATES with Ivanov quotes, ADDS Primakov
conversation with Prodi, Russian observers leave Kosovo. Trims. &QL; 
 &UR; By JUDITH INGRAM &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ As Russian officials warned against NATO
airstrikes in Yugoslavia, the defense minister offered military
observation planes on Monday as part of a last-ditch political
solution to the crisis in Kosovo province.
	   NATO bombardment ``will throw relations between NATO and Russia
far back, will jeopardize many of the cooperation accords that have
been reached in recent years,'' Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov
said in a telephone conversation with Italy's acting premier,
Romano Prodi, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
	   Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov echoed the warning, telling
Russia's ORT television that NATO's decision to enter final
preparations for airstrikes was ``very dangerous.''
	   The decision ``will carry us to the red line that, from our
point of view, shouldn't be crossed, because it could entail the
most serious consequences,'' Ivanov said.
	   Russia vehemently opposes airstrikes against Yugoslavia, a
traditional ally with which it shares a Slavic heritage and
Orthodox religion, and has been lobbying for a negotiated solution
to the crisis in the ethnic Albanian-dominated province of Kosovo.
	   Even as NATO appeared poised to launch airstrikes, Defense
Minister Igor Sergeyev told reporters that Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic had agreed to the stationing of 1,500 observers
in Kosovo, and said Russia would consider taking part, the Interfax
news agency reported.
	   ``We are prepared to provide our planes for international
control of Yugoslav air space,'' he was quoted as saying. No one
was available for comment at the Defense Ministry, and no other
details of Sergeyev's statement were provided.
	   Earlier Monday, Boris Yeltsin's spokesman Dmitry Yakushkin said
the president was ``cautiously optimistic'' that chances for a
peaceful solution have ``slightly increased'' because of U.S. envoy
Richard Holbrooke's extended talks with Milosevic, the ITAR-Tass
news agency reported.
	   Yakushkin said the Kosovo crisis was one of the reasons Yeltsin
had agreed to cut short his trip to Central Asia. Doctors ordered
him to return to Moscow for health reasons.
	   Sergeyev also expressed optimism, but he told reporters that the
government was looking at several alternative reactions to possible
NATO airstrikes against Yugoslavia, including a change in Russia's
relationship with the western alliance, Interfax said.
	   Russian Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov warned that
Russia would break the arms embargo and annul all agreements with
NATO if the alliance launches airstrikes to force Serbia, the
leading republic in Yugoslavia, to end its violent crackdown on
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
	   ``NATO should not think that Russia is weak and that its
historical geopolitical interests in the Balkans can be
disregarded,'' Zyuganov said before a meeting with Yugoslavia's
acting ambassador in Russia, Radoslav Paikovic.
	   Paikovic said that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's
brother Borislav had been named ambassador to Moscow, Interfax
said.
	   Cautioning that Russia has ``commitments to an ally in the
Balkans,'' Zyuganov said that if war breaks out following NATO
attacks ``other laws go into effect, including the laws of allied
relations.''
	   Some Russian media sources have reported that the country's
state arms exporter, Rosvooruzheniye, has already violated the
embargo by supplying land-to-air missiles to Yugoslavia.
	   But the company's general director, Oleg Sidorenko, denied the
report Monday, Interfax said.
	   Russia has recalled its representative to NATO and its
ambassador to Belgium, where NATO has its headquarters, for
consultations. Foreign Ministry official Vladimir Chizov said their
return to Brussels will depend on developments, the Interfax news
agency reported Monday.
	   Ten Russian observers left Kosovo after the government ordered
them home, the RTR television station reported.
	   (pvs/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
