w1797 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Tennis-Europea     10-12 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-European Championships,0471 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Davenport ousts Hingis from world No. 1 spot
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ERICA BULMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) _ A new era in women's tennis dawned on
Monday, and Lindsay Davenport, the new world No. 1, missed it by
sleeping in.
	   The 22-year-old American officially took over as the world's top
player from Switzerland's Martina Hingis when the rankings were
released Monday morning. She got the top spot based on her
performance at the Porsche Grand Prix in Filderstadt, Germany,
where she reached the finals.
	   Davenport, playing at the European Championships in Zurich,
didn't feel like celebrating by playing tennis.
	   ``I woke up late this morning and I didn't feel like hitting a
ball,'' said Davenport, the winner of five titles this season,
including the U.S Open. ``That was my first thought as No. 1.''
	   Davenport will not play her first match until Wednesday, when
she faces French qualifier Julie Halard-Decugis.
	   ``Making it to the top was never really an obsession of mine and
I never thought I'd get to No. 1 in the world,'' said Davenport.
	   ``You always look up to the No.1 players in the world and think
what great players they are or were,'' said Davenport. ``I'm very
honored to be a part of that. I hope to continue a bit longer at
No. 1 and will keep trying to stay at the top.''
	   Even though Davenport began her reign on Hingis' home turf, she
won't have the opportunity to face the 18-year-old in Zurich, with
Hingis pulling out due to a strained ankle.
	   Hingis' withdrawal means Davenport cannot be overtaken and is
guaranteed at least another week as the No. 1.
	   ``I'm very disappointed,'' said Hingis, who fell from the top
spot after a quarterfinal loss to Dominique Van Roost in
Filderstadt. ``But I consulted the doctor, and he advised me not to
play this week.''
	   Hingis had spent 80 weeks at the top of the rankings, dating
from March 1997, when she became the youngest player ever to hold
the position.
	   Davenport's task at the dlrs 1 million European Championship has
been made even easier with world No. 3 Jana Novotna and No. 6
Monica Seles also pulling out due to injury. World No. 4 Arantxa
Sanchez-Vicario will also be absent.
	   As a result, Davenport's main opposition will come from
compatriot Venus Williams, seeded second, who also has her sights
set on the No. 1 spot.
	   France's Sandrine Testud, who beat out Davenport in the final at
Filderstadt on Sunday, will be looking for a second consecutive
title.
	   Fifth-seed Patty Schnyder, who won five title this season and
reached the final of the Grand Slam Cup, will carry Swiss hopes in
Hingis' absence.
	   Davenport is only the eighth player to hold the No. 1 ranking
since the inception of the WTA rankings in 1975.
</TEXT>
