<BODY>
<SLUG> C-Yugoslavia-Kosovo UPDATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Albanian leader welcomes reports Milosevic agreed to monitors
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ A top ethnic Albanian leader in
strife-torn Kosovo welcomed indications late Monday that Yugoslav
president was about to accept international monitors in the
province.
	   ``International monitoring could prove useful and provide a way
out of the Kosovo crisis without further war,'' Fehmi Agani, head
of the ethnic Albanian team set up to negotiate with Belgrade
authorities, told The Associated Press.
	   Just as U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke ended his marathon talks
with president Slobodan Milosevic and left Belgrade to brief NATO,
Russian defense minister Igor Sergeyev told journalists in Moscow
that Milosevic had agreed to allow 1,500 international observers to
monitor compliance with U.N. demands to halt the Serb crackdown in
Kosovo.
	   ``If Milosevic really accepts an international monitoring force,
it would create a position of equilibrium in which the two sides
can then negotiate,'' Agani said.
	   ``A monitoring force would annul Milosevic's war gains and open
up an opportunity for dialogue on an equal basis. Only such
dialogue can have a chance to succeed,'' Agani concluded.
	   According to Agani, Milosevic had attempted by waging war in
Kosovo, to create an upper-hand position ahead of talks with Kosovo
Albanians.
	   (ih/kk)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
