<SLUG> BC-NATO-Kosovo-UPDATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With NATO-Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Holbrooke arrives to brief NATO ambassadors on latest Yugoslav
talks &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke arrived
here Monday evening to brief the NATO allies on his Kosovo peace
efforts.
	   He arrived at the Brussels airport at 1845GMT and headed for the
NATO complex about a mile (1.5 kilometers) away.
	   Holbrooke came here from marathon talks with Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic in Belgrade amid indications a breakthrough was
near in talks about ending the violence in Kosovo and thus avert
NATO air strikes.
	   Holbrooke was to return for more talks in Belgrade on Tuesday.
	   Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev said in Moscow Milosevic
has agreed to allow 1,500 international observers to monitor
compliance with U.N. demands to halt the crackdown in Kosovo.
	   Holbrooke met here with the ambassadors of the 16 NATO nations
who have been meeting daily to discuss the Kosovo crisis.
	   Despite reported progress on the diplomatic front, NATO was
still expected to approve the last military step needed to launch
airstrikes against the Serbs, a NATO official said Monday.
	   They planned to transfer command over the airplanes and other
hardware necessary for an airstrike to Supreme Allied Commander
Wesley K. Clark and authorize its deployment over Yugoslavia.
 &UR; (rw)	   
</TEXT>
