<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Clinton Survey </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Clinton's popularity rises in Germany
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ Despite President Clinton's
involvement in the Monika Lewinsky affair, his popularity as a
politician has grown in Germany from 55 to 67 percent, a reputable
German polling institute said Monday.
	   The poll, which surveyed 1,129 people between Sept. 16-22,
showed that of those asked, only 8 percent said they had a bad
opinion of Clinton as a politician, compared to 17 percent in a
poll taken at the beginning of September.
	   Twenty-five percent of those asked had no opinion in the latest
poll, compared to 28 percent in the earlier survey, the Allensbach
polling institute said.
	   The institute said that those Germans surveyed who approved of
Clinton were most impressed with the steadfastness he has shown in
continuing to do his job under a tough pressure situation.
	   Although the survey ended the day after Clinton's video-taped
questioning by a grand jury was broadcast on international
television, the institute said it felt that the positive opinion of
the American president would remain steady.
	   While no margin of error was given for the latest poll,
Allensbach usually claims a plus or minus 3 percent for a survey of
that size.
	   (ms-gb)
</TEXT>
