<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Shipyard Blast, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Three killed in shipyard explosion
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RAISES death toll to 3, ADDS background on Filippov. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ At least three people were killed and three
injured Monday in a gas explosion at a Russian shipyard, the
ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
	   The blast at the Admiralty Shipyard in St. Petersburg also
sparked a blaze that took more than two hours to extinguish. Rescue
teams continued searching for victims into the night, ITAR-Tass
reported.
	   The report, which cited sources close to the shipyard
administration, said that the dead including a woman and two men
who had worked at the shipyard. The three injured were also
workers, ITAR-Tass said, citing local emergency officials.
	   Meanwhile, city prosecutors on Monday were carrying out a probe
into another explosion that occurred in St. Petersburg over the
weekend.
	   Dmitry Filippov, the head of the financial company Rosko, was
badly wounded by a bomb explosion at the entrance of his apartment
building on Saturday. He is in critical condition in a city
hospital.
	   His predecessor in the job was shot and killed two years ago.
	   Filippov also serves as chairman of the board of Menatep Bank in
St. Petersburg and as chairman of the board of bankers and
industrialists, a local government organization.
	   Until 1993, he was head of the St. Petersburg Tax Inspectorate
and the St. Petersburg Fuel Company. The energy sector in St.
Petersburg is widely believed to be infiltrated by organized
criminal groups.
	   Contract shootings and bombings have become customary in Russia
as mobsters wage turf battles and fight for control over profitable
businesses.
	   (pvs/str/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
