<DOCNO> APW19981012.1061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 10/12/1998 15:20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1850 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Turkey-Balkan-Summit 1stLd-Writethru   10-12 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Balkan-Summit, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkey and Greece join forces on Kosovo, but unable to talk about
</HEADLINE>
own disputes &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: AMs, UPDATES with Yilmaz meeting Simitis, no headway on Greek
Turkish disputes, INCORPORATES BC-Turkey-Balkan Summit-Yugoslavia,
RECASTS throughout, CHANGES byline &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos Available &QL; 
 &UR; By PATRICK QUINN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ANTALYA, Turkey (AP) _ Traditional enemies Greece and Turkey
united Monday to pressure Yugoslavia into making concessions on
Kosovo, but the two neighbors failed to make any progress on
disputes which could lead the two NATO allies to war.
	   ``We discussed our bilateral relations and found that we have
problems,'' Greek Premier Costas Simitis said after his meeting
Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz. ``This is a known phenomenon
in Greek-Turkish relations and I hope that one day we may be able
to overcome these difficulties.''
	   Solving their own intractable problems is important if the two
countries hope to set an example for other leaders gathered in this
Mediterranean resort, and help some in the turbulent region realize
their dream of European Union and NATO membership. Prime ministers
from Bulgaria, Macedonia and Romania are at the two-day summit as
are the foreign minister of Albania and observers from Bosnia and
Croatia.
	   Simitis said they did not discuss the one issue which could lead
the two NATO allies to conflict this year: the deployment of
Russian-made S-300 missiles by Greek Cypriots on the war-divided
island.
	   ``The S-300 were not discussed at all, but I referred to
Cyprus,'' Simitis added.
	   Turkey has said it will use military force to prevent the
installation of the missiles, an action which Athens has said will
translate into war. A clash between the region's two most powerful
countries would make the Kosovo crisis pale by comparison.
	   Cyprus is an issue on which Turkey does not fool around. It
invaded and occupied its northern third in 1974 in the wake of an
abortive Athens-backed coup by Greek-Cypriot supporters of union
with Greece. It retains more than 30,000 combat troops in the
Turkish Cypriot breakaway state, recognized only by Ankara.
	   Turkey's apparent determination to start a war with military
powerhouse Syria over its harboring of Turkish Kurdish insurgents
is indicative of the no-nonsense approach taken by its military,
which essentially pulls Ankara's foreign policy strings.
	   Simitis and Yilmaz did however discuss their countries'
longstanding disputes in the Aegean Sea, which have twice led them
to the brink of war in the past 11 years, but failed to reach any
consensus about how to deal with them.
	   ``I believe that any discussion is useful. It may not solve
problems but contributes to there being better information between
the two sides and a better understanding of solving problems,''
Simitis said in an effort to find a positive note.
	   But the two premiers did find common ground in their effort to
convince Yugoslavia to accept a request by U.S. envoy Richard
Holbrooke that President Slobodan Milosevic agree to an expanded
international monitoring mission in Kosovo.
	   ``The climate seems positive to find a solution without having
to resort to war action,'' Simitis said.
	   Turkey and Greece also spent the entire day pressuring Yugoslav
Premier Momir Bulatovic to accept a reference to Kosovo in their
joint statement and avert his country's political ouster from
future joint Balkan initiatives.
	   But as Bulatovic earlier in the day railed against NATO and the
international community before the frustrated Balkan leaders, he
failed to look out the window and see what was coming.
	   In the distance the French aircraft carrier Foch was building up
steam and moving across this picturesque bay on a journey towards
the Adriatic Sea and the Yugoslav coast to join an assembling NATO
armada.
	    &UR; pq-sf
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Turkey-Balkan-Summit, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
