<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Kuwait-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cohen says Gulf allies receptive to missile defense system
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP photo available
 &UR; By DIANA ELIAS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UDAIRI RANGE, Kuwait (AP) _ U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen
said Monday that Washington's Gulf allies have been receptive to
the idea of a regional missile defense system.
	   Cohen said that such a system has become ``imperative'' to
protect civilians and U.S. soldiers from the threat of missiles
from countries such as Iran.
	   He said the United States wants its allies to help fund the
development of anti-missile systems or ``cooperate in the future as
far as deployment is concerned.''
	   ``The response I think has been quite positive,'' Cohen told
reporters after visiting hundreds of American troops training at
this desert outpost some 40 kilometers (25 miles) from the Iraqi
border.
	   Cohen visited Bahrain, Qatar, the United Arab Emirates and Oman
before arriving in Kuwait Monday. He travels later to Saudi Arabia.
	   The U.S. Theater High-Altitude Area Defense missile program or
THAAD has cost so far some dlrs 3.2 billion.
	   It has suffered five successive test failures, and top U.S.
officials have been considering whether to cancel it.
	   THAAD is supposed to be an improvement on the Patriot missile
system that was used during the 1991 Gulf War.
	   Cohen has called for a continuation of the program, saying an
anti-missile system is needed to protect soldiers from long-range
missiles.
	   Kuwaiti and U.S. troops have conducted scores of military
exercises since the end of the 1991 Gulf War that forced Iraqi
soldiers from Kuwait.
 &UR; de-lm 	   
</TEXT>
