<SLUG> BC-Italy-Benetton-Child Labor </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Benetton's Turkish licensee says it's examining child labor
</HEADLINE>
allegations &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Benetton's Turkish licensee said Monday it was
suspending all dealings with an Istanbul factory accused of
employing children as young as 9 years old, Italy's ANSA news
service reported.
	   Bogazici Ready Wear said it had begun an investigation into the
allegations, raised by a Turkish textile workers group.
	   The factory employs children between the ages of 9 and 13 and
pays them less than $90 a month, making clothing under the name of
the Italian-based clothing manufacturer and retailer, alleged
Dervis Kaplan, leader of the textile workers group.
	   ``This scandal should cease,'' Italy's Corriere della Sera daily
quoted Kaplan as saying.
	   Benetton's offices in Turkey did not immediately return calls
for comment late Monday.
	   According to Corriere della Sera, Benetton responded, ``If it's
true, we will intervene. Our Turkish partner, in fact, guaranteed
us in writing it would respect the laws on labor.''
	   Bogazici Ready Wear said it had suspended dealings with the
factory at the request of an Italian textile group.
	   (ek)
