<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Closure,0183 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israel to ease blockade of Palestinian areas
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israel on Tuesday will ease the blockade of
Palestinian areas that it imposed on October 2, the army spokesman
announced.
	   As of 2 a.m. (midnight GMT) Tuesday, 21,000 Palestinian workers
from the West Bank and the Gaza Strip will be allowed to go to
their jobs in Israel, the spokesman said Monday.
	   The blockade was imposed after Israeli security services warned
that Hamas, a Palestinian group opposed to current Mideast peace
efforts, planned to make a major suicide bomb attack or kidnap an
Israeli soldier in retaliation for the killing of two of its
leaders by Israeli special forces.
	   Hamas has carried out more than a dozen suicide bombings in
Israel since 1994, killing scores of Israelis.
	   The Israeli closures cause extensive economic hardship in the
Palestinian areas where unemployment is already high. Before the
most recent blockade, about 60,000 Palestinians had permits to work
in Israel.
	   Palestinian leaders have condemned the closures as collective
punishment.
</TEXT>
