<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 10/12/1998 17:23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1970 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 13thLd-Writethru   10-12 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 13th Ld-Writethru,0942 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. envoy briefs NATO, Milosevic concession reported
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with conflicting claims by ethnic
Albanian, Serb media on Kosovo violence Monday. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos BEL101,DWN101,LMN105 &QL; 
 &UR; By DUSAN STOJANOVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ With NATO poised to approve
airstrikes, U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke consulted late into the
night Monday with alliance members amid reports he and Yugoslavia's
president were near a breakthrough in defusing the Kosovo crisis.
	   Holbrooke traveled to Belgium while Western nations evacuated
diplomats from Yugoslavia _ adding to the sense that a last-minute
deal was necessary to avoid the bombing of Serbian targets.
Holbrooke flew to Brussels Monday evening and went right to the
NATO complex a mile (kilometer) away.
	   Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev told journalists in
Moscow that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic had agreed to
allow 1,500 international observers to monitor compliance with U.N.
demands to halt the Serb crackdown in Kosovo.
	   If true, that would represent a key last-minute concession by
Milosevic that came only hours before NATO planned to authorize the
attack against Milosevic's forces.
	   There was no immediate confirmation of Milosevic's reported
concession. But a statement from Milosevic's office said Holbrooke
would return and hold more talks Tuesday.
	   In the Kosovo capital of Pristina, a senior ethnic Albanian
leader, Fehmi Agani, said that if Milosevic agrees to such a force,
it could ``provide a way out of the Kosovo crisis without further
war.'' Agani is head of the ethnic Albanian team set up to
negotiate with Belgrade authorities.
	   A U.S. source, speaking on condition of anonymity, indicated
that Holbrooke had made enough progress that he needed to update
NATO personally as its ambassadors met in Brussels to OK an
activation order _ the last formal step before airstrikes could be
launched.
	   A NATO official who spoke on condition of anonymity said an
activation order would show NATO's resolve to end the violence in
Kosovo, where hundreds of people have been killed and tens of
thousands uprooted since a crackdown against ethnic Albanian rebels
started on Feb. 28. Kosovo is in southern Serbia, the main republic
of Yugoslavia.
	   The order would transfer the command over the airplanes and
military equipment necessary for an airstrike to Supreme Allied
Commander Wesley K. Clark and authorize their deployment over
Yugoslavia.
	   Clark could then proceed in consultation with NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana all the way to actually ordering
planes and missiles launched.
	   Sergeyev said Russia, which as Yugoslavia's ally has tried to
broker a deal that would avoid NATO intervention, was prepared to
provide planes for controlling Yugoslav airspace, and consider
participating in the monitoring force.
	   Earlier Monday, U.N. chief Kofi Annan phoned Milosevic to urge
him to comply with U.N. resolutions to end the Kosovo turmoil.
	   Milosevic responded that he was ``in the process of complying,
or trying to come into full compliance with the Security Council
resolutions,'' U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said.
	   The United Nations has condemned massacres of ethnic Albanians
in Kosovo but has not supported airstrikes.
	   Holbrooke's mission to Brussels followed a flurry of diplomatic
evacuations by Western nations from Yugoslavia. That added to a
sense that intervention was imminent _ barring a breakthrough in
negotiations.
	   The international diplomats' mission evacuated Kosovo for
neighboring Macedonia, with the Russian members the last to depart.
	   Holbrooke, who has met with Milosevic seven times in the past
eight days for a total of roughly 50 hours, described his earlier
overnight meeting with Milosevic as ``intense, indeed, and at times
very heated.'' He said the standoff between NATO and the Yugoslav
president ``can only be called an emergency.''
	   The Americans and Europeans are demanding that Milosevic halt
the crackdown he launched against the separatist Kosovo Liberation
Army. Ethnic Albanians represent 90 percent of Kosovo's 2 million
people.
	   In Kosovo, the ethnic Albanian-run Kosovo Information Center
said that two ethnic Albanians were wounded Monday when
``newly-arrived Serb forces shot at a village'' in the central
Drenica region.
	   The center also reported shooting near Malisevo, 40 kilometers
(25 miles) southwest of Pristina.
	   Serb sources claimed there were no clashes Monday in the
province. None of the reports could be independently confirmed.
	   Italy on Monday authorized the use of its military bases for any
NATO raid, while the outgoing German government said it intends to
allow German warplanes to participate in any attack.
	   In Paris, French Defense Minister Alain Richard said his country
would provide around 40 aircraft for possible airstrikes, which
could last ``several days.''
	   The U.N. Security Council demands include an immediate
cease-fire, a withdrawal of special troops in the province,
permission for refugees to return home and the start of talks with
independence-minded ethnic Albanians on Kosovo's future.
	   The United States was making military preparations if
Holbrooke's mission failed. Six U.S. B-52 bombers arrived in
Britain on Sunday and a contingent of A-10 antitank planes flew
from Germany to Italy.
	   The positioning of more U.S. planes within range of Yugoslavia
and preparing them for attacks were clearly designed to convince
Milosevic of Washington's resolve to force compliance with U.N.
demands.
</TEXT>
