w1973 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Morocco-MissingPrison     10-12 0349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Morocco-Missing Prisoners </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
First official admission missing political opponents are dead
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ABDELHAKIM YAMANI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   RABAT, Morocco (AP) _ A Moroccan official admitted for the first
time Monday that dozens of missing political opponents were dead,
and he pledged to investigate other cases.
	   Among 112 people declared missing by their families or by
non-governmental organizations since the 1960s, 56 ``are dead and
their death certificates will soon be delivered to their
families,'' said Driss Dahak, head of the official human rights
body.
	   Speaking at a news conference, Dahak declined to elaborate on
the circumstances surrounding the 56 deaths during years of
political repression by the government of King Hassan II.
	   Rights activists have also reported 500 missing ethnic Sahrawis
from the Western Sahara, a territory Morocco claims as its own,
which Dahak also declined to discuss.
	   But the official said his Consultative Council for Human Rights
(CCDH) would on Tuesday establish a commission ``to establish lists
of disappeared people and to study their situations case-by-case.''
	   Regarding the rest of the 112 reported disappeared, Dahak said
12 people, including a Libyan, were freed. But the whereabouts of
44 remained unknown, including six who were likely dead and 18 who
disappeared ``under mysterious conditions,'' Dahak said without
elaborating.
	   As the government periodically does, Dahak also announced that
28 political prisoners would be soon freed by royal pardon.
	   Hassan, who has in recent years loosened his grip on the
government and sought to liberalize the country, on Friday told the
Moroccan parliament that the remaining cases before the official
human rights council should be settled within six months.
	   For years, Morocco was known to maintain secret detention
centers in Rabat and Casablanca, as well as an internment camp in
the south. Most of those detained were leftists, though many
members of the military were arrested after a foiled coup in 1972.
	   (cb-parf)
</TEXT>
