<SLUG> BC-Congo, 3rd Add,0172 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KALIMA, Congo: Rwandan and Ugandan rebels.
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; URGENT &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   Kabila, who is supported by troops from Angola, Zimbabwe and
Namibia, defeated the rebels on the outskirts of the capital,
Kinshasa, in mid-August.
	   Since then, the rebels have been contained in their eastern
strongholds, including the city of Kisangani in north-central
Congo.
	   The rebels made slow progress in taking Kindu, which was
defended by a force of about 5,000 troops. Rebel fighters shot down
a Boeing 727 airplane on Saturday, claiming it was transporting 40
government troops and ammunition to Kindu.
	   But Congo Airlines, which owned the aircraft, said the victims
were civilians fleeing fighting in Kindu. There was no independent
confirmation.
	   Since then, rebels said they had closed down all routes from the
town and had fired shells each day into Kindu and the air base, 4
kilometers (2 miles) away.
	   Rebels said most of the civilian population is believed to have
fled the fighting into surrounding forests. 	   
</TEXT>
