<HEADLINE>
Mood is grim as Yugoslavs prepare for the worst
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: SUBS graf 14 bgng: ``Near the ... to CORRECT spelling of
Golubovic. &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos PRI104-105,BEL107-108 &QL; 
 &UR; By JEFFREY ULBRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ The mood is grim, in Kosovo and
across Yugoslavia.
	   Embassies are closing. Diplomats and observers are fleeing.
Humanitarian organizations await the word to pull out.
	   There were hints in the capital Belgrade on Monday that a
settlement in the crisis was in the works, following talks between
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and U.S. negotiator Richard
Holbrooke. However, no deal was certain and the threat of NATO
airstrikes against Yugoslavia remained.
	   Word of the possible diplomatic breakthrough had little
immediate impact across Yugoslavia, where most people must get
their news almost exclusively from state radio, which did not
report the development.
	   The Serbs in Pristina, Kosovo's capital, are angry, both at the
ethnic Albanians, whose more radical wings are fighting for
independence, and at foreigners, whose nations are preparing
military action against them.
	   Fear is palpable in Kosovo's hinterlands, where hundreds of
ethnic Albanians have been killed over the past seven months and
hundreds of thousands driven from their homes. Though many would
welcome NATO airstrikes, they also are afraid Serb police will
exact a terrible vengeance upon them.
	   Some people, however, just think the West is after the wrong
target.
	   ``I hate Americans,'' said Ljubisa, a civil servant from
Kosovo's second largest city, Pec, who didn't want to give his last
name. ``If they have anything against (Milosevic), why don't they
just shoot him? I have three little kids and I didn't hurt
anybody.''
	   Jasna, 30, who also declined to give her last name, was talking
tough.
	   ``If they bomb, I told my husband to send the kids and me to
Serbia,'' she said. ``Then I'm coming back and we're going to get
even with the Albanians.''
	   The last American, European Union and Russian diplomats from the
Kosovo Diplomatic Observer Mission, sent here in July to monitor
the situation, pulled out of Kosovo Monday and headed south for
safety Macedonia.
	   In Belgrade, the British, German and Danish embassies closed and
their staffs began the drive to Budapest, Hungary. The American
Embassy was down to 12 people, mostly in support of the Holbrooke
mission.
	   ``For God's sake, let's get it over with, one way or another,''
said anguished Belgrade housewife Milena Popovic, adding that the
uncertainty was worse than anything else.
	   Near the ethnic Albanian village of Golubovic, west of Pristina,
66-year-old Qazim Berisha stood outside his temporary shelter made
of dried cornstalks. He and 27 of his relatives have been on the
move for the past four months. Two of his sons have been abducted
by Serbs.
