<SLUG> BC-NATO-Kosovo, 6th Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO ready to approve order to bring air strikes closer
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Holbrooke declining to comment after meeting with
NATO ambassadors; PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, Russian Defense Ministers &QL; 
 &UR; With Yugoslavia-Kosovo
 &UR; AP Photo BRU101
 &UR; By RAF CASERT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ Despite progress on the diplomatic
front, NATO was still expected to approve on Monday the last
military step needed to launch airstrikes against Yugoslavia to get
President Slobodan Milosevic to comply with international demands
on Kosovo.
	   ``There is no reason not to sustain the military pressure,''
said a NATO official, who demanded anonymity.
	   U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke briefed the ambassadors of the 16
NATO nations on the ``emergency'' situation in Kosovo but, speaking
to reporters later, declined all comment on his talks.
	   However, Holbrooke denied he was trying to make a deal with
Milosevic, adding,
	   ``That is not the case. We are discussing the situation in
Kosovo in intense detail. Tomorrow morning, we'll see President
Milosevic again (in Belgrade) and we'll proceed from there.''
	   Holbrooke came here from marathon talks with Milosevic amid
indications a breakthrough was near in talks about ending the
violence in Kosovo and thus avert allied airstrikes.
	   He also met here with Bronislaw Geremek, the Polish foreign
minister, whose country holds the presidency of the Organization
for Security and Cooperation. He said the OSCE had a ``major role''
to play in bringing peace to Kosovo.
 &UR; Russian Defense Minister, 5th graf	   
