<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-Kosovo, 7th Ld,0268 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO ready to approve order to bring air strikes closer
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Holbrooke declining to comment after meeting with
NATO ambassadors. &QL; 
 &UR; With Yugoslavia-Kosovo
 &UR; AP Photo BRU101
 &UR; By RAF CASERT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ Despite diplomatic progress, NATO
officials met Monday to consider taking the last military step
needed to launch airstrikes against Yugoslavia to force President
Slobodan Milosevic to comply with international demands on Kosovo.
	   ``There is no reason not to sustain the military pressure,'' a
NATO official said on condition of anonymity.
	   U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke briefed the ambassadors of the 16
NATO nations on the ``emergency'' situation in Kosovo. After the
meeting, he declined comment on the talks.
	   Responding to questions about his talks with Milosevic, he said
he was not trying to cut a deal with the Yugoslav leader.
	   ``We are discussing the situation in Kosovo in intense detail,''
he said. ``Tomorrow morning, we'll see President Milosevic again
(in Belgrade) and we'll proceed from there.''
	   Holbrooke came to Brussels after marathon talks with Milosevic
amid indications a breakthrough was near. Holbrooke is trying to
end a Serb crackdown on ethnic Albanians Kosovo and avert allied
airstrikes.
	   He also met with Polish Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek,
whose country holds the presidency of the Organization for Security
and Cooperation. He said the OSCE had a ``major role'' to play in
bringing peace to Kosovo.
	    &UR; Russian Defense Minister, 5th graf
</TEXT>
