<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Congo, 1st Ld-Writethru,0473 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Congolese rebels say they capture strategic eastern air base
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: COMBINES urgent series; minor edits. &QL; 
 &UR; By HRVOJE HRANJSKI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KALIMA, Congo (AP) _ Congolese rebels and their Rwandan allies
said Monday they had captured the strategic, government-held air
base of Kindu in eastern Congo.
	   After eight days of fighting, a rebel commander said 9,000 rebel
fighters entered the town and its air base, 80 kilometers (50
miles) southwest of Kalima, late Monday.
	   ``The whole town and the airport are in our hands,'' said Arthur
Mulunda, a rebel battalion commander.
	   The claim could not immediately be confirmed. If true, Kindu
would be the rebels' biggest prize in their two-month campaign to
topple President Laurent Kabila.
	   Kabila had turned Kindu into a launching pad for a
counter-offensive against rebel eastern strongholds.
	   Mulunda said his men had captured many government prisoners but
did not give a figure. In Kalima, a rear base for the rebel attack,
soldiers sang and fired weapons in celebration.
	   Mulunda said the victory will open routes to the diamond-rich
province of Eastern Kasai and its capital, Mbuji-Mayi, as well as
to southern Katanga Province, Kabila's home.
	   ``This is a big victory for us,'' Mulunda said. ``Kabila wanted
to use Kindu for a big counter-offensive. He cannot do anything
now,'' he said. ``Mbuji-Mayi is next.''
	   The rebels _ ethnic Tutsis, disenchanted members of Kabila's
army and opposition politicians _ have been reinforced with troops
and weapons from neighboring Rwanda.
	   Kabila has so far refused to negotiate with the rebels, accusing
them of being the puppets of Rwanda and neighboring Uganda.
	   Both countries say they have legitimate security interests in
eastern Congo and accuse Kabila of failing to rid the border area
of Rwandan and Ugandan rebels.
	   Kabila, who is supported by troops from Angola, Zimbabwe and
Namibia, defeated the rebels on the outskirts of the capital,
Kinshasa, in mid-August.
	   Since then, the rebels have been contained in their eastern
strongholds, including the city of Kisangani in north-central
Congo.
	   The rebels made slow progress in taking Kindu, which was
defended by a force of about 5,000 troops.
	   Rebel fighters shot down a Boeing 727 airplane on Saturday,
claiming it was transporting 40 government troops and ammunition to
Kindu. Congo Airlines, which owned the aircraft, said the victims
were civilians fleeing fighting in Kindu. There was no independent
confirmation.
	   Since then, rebels said they had cut off all routes from Kindu
and had fired shells each day into it and the air base, four
kilometers (two miles) away.
	   Rebels said most of the civilian population is believed to have
fled the fighting into nearby forests.
</TEXT>
