<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Afghanistan,0447 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN chief says envoy's mission critical
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ The dispute between Iran and Afghanistan's
Taliban militia over the slaying of Iranian diplomats poses a real
threat to stability in the region, Secretary-General Kofi Annan
said Monday.
	   In a report, Annan said the ongoing mission to the region by his
envoy, Lakhdar Brahimi, is ``of critical importance'' to try to
bring about a settlement between the two sides.
	   ``The outcome of his efforts will depend primarily upon
determination of all parties involved, Afghan as well as their
neighbors, to reach agreement on a pragmatic and practical formula
to return Afghanistan to a stability and an appreciable degree of
normality,'' Annan wrote.
	   The U.N. chief authorized Brahimi to travel to Taliban
headquarters in southern Afghanistan on Monday as part of a tour
that has taken him to Iran and Pakistan.
	   Annan stressed that the visit was an exceptional measure since
the United Nations withdrew all its international personnel from
the country following the Aug. 21 fatal shooting of a U.N. military
adviser. The United Nations is demanding a full report from the
Taliban on the slaying of Lt. Col. Carmine Calo of Italy.
	   Annan dispatched Brahimi to the region after the Taliban
acknowledged its soldiers, acting on their own, killed several
Iranian diplomats when the militia captured the northern Afghan
city of Mazar-e-Sharif from the opposition in August.
	   Iran has deployed more than 200,000 soldiers, hundreds of tanks
and scores of jet fighters on its border with Afghanistan and has
threatened to retaliate. Tehran has demanded an apology from the
Taliban and the arrest and deportation of those who killed the
diplomats. So far the Taliban has refused both requests.
	   The Taliban has accused Iran of arming and financing the Afghan
opposition, while Pakistan is believed to be supporting the
Taliban.
	   In his report, Annan decried the failure of peace talks and
intensified fighting between the Taliban, who control roughly 90
percent of the country, and troops loyal to the opposition alliance
that includes President Burhanuddin Rabbani, who was ousted from
Kabul in 1996.
	   ``The prolonged civil war in Afghanistan, itself a massive
humanitarian tragedy, is now threatening to become a regional
conflict and poses a real danger to stability in the region,''
Annan said.
	   He urged all sides respect the human rights of civilians. And he
particularly urged care for cultural relics in war zones,
particularly ancient statues of Buddha in Bamiyan.
</TEXT>
