<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Balkan-Summit, 1st Ld-Writethru,0471 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkey and Greece join forces on Kosovo, but unable to talk about
</HEADLINE>
own disputes &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with Yilmaz meeting Simitis, no
headway on Greek Turkish disputes; changes byline. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos ANT101,103,104,107-110 &QL; 
 &UR; By PATRICK QUINN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ANTALYA, Turkey (AP) _ Traditional enemies Greece and Turkey
united Monday to pressure Yugoslavia into making concessions on
Kosovo, but the two neighbors failed to make any progress on
disputes that could lead the two NATO allies to war.
	   ``We discussed our bilateral relations and found that we have
problems,'' Greek Premier Costas Simitis said after meeting Turkish
Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz.
	   ``This is a known phenomenon in Greek-Turkish relations, and I
hope that one day we may be able to overcome these difficulties.''
	   Solving their own intractable problems is important if the two
countries hope to set an example for other leaders gathered in this
Mediterranean resort and to help some in the turbulent region
realize their own dreams of membership in the European Union and
NATO. Prime ministers from Bulgaria, Macedonia and Romania attended
the two-day summit as did the foreign minister of Albania and
observers from Bosnia and Croatia.
	   Simitis said they did not discuss the one issue now threatening
to trigger conflict between the two NATO allies: the deployment by
Greek Cypriots of Russian-made S-300 missiles on war-divided
Cyprus.
	   ``The S-300 were not discussed at all, but I referred to
Cyprus,'' Simitis added.
	   Turkey has said it will use military force to prevent
installation of the missiles, an action that Athens has said will
mean war.
	   Turkey invaded and occupied the northern third of Cyprus in
1974, after an abortive Athens-backed coup by Greek Cypriots
seeking to unite the island with Greece. More than 30,000 troops
are based in the Turkish Cypriot breakaway state, which is
recognized only by Ankara.
	   Turkey's apparent determination to risk war with neighboring
Syria over Syria's harboring of Kurdish insurgents indicates the
hard-nosed approach the Turkish military is taking elsewhere.
	   Simitis and Yilmaz discussed longstanding disputes in the Aegean
Sea that have twice led Greece and Turkey to the brink of war in
the past 11 years. The leaders failed, however, to reach agreement
on how to solve them.
	   The two premiers did find common ground in their effort to
convince Yugoslavia to accept a request by U.S. envoy Richard
Holbrooke that President Slobodan Milosevic agree to an expanded
international monitoring mission in the secessionist province of
Kosovo.
	   Turkey and Greece also spent Monday pressuring Yugoslav Premier
Momir Bulatovic to accept a reference to Kosovo in their joint
statement.
</TEXT>
