<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Bank Bills, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japanese upper house approves bank failure measures
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS reports that public funds expected to total 60 trillion
yen (dlrs 513 billion) in 8th graf, bank recapitalization bill
expected to become law on Friday in 19th graf &QL; 
 &UR; By TODD ZAUN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan took a big step toward ending its banking
crisis with the passage of laws that will allow the government to
take over foundering banks to fix them or shut them down.
	   The legislation, passed Monday, establishes rules for how the
government will deal with banks doomed to fail and establishes a
public institution similar to the U.S. Resolution Trust Corp.,
created during the 1980s U.S. savings and loan crisis to buy the
bad debt from banks.
	   The new laws were the first half of a broader plan to strengthen
the debt-ridden financial system.
	   Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's ruling party has a comfortable
majority in the powerful lower house, but needs some cooperation in
the opposition-dominated upper house.
	   The package is crucial for cleaning up nearly dlrs 1 trillion in
bad loans left by the collapse in the early 1990s of runaway real
estate and stock prices.
	   It is also a key first step in Japan's efforts to overcome its
deepest recession since the end of World War II.
	   The laws passed Monday established a framework for bank bailouts
but didn't specify how much public money could be used. The ruling
Liberal Democratic Party originally proposed using about 10
trillion yen (dlrs 86 billion).
	   But through negotiations with opposition parties the total
public funds to be used will amount to 60 trillion yen (dlrs 513
billion), including 17 trillion yen (dlrs 145.3 billion) for use in
protection of depositors, the Nihon Keizai newspaper reported
Tuesday.
	   Toyoo Gyohten, a special adviser to the prime minister for
financial affairs, had said in Singapore earlier Monday that the
bailout could reach 60 trillion yen (dlrs 513 billion).
	   ``Adequate public funds will be made available,'' he said.
	   The markets took the news as a sign the country is getting
serious about fixing its financial problems.
	   The benchmark Nikkei Stock Average surged 675.04 points, or 5.24
percent, closing the day's trading at 13,555.01.
	   Japan could use a boost.
	   Bank problems have made new loans hard to get and business has
been suffering, especially small and medium-size companies.
Unemployment is at a record high, bankruptcies are soaring and
consumer spending is falling.
	   Growth shows no sign of coming back soon. The Economic Planning
Agency announced last week that the economy would shrink by 1.8
percent this year, and the head of the agency said on Sunday that
it could shrink next year as well.
	   Under the new laws, a committee will be set up to handle bank
failures. The committee will take one of three steps: nationalize
the bank temporarily through the government's purchase of its
shares; order the liquidation of the institution; or transfer the
bank's operations to a public bridge bank.
	   The laws cleared the upper house of Parliament on Monday after
passing the more powerful lower house on Oct. 2.
	   Shortly after the bills passed, politicians from the ruling and
opposition camps announced an agreement on a bank recapitalization
proposal to inject public funds into the banking system to ease the
nation's credit crunch.
	   That is expected to be approved in the lower house Tuesday and
voted into law Friday in the upper house, with the backing of the
two opposition parties, national broadcaster NHK said.
	   With Japan under pressure to turn around its economy and help
Asian neighbors, the bills are a major victory for Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi and end one phase of a fierce dispute between his
ruling party and the opposition.
	   The first test case of the new legislation will be the troubled
Long-Term Credit Bank, which has been rumored to be on the verge of
collapse since summer.
	   LTCB, one of Japan's biggest lenders, is struggling under the
weight of failed real estate loans.
	   In June, LTCB announced it was in talks to merge with Sumitomo
Trust _ a move that was widely regarded as a government-directed
bailout. But under the new legislation, the bank will be
nationalized temporarily and its bad loans will be sold, Kyodo News
agency reported.
	   The bills also abolish a 13 trillion yen (dlrs 113 billion) fund
that previously provided public money to be pumped into the banking
system to recapitalize banks.
 &UR; (tz-jc-apdj-km) 	   
</TEXT>
