<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-Kosovo, 9th Ld,0383 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO ready to approve order to bring air strikes closer
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with more comments from Holbrooke, head of OSCE. &QL; 
 &UR; With Yugoslavia-Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo BRU101 &QL; 
 &UR; By RAF CASERT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ Despite diplomatic progress, NATO met
into the early hours Tuesday to consider taking the last military
step needed to launch airstrikes against Yugoslavia to force
President Slobodan Milosevic to comply with international demands
on Kosovo.
	   After talks with the 16-nation alliance, U.S. envoy Richard
Holbrooke said ``some movement in Belgrade'' had improved chances
for a negotiated settlement on Kosovo, with the Organization for
Security and Cooperation playing an important role.
	   ``We think that's a very positive, potentially positive
development, and we welcome it,'' Holbrooke said of OSCE
involvement in solving the Kosovo crisis. Russia and Milosevic also
back this.
	   Polish Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek, whose country holds
the OSCE presidency, said the 54-nation regional security
organization could send thousands of unarmed civilians to verify a
Kosovo settlement.
	   But as long as no agreement was reached, NATO planned to keep up
the pressure, including the threat of airstrikes.
	   ``There is no reason not to sustain the military pressure,''
said a NATO official, who demanded anonymity.
	   Holbrooke denied he was trying to cut a deal with Milosevic.
``That is not the case,'' he told reporters. ``We are discussing
the situation in Kosovo in intense detail. Tomorrow morning, we'll
see President Milosevic again (in Belgrade), and we'll proceed from
there.''
	   He said his aim remained to get Milosevic to provide ``full and
effective compliance with United Nations Security Council
resolutions'' calling on him to end his crackdown on the
secessionist province of Kosovo.
	   There were indications a breakthrough was near in the talks
about ending the violence in Kosovo and thus avert allied
airstrikes.
	   Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev said in Moscow Monday
that Milosevic had agreed to allow 1,500 international observers to
monitor compliance with U.N. demands to halt the crackdown. Geremek
spoke about the need for ``thousands.''
	   A NATO, 10th graf pvs
</TEXT>
