<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Briefs,0466 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A Package of Caribbean News Briefs
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 
 &UR; ANTIGUA: Eric Clapton's addiction recovery center opens &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ST. JOHN'S, Antigua (AP) _ A dlrs 6.5 million addiction recovery
center completely underwritten by British rock star Eric Clapton
will accept its first patient Tuesday and promises to turn away no
one who needs treatment.
	   Clapton, himself once addicted to drugs, built the 36-bed
Crossroads Centre of Antigua over the past five years. It will
offer intensive, 29-day recovery programs to people addicted to
drugs or alcohol at a cost of dlrs 9,000.
	   For those unable to pay, foundations have been formed in
Antigua, the United States, Canada and the United Kingdom to offer
financial aid.
	   ``No one will be turned away,'' said administrator Anne Vance,
who for 11 years worked at the Betty Ford Center in Southern
California. It was Vance who met Clapton in 1994 in London and
eventually persuaded the singer and virtuoso guitarist to provide
the financing for the Caribbean's only such facility.
 &UR; ST. KITTS: Extradition case delayed in case of alleged drug
trafficker
	   BASSETERRE, St. Kitts (AP) _ A magistrate on Monday adjourned
the extradition case against an accused drug trafficker who
allegedly caused a stir by threatening to kill U.S. students on
this Caribbean island.
	   The United States has been attempting to extradite Charles
``Little Nut'' Miller since 1996 to try him in Florida on drug
trafficking charges. The case took on a high profile in August when
the State Department told students at the Ross University
veterinary school that Miller had threatened to kill Americans if
he were extradited.
	   Miller denied he ever made the threat and most of the 250 U.S.
students at the school stayed on, though some left the island.
 &UR; JAMAICA: Police seek Cuban refugees who were adrift for a week
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ Police in Jamaica were searching Monday
for four Cuban refugees who were part of a group of 14 who set out
in a boat for Puerto Rico but ended up on the north coast of
Jamaica instead.
	   Ten of the refugees _ three women and seven men _ were
apprehended Sunday evening after they landed near Hope Bay on the
north coast of the island after seven days at sea. The other four
remain at large.
	   Police said the refugees set out from Santiago de Cuba in a
14-foot fishing boat but drifted helplessly after their outboard
motor failed.
	   The 10 Cubans in custody were examined by medical personnel and
were in good health, according to police. Local and international
officials will consider their cases and they will be returned to
Cuba if they are not granted asylum in another country.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Caribbean-Briefs; CT:i; 
(REG:CRB;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
