<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0712 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ Despite diplomatic progress, NATO
officials met into the early hours Tuesday to consider taking the
last military step needed to launch airstrikes against Yugoslavia
to force President Slobodan Milosevic to comply with international
demands on Kosovo. U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke briefed ambassadors
of the 16 NATO nations on the ``emergency'' situation in Kosovo but
later declined comment on the meeting. There were signs a
breakthrough was near in the talks aimed at ending violence in the
secessionist Serbian province and thus avert allied airstrikes. A
NATO official said the alliance would proceed with plans for
airstrikes to keep the pressure on Milosevic. They would likely
include the issuance on Tuesday of an ``activation order'' to put
planes and other hardware to be used in such an attack under joint
NATO command. (NATO-KOSOVO)
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ Turkey said Monday that Syria appeared to
have moved toward meeting its demands in a confrontation over
Kurdish rebels _ the first sign of a breakthrough in a two-week-old
crisis that has threatened war between the two neighbors. According
to Foreign Minister Ismail Cem, Syria relayed a message Monday
through Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, whose government has
been trying to mediate the crisis. Cem said the message ``indicates
that there is an effort on the Syrian side to meet the concerns
that we have raised.'' Turkey accuses Syria of sheltering and
supporting Kurd rebels responsible for cross-border attacks. Two
weeks ago, saying its patience had run out, it suggested it might
carry out an unspecified military operation. Syria denies the
accusations. (TURKEY-SYRIA)
	   KALIMA, Congo (AP) _ Congolese rebels and their Rwandan allies
said Monday they had captured the strategic, government-held air
base of Kindu in eastern Congo. After eight days of fighting, rebel
commander Arthur Mulunda said 9,000 rebel fighters entered the town
and its air base, 80 kilometers (50 miles) southwest of Kalima,
late Monday. The claim could not immediately be confirmed. If true,
Kindu would be the rebels' biggest prize in their two-month
campaign to topple President Laurent Kabila. Kabila had turned
Kindu into a launching pad for a counter-offensive against rebel
eastern strongholds. Bob Ngoy, a rebel commander, said 1,377
government troops surrendered in Kindu on Monday. (CONGO)
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu will reject
an attempt by hard-liners in his Cabinet to restrict his freedom to
negotiate at a U.S. summit this week, an Israeli official said
Monday. He will be meeting President Bill Clinton and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat Thursday to discuss an American plan calling
for the withdrawal of Israeli forces from 13 percent of the West
Bank. Right-wing ministers Yitzhak Levy and Shaul Yahalom oppose
the withdrawal and intend to urge the cabinet Tuesday to forbid
Netanyahu to agree to it unless the Palestinians clamp down on
Islamic militants and fulfill other conditions. However an Israeli
official said Netanyahu will certainly reject the right-wing move.
``No negotiator would agree to his freedom being circumscribed in
such a way before the talks,'' the official said on condition of
anonymity. (ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS)
	   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) _ Nitric oxide doesn't just pollute the
air: it also saves lives and enhances men's sexual performance.
Unlocking its secrets won three American researchers the Nobel
Medicine Prize on Monday. The 7.6-million-kronor (dlrs 978,000)
award is divided equally between Robert F. Furchgott, Louis J.
Ignarro and Ferid Murad, who discovered new properties of the gas,
which helped in developing the anti-impotence drug Viagra. Nitric
oxide can ease chest pains and has been used to find stronger and
more selective drugs to treat cardiovascular conditions. Scientists
are now testing to see whether the colorless gas can be used to
stop the advance of cancer because of its ability to defend against
tumors and kill infectious bacteria, fungi and parasites.
(NOBEL-MEDICINE)
</TEXT>
