<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-People and Places,0759 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
People and places in the news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items about Prince Charles, Brian Wilson, an American
bridge jumper, Eric Clapton and an Iraqi cancer patient; Some items
have already moved separately &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) _ Prince Charles is donating one of his
lithographs of Windsor Castle to benefit a hospital that treated
victims of Northern Ireland's worst-ever terrorist attack.
	   The signed and dated lithograph will be auctioned Wednesday in
support of County Tyrone Hospital in Omagh, where an Aug. 15 car
bomb planted by Irish Republican Army dissidents killed 29 people
and wounded 370.
	   ``This is the first time a piece of art by Prince Charles has
been auctioned anywhere in the world, so we have not placed a
reserve price on it,'' said John de Vere White, Dublin's premier
auctioneer of fine art.
	   Christie's London office has valued the lithograph at 2,000 to
3,000 British pounds (dlrs 3,400 to dlrs 5,100).
	   The heir to the British throne visited the hospital and the
bomb-ravaged town three days after the attack.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	   IRVINE, California (AP) _ The reclusive Brian Wilson belted out
``Surfin' USA'' and ``California Girls'' during a rare live
appearance.
	   The former Beach Boy joined Jimmy Buffett and his Coral Reefer
Band on Sunday night at Irvine Meadows as Buffett wrapped up his
summer tour.
	   A serious-faced Wilson, who just recorded a new CD, appeared
slightly uncomfortable and raised his arms when he got a standing
ovation.
	   Wilson, 56, lives most of the year in St. Charles, Illinois,
with his wife and twin daughters.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	   CLEVELAND (AP) _ A man trying to escape police survived a
110-foot (35-meter) plunge off a highway bridge into the Cuyahoga
River, but was caught when authorities followed his wet footprints.
	   The man, whose identity was not released, attacked his former
girlfriend and her new boyfriend with a baseball bat at the woman's
apartment early Sunday in the suburb of Euclid, police said.
	   When police responded, he fled in a station wagon through
downtown Cleveland and one of his tires blew out. He parked on a
bridge and leapt into the Cuyahoga River, Euclid police Detective
Mike Grida said.
	   The river at that spot is about 25 to 30 feet (8 to 9 meters)
deep. The man crawled out, leaving a trail of wet footprints.
Cleveland police tracked the suspect to a phone booth and arrested
him.
	   The man was treated for minor injuries and taken to Euclid City
Jail, police said.
	   His former girlfriend and her boyfriend sustained minor
injuries.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	   ST. JOHN'S, Antigua (AP) _ A dlrs 6.5 million addiction recovery
center underwritten by British rock star Eric Clapton opens Tuesday
with promises to turn away no one who needs treatment.
	   Clapton, who himself overcame a drug and alcohol addiction in
the 1970s, built the 36-bed Crossroads Centre of Antigua over the
past five years. It will offer an intensive, 29-day recovery
program for drug and alcohol addictions at a cost of dlrs 9,000.
	   For those unable to pay, foundations have been formed in
Antigua, the United States, Canada and the United Kingdom to offer
financial aid.
	   ``No one will be turned away,'' said administrator Anne Vance.
	   But there is no free ride. ``For those who cannot pay the full
fee, we will expect some kind of voluntary contribution in the form
of work after the patient has recovered,'' Vance said.
	   Clapton, who maintains a residence in Antigua on a bluff
overlooking the Atlantic not far from the center, has said he will
work directly with patients from time to time, drawing on his own
experiences.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	   LONDON (AP) _ A 4-year-old Iraqi girl who came to Britain six
months ago for leukemia treatment returns home Tuesday with her
cancer in remission, doctors said.
	   Mariam Hamza ``has responded well ... and we wish to be
optimistic,'' said Ken Thompson, chief of Yorkhill Hospital, a
children's hospital in Glasgow, Scotland.
	   Mariam was brought to Britain by lawmaker George Galloway, a
left-wing member of Britain's governing Labor Party, who met her
during a visit to Iraq.
	   Galloway said he wanted to highlight the suffering of the Iraqi
people as a result of U.N. sanctions imposed in 1991 after the
Iraqi invasion of Kuwait, which led to the Gulf War.
	   Iraqi opposition groups were outraged, saying Iraqi leader
Saddam Hussein's government had plenty of money to import food and
medicine under a U.N. program that allows Iraq to sell oil to pay
for such humanitarian goods.
</TEXT>
