<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Today In History,0510 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sunday, October 18
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   Today is Sunday, October 18, the 291st day of 1998. There are 74
days left in the year.
	   Highlights in history on this date:
	   1685 - King Louis XIV of France revokes the Edict of Nantes,
which established the legal toleration of France's Protestant
population, the Huguenots.
	   1767 - The Boundary between Maryland and Pennsylvania, the
Mason-Dixon line, is agreed upon.
	   1867 - The United States takes formal possession of Alaska from
Russia.
	   1892 - The first long-distance telephone line is opened between
Chicago and New York.
	   1898 - The American flag is raised in Puerto Rico shortly before
Spain formally relinquishes control of the island to the United
States.
	   1944 - Soviet troops invade Czechoslovakia during World War II.
	   1968 - The U.S. Olympic Committee suspends two black athletes,
Tommie Smith and John Carlos, for giving a black-power salute as a
protest during a victory ceremony in Mexico City.
	   1969 - The U.S. government bans artificial sweeteners known as
cyclamates because of evidence they caused cancer in laboratory
rats.
	   1981 - Andreas Papandreou's Panhellenic Socialist Movement wins
48 percent in national elections, becoming Greece's first leftist
government.
	   1989 - Gunmen assassinate Colombian Liberal party presidential
candidate Luis Carlos Galan, the frontrunner in polls, at a
campaign rally outside Bogota. Four candidates are murdered in the
months leading up to the 1990 election.
	   1992 - The opening ceremony of World Series baseball is marred
when a U.S. Marine Corps color guard presents the Canadian flag
upside-down, prompting the Marines and President George Bush to
apologize.
	   1993 - U.N. oil embargo takes effect against Haiti.
	   1994 - Boat people begin to return to Haiti after the
reinstatement of President Jean-Bertrand Aristide .
	   1995 - The United States announces it will grant Fidel Castro a
visa permitting the Cuban president to address the United Nations.
	   1996 - A Kurdish faction backed by the Iraqi government begins a
major counteroffensive, retaking the strategic town of Kuysanjaq
from a rival Kurdish group.
	   1997 - From inside a steel cage, former mental asylum inmate
Saber Abu el-Ulla and his brother, Mahmoud, plead guilty to killing
nine German tourists and an Egyptian bus driver in a fiery attack
outside a Cairo museum.
	   Today's Birthdays:
	   Henri Bergson, French philosopher and Nobel laureate
(1856-1941); Pierre Elliott Trudeau, former Canadian Prime Minister
(1919--); George C. Scott, Oscar winning American actor (1926--);
Violeta Barrios de Chamorro, Nicaraguan President (1929--); Lee
Harvey Oswald, accused killer of U.S. President John F. Kennedy
(1939-1963); Martina Navratilova, Czech tennis player (1956--);
Jean-Claude Van Damme, Belgian actor (1958--)
	   Thought for Today:
	   Only those ideas that are least truly ours can be adequately
expressed in words _ Henri Bergson, French philosopher (1859-1941).
</TEXT>
