<SLUG> BC-NATO-Kosovo, 9th Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URGENT
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; NATO sets stage for air strike against Yugoslavia for later in
week &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with NATO agreeing on airstrikes.
 &UR; AP Photo BRU101
 &UR; By RAF CASERT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ The NATO alliance on Tuesday finalized
plans for airstrikes against Yugoslavia, possibly as early as the
coming weekend, NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said.
	   He said despite the fact U.S envoy Richard Holbrooke was making
progress in talks with Slobodan Milosevic, the allies agreed to
increase the airstrikes threat to get the Yugoslav president to
back down in Kosovo.
	   ``We have to maintain this pressure,'' Solana told a news
conference after a meeting of the NATO ambassadors.
	   At that meeting, Solana said, Holbrooke briefed the allies on
his talks with Milosevic and ``reported there had been progress ...
largely due to the pressure of the alliance'' to use the threat of
military force.
	   Solana said the allies issued an ``activation order'' formally
putting warplanes and other hardware belonging to NATO governments
under the command of the Supreme Allied Commander Wesley K. Clark.
	   He said order was for both ``limited air strikes and a phased
air campaign'' against Yugoslavia.
	   MORE 	   
</TEXT>
