<DATE_TIME> 10/12/1998 20:06:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2110 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-US-Shoppers'Parad     10-12 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-US-Shoppers' Paradise,1122 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Foreign visitors make shopping part of their vacation
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With FEA-US-Shoppers' Paradise-Price Box &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo NY304 &QL; 
 &UR; By VIOREL URMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Marco Bassano's day started on a heavenly note.
	   ``I'm in paradise,'' the Italian tourist said, contemplating the
Sony digital camera he had just bought from a video store in Times
Square. ``It's almost half the price you'd pay for it in Europe.
What a bargain!''
	   Lured by the sheer volume of retail goods and bargain prices,
foreign visitors increasingly are going on shopping expeditions
during vacations in the United States.
	   They are spending billions of dollars at American shops and
malls for items that are more costly or less available at home,
such as CDs, car stereos, sports equipment, leather goods, designer
clothing, jeans and electronics.
	   ``As a shopping foreign tourist, I can say there's a lot more
variety, better service and it's cheaper than in other parts of the
world,'' said Bassano, a 38-year-old physician from Rome, who added
that he paid ``about 400 dollars'' for the floppy disk camera.
	   Comparatively, a Sony digital camera sells for about 1.1 million
lire (dlrs 709) in Italy and for 100,000 yen (dlrs 854) in Japan.
	   The New York City Convention and Visitors Bureau said that in
1995, the most recent year of record, 5.4 million international
visitors spent dlrs 4.7 billion in New York, the top city visited
by foreigners in the United States.
	   More than a quarter of that amount _ dlrs 1.3 billion, or an
average of dlrs 240 per person _ went for retail goods.
	   International visitors are expected to top 6 million in 1998 and
spending for consumer goods is expected to jump as well, the bureau
said.
	   Shopping is so popular that Bloomingdale's department store is
rated the third-biggest tourist attraction in New York after the
Empire State Building and the Statue of Liberty.
	   Store managers and salespersons agree that the lure of bargains
can prove irresistible to foreigners.
	   At Structure, an apparel chain store across the street from the
Empire State Building, Masashi Nakamura bought two cotton shirts at
the ``buy one, get one free'' day's discount, paying dlrs 24.99 for
both.
	   ``This stuff is made in Hong Kong. It's good quality,'' the
Japanese tourist said.
	   New York has a special image because of the huge volume of
merchandise on the market and the appealing way shelves display new
goods _ many at a discount _ to attract customers, said Arsenio
Amadis, a salesman at Structure.
	   ``When it comes to chasing after bargains, this city has no
peer,'' he said, referring to the numerous promotions, sales and
clearances.
	   Economists also point to the Americans' consumer-oriented
culture and to the fact that consumer spending accounts for
two-thirds of the nation's overall economic activity.
	   For some visitors, shopping is a big winner: Bargains look more
attractive and prices for U.S.-made big-brand wares are lower than
at home.
	   ``The bargain goods in Germany are low quality,'' said Michael
Dittmer, a German tourist, as he tried on a pair of jeans retailing
for dlrs 38 at Gap, an apparel chain. ``On the other hand, brand
items like Nike or Levi's can be two times more expensive (in
Germany).''
	   Camping gear is high on the shopping list of German tourists. An
MSR (Mountain Safety Research) cooking stove that costs about dlrs
60 in the United States, retails for more than 170 marks (dlrs 100)
in Germany, German visitors say.
	   At Lord and Taylor on Fifth Avenue, discount sales abound.
	   ``Additional 25 percent off on already reduced summer fashions _
total savings up to over 65 percent,'' according to a sign in the
dresses' department. ``Shoes: take 30 percent off the ticketed
price.''
	   Though goods often carry original tags with artificially high
prices that are for ``markdowns,'' such deep discounts are often
the rule _ not the exception.
	   Customers were waiting in line to make a purchase at the ladies'
handbags counter, which in Japan, for example, can cost anywhere
from 50,000 to 100,000 yen (dlrs 427 to dlrs 854).
	   ``Foreign tourists buy (American) designer leather handbags
which are cheaper than overseas. Even the dlrs 300 handbags sell
very well,'' said Lord and Taylor saleswoman Ghislaine Nocera.
``Our clients know what they want and why they want it.''
	   For some Latin Americans, shopping gets the upper hand.
	   According to the Visitors Bureau, South Americans _ particularly
Brazilians and Chileans _ often come to the city for 3-5 days to
load up on goods.
	   Thanks to their overvalued currency, the real, traveling and
shopping abroad has become cheaper for many Brazilians, and the
United States is their favorite destination. Shopping abroad for
upscale designer labels may also be popular because they are hard
to come by in Brazil.
	   The number of Brazilians visiting New York has more than doubled
in recent years _ from 131,000 in 1993 to 333,000 in 1997,
according to bureau statistics.
	   With the vacation market booming, tour organizers across the
United States want a bigger piece of the action, and sometimes they
go in cyberspace to publicize their offers.
	   Shop New York Tours, which has an Internet Web site, promotes
tours where for dlrs 25 a day visitors are bused to selected stores
``which offer quality, value and great prices,'' manager Joshua
Kamens said.
	   And the stronger dollar is not an impediment.
	   ``Even if the exchange rates for the dollar are higher for
European, Asian and Latin American shoppers, it's still cheaper for
them to buy things in the United States. We give them better value
for their money (at a lower price),'' said salesman Steve Maverick
from Computer Warehouse in midtown Manhattan.
	   Among his customers are tourists from Kuwait, Lebanon and Saudi
Arabia, who buy cameras, computers and video recorders. Personal
organizers are particularly strong sellers.
	   According to 1996 figures, Canada topped the list of New York
visitors with slightly over 1 million visitors, followed by Britain
with 562,000; Germany, 471,000; Japan, 446,000; Brazil, 258,000;
and France, 254,000.
	   New York isn't the only shopping mecca for bargain hunters from
abroad. Los Angeles and Miami placed second and third as
destinations for non-U.S. tourists.
	   And Las Vegas, a gambling haven, is fast becoming a shopping
paradise.
	   Among the most popular destinations is The Forum Shops, a mall
that resembles an Italian piazza. Opened in 1992, it is the most
successful shopping center in the United States with more than
50,000 people visiting each day, including overseas shoppers.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-FEA-US-Shoppers' Paradise; CT:f; 
