<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-Kosovo, 10th Ld,0219 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO sets stage for air strike against Yugoslavia for later in
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; URGENT &QL; 
week &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with NATO agreeing to airstrikes. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo BRU101 &QL; 
 &UR; By RAF CASERT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ The NATO alliance on Tuesday made final
plans for airstrikes against Yugoslavia, possibly by the end of the
week, NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said.
	   He said that despite some progress by U.S envoy Richard
Holbrooke in talks with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, the
allies agreed to strengthen the threat of airstrikes in an effort
to force the Yugoslav president to back down in Kosovo.
	   ``We have to maintain this pressure,'' Solana told a news
conference after a meeting of the NATO ambassadors.
	   At that meeting, Solana said, Holbrooke briefed the allies on
his talks with Milosevic and ``reported there had been progress ...
largely due to the pressure of the alliance'' to use the threat of
military force.
	   Solana said the allies issued an ``activation order'' formally
putting warplanes and other hardware belonging to NATO governments
under the command of the Supreme Allied Commander Wesley K. Clark.
	   He said the order was for both ``limited air strikes and a
phased air campaign'' against Yugoslavia.
	   MORE
</TEXT>
