<DOCNO> APW19981012.1305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 10/12/1998 20:17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2126 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-Kosovo 9thLd 1stadd 10-12 0381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-Kosovo, 9th Ld, 1st add </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUSSELS: against Yugoslavia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   Solana said the allies agreed airstrikes could come ``no earlier
than 96 hours from today,'' meaning the first war planes and
missiles could be heading for targets across Yugoslavia as early as
next Saturday.
	   ``We hope this will help negotiations bear fruit. I still
believe that diplomacy can succeed and that the use of military
force can be avoided,'' said Solana.
	   Holbrooke briefed the NATO envoys on what he called the
``emergency'' situation in Kosovo. He denied he tried to cut a deal
with Milosevic.
	   ``We are discussing the situation in Kosovo in intense detail.
Tomorrow morning, we'll see President Milosevic again (in Belgrade)
and we'll proceed from there,'' he told reporters.
	   He said there was ``some movement in Belgrade'' and that he said
his aim remained to get Milosevic to provide ``full and effective
compliance with United Nations Security Council resolutions''
calling on him to end his crackdown on Kosovo.
	   Holbrooke talked with Milosevic in Belgrade Monday, then flew
here to brief the NATO envoys and to meet with Polish Foreign
Minister Bronislaw Geremek whose country now heads the Organization
for Security and Cooperation.
	   Geremek said the 54-nation OSCE could send thousands of unarmed
civilians to verify a Kosovo settlement.
	   ``We think that's a very positive, potentially positive
development and we welcome it,'' Holbrooke said.
	   Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev said in Moscow Monday
Milosevic had agreed to allow 1,500 international observers to
monitor compliance with U.N. demands to halt the crackdown in
Kosovo. Geremek spoke about the need for ``thousands.''
	   Officials hailed the issuance of the ``activation orders''
putting NATO effectively on a war footing as showing the alliance's
resolve to end the violence in Kosovo, where hundreds of people
have been killed and an estimated 275,000 uprooted since February's
crackdown on ethnic Albanian rebels.
	   After the four-day notice period of the ``activation orders''
expires, Supreme Allied Commander Wesley K. Clark will no longer
need any approval from the 16 NATO governments and proceed only in
consultation with Solana, NATO officials said.
	   MORE	   
</TEXT>
