r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Cricket-PayCut     10-12 0215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Pay Cuts </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Top Australian cricketers offered less money: report
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ A Sydney newspaper said Tuesday that
leading Australian test cricketers who have spent a year
campaigning for more money face pay cuts this season.
	   The Daily Telegraph said the Australian Cricket Board has
reduced the contracts to its top six players _ captain Mark Taylor,
Mark and Steve Waugh, Shane Warne, Ian Healy and Glenn McGrath.
	   Last season, Australia's top six players were paid a base
contract fee of 200,000 Australian dollars (about 120,000 US dlrs).
The newspaper says that figure has been reduced to between 160,000
and 190,000 Australian dollars (between 96,000 and 114,000 US
dlrs).
	   The report said the extra money will go to domestic Sheffield
Shield players, lower-tier ACB players and the players' bargaining
agent James Erskine.
	   The report said several players, including Mark Waugh, were
angry about the move. Waugh was quoted as saying the pay cut was
``insane.''
	   ACB chief executive Malcolm Speed said he was happy with the
system and said it was put into place with the players' assistance.
	   ``What we are putting in place is exactly what has been
suggested by the players' association,'' Speed said. (djp)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Cricket-Pay Cuts; CT:s; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:ASIA;)
