<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-Yankees Sale?,0301 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Proposed price of Yankees deal depends on success
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Cablevision's proposed offer to buy the New York
Yankees would automatically increase in price if the team wins the
AL pennant or the World Series, The New York Times reported Monday.
	   ``There's so much for the division series, so much for the
league series, so much for the World Series,'' an unidentified
baseball official was quoted as saying by the newspaper. ``It's not
cumulative. There's a certain amount for each level.''
	   Cablevision, which owns the television rights to Yankees games
under a dlrs 486 million, 12-year contract that expires after the
2000 season, has offered to buy the team and let George
Steinbrenner remain in charge, perhaps for several years, perhaps
as long as he wants. Most reports say a deal would be worth dlrs
600 million to dlrs 650 million, but the Times said one official
said he heard it could be worth as much as dlrs 900 million.
	   ``It's based on having a deal, and I don't have a deal,''
Steinbrenner told the Times. ``We don't have any agreement. In the
future that may be in there, but it's not in there for this year
unless we have a deal, and we don't have a deal.''
	   Cablevision also owns Madison Square Garden, and officials have
said recently that Steinbrenner could be offered operating control
of the NBA's New York Knicks and the NHL's New York Rangers as part
of a Yankees sale.
	   Baseball officials said they had heard only second-hand about
the possible sale talks and weren't sure what Steinbrenner would do
in the end.
	   Steinbrenner led a group that purchased the Yankees from CBS
Inc. in 1973 for about dlrs 10 million. Steinbrenner and his family
own about 55 percent of the team.
</TEXT>
