w2173 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-Markets     10-12 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar rises against yen, Tokyo stocks lower in early trading
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar rose against the yen early Tuesday,
while Japanese stock prices fell on profit-taking after Monday's
rally.
	   The dollar bought 117.90 yen in early trading, up 1.18 yen from
late Monday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level of
117.63 yen overnight.
	   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 252.23 points, or 1.86
percent, to 13,302.78 in the first 30 minutes of trading. On
Monday, the Nikkei surged 675.04 points, or 5.24 percent.
	   The dollar moved higher against the yen as traders covered
short, or oversold, dollar positions amid speculation that Japan's
central bank may further ease credit after its policy board meeting
Tuesday, dealers said.
	   Last month, the Bank of Japan lowered short-term interest rates
in an attempt to lessen a reported credit crunch among small firms
affected by the nation's recession-hit economy.
	   Lower interest rates tend to make a nation's currency less
attractive to investors.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, share prices opened mixed in a
favorable reaction to an overnight rise on Wall Street, where the
Dow Jones industrial average closed Monday's trading at 8,001.47,
up 101.95, or 1.3 percent.
	   But profit-takers soon gained the upper hand, pushing the
market's main index into negative territory. The Nikkei had rallied
on Monday following the passage of legislation to revitalize
Japan's debt-ridden banking system.
	   Among Tuesday's early gainers were some banking issues, which
were bought following news that the ruling Liberal Democratic Party
and two political allies agreed on a new framework for pumping
public funds into the ailing banking system to recapitalize
debt-plagued banks.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section fell 16.49 points, or 1.61 percent, to 1,006.85. The
TOPIX closed up 40.84 points, or 4.16 percent, the day before.
	   The yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government
bond fell to 0.880 percent from Monday's finish of 0.900 percent,
driving its price up to 108.20 yen from 108.01 yen.
 &UR; (km-dj)
</TEXT>
