w2177 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-Kosovo     10-12 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-Kosovo,0537 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO gives Milosevic four days to comply or suffer airstrikes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous to combine urgent series. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo BRU101 &QL; 
 &UR; By RAF CASERT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ The NATO alliance on Tuesday gave
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic four days to comply with
international demands on Kosovo or face airstrikes as early as this
weekend. The threat appeared to be working.
	   NATO Secretary-General said the 16 member nations completed the
airstrike plan against Yugoslavia to bolster the negotiating
position of U.S envoy Richard Holbrooke, who was trying to put the
finishing touches on a peace plan for Kosovo during a new round of
talks with Milosevic on Tuesday.
	   ``I still believe diplomacy can succeed and the use of military
force can be avoided,'' Solana said at NATO headquarters early
Tuesday.
	   In Washington, Clinton administration officials said Milosevic
has already agreed to comply with U.N. demands to end his
seven-month crackdown on Kosovo's ethnic Albanians and accepted the
deployment of 2,000 monitors to ensure that he abides by his
promises.
	   Holbrooke lauded NATO's resolve to attack as a necessary stick
for forcing Milosevic to relent in Kosovo, a Serbian province where
Albanians are battling for independence. A U.S. official said
Milosevic agreed to aerial monitoring of Yugoslav compliance in
addition to the stationing of monitors on the ground.
	   The allies issued an ``activation order'' formally putting
warplanes and other hardware belonging to NATO governments under
the command of the Supreme Allied Commander Wesley K. Clark. The
order is the last military move barring actual airstrikes.
	   Solana said the allies agreed to give Milosevic a breathing
space of four days to agree on a comprehensive deal on Kosovo.
	   Holbrooke talked with Milosevic in Belgrade Monday, then flew
here to brief the NATO envoys and to meet with Polish Foreign
Minister Bronislaw Geremek whose country now heads the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
	   Holbrooke said a monitoring force from the OSCE ``could be a
very important'' part of the Kosovo plan.
	   ``We think that's a very positive, potentially positive
development and we welcome it,'' Holbrooke said of OSCE involvement
in solving the Kosovo crisis. Russia and Milosevic also back this.
	   Geremek said the 54-nation regional security organization could
send thousands of unarmed civilians to verify a Kosovo settlement.
	   Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev said in Moscow Monday
Milosevic had agreed to allow 1,500 international observers to
monitor compliance with U.N. demands to halt the crackdown in
Kosovo.
	   Officials hailed the issuance of the ``activation orders,''
which put NATO effectively on a war footing, as showing the
alliance's resolve to end the violence in Kosovo, where hundreds of
people have been killed and an estimated 275,000 uprooted since
February's crackdown on ethnic Albanian rebels.
	   After the four days expires, Supreme Allied Commander Wesley K.
Clark will no longer need any approval from the 16 NATO governments
and can proceed only in consultation with Solana, NATO officials
said.
</TEXT>
