w2181 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LatinAmericanBriefs     10-12 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Latin American Briefs,0712 </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Bolivia, Peru and Mexico.

<TEXT>
	   LIMA, Peru (AP) _ President Alberto Fujimori named a new foreign
minister Monday after the last minister resigned in the middle of
talks to end a dispute with Ecuador that led to war in 1995.
	   Fernando de Trazegnies, a former head of Peru's delegation in
the peace talks, replaces Eduardo Ferrero, who resigned Oct. 2.
	   Analysts say Ferrero resigned when Fujimori decided to take over
negotiations himself, sidelining the foreign ministry and Ferrero.
	   The talks are snagged over where to draw 49 miles (78
kilometers) of unmarked border shared by Ecuador and Peru in the
forested Cordillera del Condor region.
	   Ecuador and Peru have fought wars in 1941, 1981 and 1995 _ the
last two over the disputed stretch of Andean foothills.
	   Nationalist sentiments are strong in both countries, making
territorial concessions by the leaders unacceptable back home,
analysts say.
	   ___
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ It's hard to paper over 50 million pesos
(dlrs 5 million), but Mexico City's opposition government can't
figure out how else paper costs could have dropped by 80 percent
since it took office nine months ago.
	   The Mexico City comptroller general's office is investigating
former government authorities suspected of rigging contracts for
paper and other supplies, the newspaper Reforma reported Monday.
	   Comisa, the company that buys supplies for the Mexico City
government, revealed that prices for paper products have dropped by
up to 80 per cent during the administration of Mayor Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas of the leftist Democratic Revolution Party.
	   Prices for the paper used to make subway tickets alone dropped
from 46,000 pesos (dlrs 4,600) to 10,000 pesos (dlrs 1,000) a ton,
Comisa director Salvador Nava told Reforma.
	   The Cardenas administration has investigated several former city
officials of the long-ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party over
alleged corruption and embezzlement.
	   ___
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ With the peso collapsed and interest rates
sky-high in 1995, Mexico's Supreme Court negotiated a sweetheart
deal allowing employees to get loans at 1994 interest rates, news
media reported Monday.
	   The news reports followed a Supreme Court decision last week to
let banks charge compound interest on loans _ charging interest on
interest _ despite a debtors group's argument that the practice was
illegal.
	   It was unclear whether any of the 11 Supreme Court justices
benefited from the reported sweetheart deal. Neither the court nor
the bank were immediately available for comment.
	   News media suggested the recent ruling could have been a
conflict of interest and Xavier Gomex Coronel, head of the National
Bar of Lawyers, told the Reforma newspaper that he would call for
the justices' impeachment for failing to recuse themselves from the
bank interest case.
	   When the Mexican peso collapsed in December 1994, interest rates
jumped from about 25 percent to more than 110 percent. Many
borrowers, already unable to make payments, watched their debts
spiral further out of control.
	   ___ 
	   LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) _ The United States Embassy suspended its
search Monday for a single-engine plane carrying a missionary
family from Minnesota that disappeared two weeks ago in the
Bolivian rain forests.
	   The search has ended with the plane not found, said a statement
by the World Gospel Mission. The group said it would ask for an
expanded search.
	   The plane disappeared two weeks ago Monday while flying from the
village of Yucuma on the eastern slopes of the Andes to the city of
Santa Cruz.
	   Bolivian air force and missionary planes and helicopters have
combed a densely forested area in the middle of the country, said
Ron Gouge, a member of the World Gospel Mission in Santa Cruz, 450
miles (720 kilometers) east of La Paz.
	   Aboard the missing plane were U.S. missionary and pilot John
Henry Trosen of Wadena, Minnesota.; his wife, Masako Ari Trosen,
originally from Kyoto, Japan, but now a US citizen; their children,
Isaiah Tsubasa Trosen, 3, and Sophia Hikari Trosen, 9 months;
Bolivian pastor Juan Carlos Suazo, 31; seminary student Jhonny
Mamani; and Mamani's wife, Silveria Lucia Pinto.
</TEXT>
