w2183 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-US-Lidia'sCookin     10-12 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-US-Lidia's Cooking,0713 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lidia, oh, Lidia _ the new U.S. television cooking star
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo NY350 &QL; 
 &UR; By DOUGLAS J. ROWE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ From antipasti to zuppe to dolci, Lidia
Matticchio Bastianich displays her virtuosity in making the full
meal. Anyone who's eaten her food knows she's the real deal _ and
she's becoming a big deal in the nation's culinary consciousness.
	   Her weekly half-hour cooking series, ``Lidia's Italian Table,''
is premiering on U.S. public television network stations this
month. The companion cookbook already is in bookstores, and her
latest eatery, Lidia's Restaurant, will open later this month in
Kansas City, Missouri. It is her first venture outside of New York,
where she's involved in four restaurants.
	   She's even started a line of pasta sauces and a tour company
with daughter Tanya and a family friend that conducts gourmet trips
to her native Italy.
	   If all of that sounds like she should cry ``basta!'' _ enough! _
she simply explains that her full plate of activities is ``part of
my evolution,'' which began 28 years ago when she and Felice, her
husband at the time, started a restaurant.
	   ``I think my passion _ I think? I know! _ my passion for food
came really during my formative years when I spent a lot of time
with my maternal grandmother and grandfather ... .They grew
everything we ate,'' she says in the opening segment of her 26-week
series. ``So I had an opportunity to really see food from the
ground up, and understand how it grows, and to understand what
makes it what it is.''
	   In an interview at her 17-year-old flagship, Felidia's
Ristorante in Manhattan, she cited an intellectual element to her
passion, too. She has taken courses in food anthropology and the
science of food _ interests that flow from her undergraduate days
as a biology major with an eye on a career in medicine. (Until she
quit school to get married, much to her mother's displeasure). Just
a few weeks ago she came back from Oxford, where she attended a
symposium on food as art, and she returns to Italy several times a
year to learn new things.
	   ``So I accumulate a lot of knowledge and there comes, I guess, a
point when you want to share this,'' she said.
	   Even with her experience in front of the camera, she admits to a
little stage fright, which initially comes across as stiffness on
the air. But she clearly relaxes as each program unwinds, and she
weaves her cooking instructions with memories of her childhood and
anecdotes about family and friends. She loosens up so much in the
second show that she even makes a mustache out of a bay leaf as she
reminisces.
	   She was born after World War II in the Italian coastal town of
Pula on Istria, a peninsula atop the Adriatic Sea. There, her
earliest recollections of food involve her little fingers stuck in
dough, kneading bread as she stood on a stool to reach the table.
	   Her grandparents had a little trattoria, more an extension of
their kitchen than a restaurant, and whatever her grandmother
cooked that day was what everybody ate.
	   After the war, her town became part of communist Yugoslavia and
her family became refugees, eventually immigrating to the United
States in 1958.
	   In the years just before that, Lidia helped a great-aunt who
cooked for a wealthy family in Trieste, and she thinks of her as
the first semiprofessional chef she worked with.
	   Once in America, she met Felice, and they opened their first
restaurant in 1971, then a second, before starting Felidia. In
between, she had son Joseph and her daughter.
	   With her son, she co-owns two other restaurants, Becco and
Frico, and they recently collaborated with TV Food Network star
Mario Batali to open Babbo, which _ like Felidia _ has earned a
rare three-star rating from The New York Times.
	   Now 51, Lidia concedes that the path to epicurean excellence has
had its downside: mostly, the pangs of guilt she suffered while the
children were growing up as she worked 16-hour days.
	   Despite that, she's close to her children as mother as well as
business partner, and she feels life has been good to her.
	   ``I did something that I loved, and I was rewarded in many ways
for it,'' she said. ``And it's time for me to share.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-ARTS-US-Lidia's Cooking; CT:i; 
