<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Columbus Day,0184 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indians protest Columbus' destruction of Mexican culture
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ A poet stripped off his clothing and climbed
naked on to a statue of Christopher Columbus in Mexico City on
Monday, to call attention to the ``destruction of the Mexican
culture'' sparked by the explorer's voyage to the Americas.
	   Jose Luis Chavez read a poem from atop the statue on the city's
main boulevard and called for the image to be replaced by one
honoring Moctezuma, one of the last Aztec rulers, the government
news agency Notimex reported.
	   More than 1,000 protesters, many dressed in Indian costumes,
marched down the Paseo de la Reforma boulevard on the 506th
anniversary of Columbus' landing, known as Dia de la Raza or Day of
the Race in Latin America. Dancers wearing plumed feather
headdresses performed indigenous ceremonies.
	   At the city's central Zocalo plaza, protest leaders called on
the government to respect indigenous customs and peace agreements
with Zapatista rebels who took up arms in 1994 to demand greater
rights for Indians in Chiapas state.
</TEXT>
