<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Train Crash,0152 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Four dead in train crash in eastern Mexico
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ A freight train collided head-on with a
passenger train Monday in eastern Mexico, killing four people and
injuring more than 50, the government news agency Notimex reported.
	   The accident apparently was caused by an error in a track
change, the television network Televisa said.
	   The passenger train, traveling to Mexico City from the Gulf
coast port city of Veracruz, crashed into the eastbound freight
train near the community of Rio Blanco in Veracruz state about 210
kms (130 miles) east of Mexico City, Notimex said.
	   Roberto Garcia Pena, an official with Mexico's government-owned
National Railways _ which operated the passenger train _ said the
number of injured could increase as rescue efforts continued,
Notimex reported.
	   The four people killed have not been identified, he said.
</TEXT>
