<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo,0677 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Armed with NATO order, Holbrooke meets to overcome final obstacles
</HEADLINE>
to Kosovo deal &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous to UPDATE with Milosevic's agreement to comply
with UN demands, NATO activation order. &QL; 
 &UR; By VESELIN TOSHKOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Armed with a NATO order moving the
alliance closer to launching airstrikes against Yugoslavia, U.S.
envoy Richard Holbrooke is trying to overcome the last obstacles to
an agreement with the Yugoslav president to defuse the Kosovo
crisis.
	   The threat of military attack appears to be working. Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic agreed Monday to comply with U.N.
demands to end his seven-month repression of Kosovo's ethnic
Albanians.
	   In New York, U.S. President Bill Clinton said late Monday that
Milosevic had agreed to allow a ``robust'' team of international
inspectors _ monitoring both by land and air _ to see that Serb
troops pull back, that refugees be allowed to return to their
homes, and that other conditions of the U.N. Security Council be
met.
	   Holbrooke was returning to the Yugoslav capital on Tuesday after
NATO gave Milosevic a 96-hour deadline to comply with the U.N.
orders.
	   The 16-nation alliance took the decision after Holbrooke flew to
NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, to brief ambassadors on his
talks with Milosevic.
	   Before heading back to Belgrade, Holbrooke told reporters
``we've had some movement ... in recent days and hours'' and that
he was returning ``to see if we can build on that.''
	   Shortly afterward, Clinton said that the NATO alliance had
agreed to delay military air strikes for four days to allow time
for international inspectors to verify that Milosevic has fully met
his commitments on withdrawing forces from Kosovo and initiating
peace negotiations.
	   ``Commitments are not compliance,'' Clinton said in an impromptu
statement after a campaign fund-raising event. ``Balkan graveyards
are filled with President Milosevic's broken promises.''
	   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said there would be about
2,000 inspectors.
	   Kosovo is a province of Serbia, the main republic of Yugoslavia.
Ninety percent of its 2 million people are ethnic Albanians, many
of whom want to secede. The Serbs, however, consider Kosovo part of
their historic heartland.
	   In Brussels, Holbrooke met with Polish Foreign Minister
Bronislaw Geremek, whose country currently heads the 54-nation
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
	   Diplomatic sources have suggested the OSCE, headquartered in
Vienna, Austria, could oversee the observer mission.
	   In the Kosovo capital of Pristina, a senior ethnic Albanian
leader, Fehmi Agani, said that an observer force ``could prove
useful and provide a way out of the Kosovo crisis without further
war.'' Agani is head of the ethnic Albanian team set up to
negotiate with Belgrade authorities.
	   As Holbrooke was returning to Belgrade, NATO Secretary-General
Javier Solana announced the alliance had issued an ``activation
order'' placing military resources on a war footing.
	   ``We have to maintain this pressure,'' Solana told a news
conference.
	   Solana said the order formally places warplanes and other
military hardware under the command of the Supreme Allied Commander
Wesley K. Clark. He said order was for both ``limited air strikes
and a phased air campaign'' against Yugoslavia.
	   Milosevic launched the crackdown on Feb. 28 against the Kosovo
Liberation Army, which is battling for independence for Kosovo.
	   The United States and the Europeans oppose the KLA's goal of
independence, fearing it would fuel calls for a ``Greater Albania''
uniting ethnic Albanian communities in other countries of the
southern Balkans.
	   Although the KLA has opposed a negotiated settlement short of
full independence, the Serbs have beaten the guerrillas in recent
fighting.
	   Diplomats hope that if the crackdown ends, most Albanians will
eventually support autonomy within the Yugoslav federation rather
than independence.
</TEXT>
