w2214 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UN-USArrears     10-12 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-US Arrears,0551 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US could lose vote in General Assembly if Congress doesn't approve
</HEADLINE>
money &QL; 
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ The United States could lose its vote in
the General Assembly if Congress doesn't approve close to dlrs 200
million in U.N. payments as part of the budget being debated in
Washington, officials say.
	   U.S. lawmakers agreed Monday to give themselves two more days to
try to wrangle out an agreement. Still being debated was the final
amount to be paid to the U.N. regular and peacekeeping budgets.
	   Washington would automatically lose its vote in the 185-member
assembly Dec. 31 if lawmakers don't come up with the money.
	   While the U.S. Security Council vote isn't affected, loss of the
assembly vote would cost Washington considerable influence,
particularly as it tries to make the United Nations more efficient.
	   Washington had made reform of the world body conditional upon
its paying its bills. U.N. member states, however, are growing
increasingly frustrated that their reform efforts aren't being
matched by U.S. cash _ and increasingly reluctant to follow through
with Washington's demands as a result, diplomats say.
	   ``The issue is reform and restoring U.S. credibility,'' said
Steven Dimoff, vice president of the United Nations Association of
the United States of America, a U.N. advocacy group.
	   Richard Sklar, the deputy U.S. ambassador responsible for reform
and management, said he was optimistic Congress would approve an
estimated dlrs 197 million, which would allow the United States to
keep its vote.
	   ``I'm anticipating a passage of an appropriations bill that ...
will pass and this problem will not be with us this fall,'' he said
in an interview Monday.
	   The dlrs 197 million, coupled with an estimated dlrs 150 million
that has been authorized and is expected to be paid before Dec. 31,
would bring Washington just over the threshold necessary to keep
the vote, according to top U.N. financial official, Joseph E.
Connor.
	   The money comes from payment of current U.N. assessments.
	   Still unresolved, however, is the issue of what the United
Nations estimates is the dlrs 1.3 billion in arrears owed by the
United States. A bill that would authorize dlrs 819 million of the
payments has yet to be sent to the White House, U.S. officials say.
	   But even if it escapes a presidential veto, the bill contains so
many conditions that settlement of the past U.N. dues seems
unlikely, said Dimoff. As a result, the threat of a loss of vote
will return next year, and the year after unless Washington gets
its payments up to date, he said.
	   Washington isn't the only one threatened, however. The United
Nations too, is suffering from the lost money _ an estimated dlrs
2.5 million in unpaid dues.
	   Because of the shortfall, the United Nations has found itself
borrowing more an more from a fund for peacekeeping costs, which
then makes it indebted to member states who contribute to the fund.
	   ``The financial state of the United Nations is precarious,''
Connor told a recent U.N. budget committee meeting, adding the
shortfall threatened the United Nations' ability to simply do its
job.
</TEXT>
