<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis Glance,0985 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tennis Glance
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By BOB GREENE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 
 &UR; STARS &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   _ Michael Chang won his 12th title in Asia, defeating Goran
Ivanisevic 4-6, 6-1, 6-2 at the Heineken Open in Shanghai, China.
	   _ Tim Henman upset Andre Agassi 6-4, 6-3, 3-6, 6-4 to capture
the Swiss Indoors in Basel, Switzerland.
	   _ Mariano Puerta beat fellow Argentine Franco Squillari 6-3, 6-2
to win the Campionati Internazionali di Sicilia in Palermo, Sicily.
	   _ Sandrine Testud won the Porsche Grand Prix with a 7-5, 6-3
victory over Lindsay Davenport in Filderstadt, Germany.
	   _ John Fitzgerald stopped Bjorn Borg 7-5, 6-3 in the final of
the MTN Champions in Pretoria, South Africa.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; SPEAKING &QC; 
	   ``I've dreamed of being the best ever since I was a little
kid.'' _ Lindsay Davenport, after reaching the No. 1 world ranking.
	   ``It's no drama that I'll be the No. 2 for a little while. It's
good for the motivation.'' _ Martina Hingis, after being replaced
at No. 1 by Lindsay Davenport.
	   ``Five weeks in Europe. That's a big commitment.'' _ Pete
Sampras, on his chase for points in his bid to finish as No. 1 in
men's tnenis for a record sixth straight year.
	   ``It's possible. But first I need to be able to win.'' _ Andre
Agassi, talking about his chances of finishing the year ranked No.
1 after losing the final in Basel, Switzerland.
	   ``Women's tennis is very, very hot worldwide. There's great
demand for tournaments on the women's game right now.'' _ Mike
Davies, Pilot Pen tournament president, on keeping the women's
event in New Haven, Conn., while selling the men's tournament to a
promoter in Austria.
	   ``I won't be able to play for several weeks. It's been a very
difficult and very long year. My body's telling me it's tired.'' _
Jana Novotna, who is sidelined with a bad back.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; SITE FOR FINAL &QC; 
	   Italy and Sweden will battle in Milan when they meet in the
Davis Cup final Dec. 4-6. The matches will be played indoors on a
slow clay surface expected to benefit the host team. The Italians,
who upset the United States in the semifinals, will be in their
first Davis Cup final since 1980. Italy won the title in 1976.
Defending champion Sweden, heading to its 12th final, will be
shooting for its seventh Davis Cup trophy.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; SIDELINED &QC; 
	   Not only did she lose her No. 1 ranking, Martina Hingis also
picked up an ankle injury at the Porsche Grand Prix. Because of the
injury, HIngis has pulled out of this week's European Championships
in Zurich, Switzerland. Hingis also retired from her Grand Slam Cup
semifinal in Munich, Germany, against Patty Schnyder because of
cramps.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; STYLISH LEADER &QC; 
	   Guy Forget is the new French Davis Cup and Fed Cup captain. The
33-year-old Forget succeeds Yannick Noah who stepped down from the
twin posts to spend more time in the United States with his family.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; SAMPRAS STREAK &QC; 
	   If Pete Sampras finishes a record sixth consecutive year as No.
1, he could have Boris Becker to thank. Becker, who won the
CA-Trophy tournament in Vienna, Austria, two years ago, gave his
wild card to this year's tourney to Sampras for ``sporting
reasons.'' Sampras needs as many ranking points as possible if he
is to beat the record he shares with Jimmy Connors. Seven of the
top 10 players will be competing in this week in Vienna.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; SELLING THE GAME &QC; 
	   The Pilot Pen men's tournament is no more. Citing financial
losses, tournament chairman Butch Buchholz said the event has been
sold to a promoter in Kitzbuhel, Austria, for dlrs 1.7 million. For
the past eight years, the tournament has served as a warm-up to the
U.S. Open. But in addition to the financial losses, the ATP Tour
planned to shuffle the dates, making it less likely to draw
big-name players. The women's tournament remains in New Haven,
Conn., where it outdrew the men's event last year.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; STEFFI RETURNING &QC; 
	   Steffi Graf will make her latest comeback from injury at the
Advanta Championships in Philadelphia next month. The 29-year-old
German underwent surgery on her hand three weeks ago,just the
latest of a string of injury setbacks this year. The wrist injury
forced her to withdraw from the Filderstadt, Germany, event last
week and the Ladies Kremlin Cup in Moscow later this month.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; SURFACE WORRIES &QC; 
	   Five of the world's top 10 women tennis players are due in
Moscow for the Kremlin Cup later this month, but Russia's financial
problems could keep the court from being ready. The indoor surface
is being shipped to Moscow, but the tournament says it can't afford
the import duties. ``We simply don't have the money to pay the
duties,'' said tournament general director Yakov Shakhtin.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; SCHNYDER, ANNA IN CHASE &QC; 
	   A pair of teenagers, Patty Schnyder and Anna Kournikova, are the
latest qualifiers for the season-ending Chase Championships of the
Corel WTA Tour. It marks the first time either has qualified for
the event.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; SITES TO SURF &QC; 
	   Zurich: www.european-championships.com/
	   Vienna: www.creditanstalt.co.at/ca-trophy/
	   Singapore: www.heineken.com/events/sing_open_98.html
	   Moscow: www.kremlin-cup.ru/
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; Tournaments this week &QC; 
 &UR; ATP Tour &QC; 
	   dlrs 675,000 CA Tennis Trophy, carpet, Vienna, Austria
	   dlrs 575,000 Heineken Open, carpet, Singapore
 &UR; Corel WTA Tour &QC; 
	   dlrs 926,250 European Championships, carpet, Zurich,
Switzerland
 &UR; Senior Tour &QC; 
 &UR; Oct. 15-18 &QC; 
	   Melbourne Champions, hard, Melbourne, Australia
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; Tournaments week of Oct. 19 &QC; 
	   dlrs 975,000 IPB Czech Indoor, carpet, Ostrava, Czech Republic
	   dlrs 725,000 Grand Prix de Lyon, carpet, Lyon, France
 &UR; Corel WTA Tour &QC; 
	   dlrs 926,250 Ladies Kremlin Cup, carpet, Moscow
 &UR; Senior Tour &QC; 
 &UR; Oct. 22-25 &QC; 
	   Telstra Smart Champions, Sydney, Australia
</TEXT>
