<SLUG> BC-Japan-Bribery </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japanese oil broker sentenced to two years in prison
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ A court sentenced an influential oil broker to two
years in prison Tuesday on bribery and tax-evasion charges in a
case that shook the upper echelons of Japan's political and
business worlds.
	   Osaka-based oil wholesaler Junichi Izui, 61, was also fined 80
million yen (dlrs 683,000) by the Tokyo District Court, a court
official said on customary condition of anonymity.
	   But the court cited a lack of evidence in finding Izui innocent
of fraud charges involving alleged dubious deals with a major
Japanese oil company.
	   Izui was convicted of giving about 2.16 million yen (dlrs
18,000) in bribes in 1995 to Tsuneharu Hattori, the former
president of Japan's newest international airport near Osaka, in
exchange for a lucrative airport maintenance contract for an
acquaintance.
	   Hattori has already been convicted of receiving the bribes and
was sentenced to an 18-month prison term.
	   In testimony before a parliamentary committee last November,
Izui named three ruling party politicians, including current Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi, as among those who accepted political
contributions from him.
	   All three politicians said the donations did not violate
political fund-raising rules and denied giving any favors to Izui
in return.
	   Izui has also claimed making payments to top bureaucrats and
business leaders.
	   Two top Mitsubishi Oil officials resigned their positions last
year to take responsibility over a string of shady deals with Izui.
	   As many as 46 officials from the Ministry of International Trade
and Industry were reprimanded after they admitted to receiving free
meals or rounds of golf from Izui.
 &UR; (km)
</TEXT>
