<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar rises against yen, Tokyo stocks lower in morning trading
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with midday trading &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar was higher against the yen at
midday Tuesday on hopes Japan's central bank may further ease
credit. Japanese stock prices fell on profit-taking after Monday's
rally.
	   The dollar bought 118.41 yen at midday, up 1.69 yen from late
Monday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 117.63
yen overnight.
	   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 30.44 points, or 0.22
percent, to end morning trading at 13,524.57 after losing more than
250 points earlier in the session. On Monday, the Nikkei surged
675.04 points, or 5.24 percent.
	   Japanese investors bought the dollar on growing speculation the
Bank of Japan may announce a further easing of its monetary policy
after its policy board meeting later Tuesday, traders said.
	   Last month, the BOJ lowered short-term interest rates in an
attempt to lessen a reported credit crunch among small firms
affected by the nation's recession-hit economy.
	   Lower interest rates tend to make a nation's currency less
attractive to investors.
	   But the dollar failed to climb further because of selling orders
made through U.S. banks. Some traders said the sellers were U.S.
hedge funds.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, share prices fell on profit-taking
after a big rise Monday, when the Nikkei rallied following the
passage of legislation aimed at revitalizing Japan's debt-ridden
banking system.
	   Traders said the downside for stocks was supported by the steep
overnight rise in New York and a political breakthrough on key
Japanese banking bills.
	   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average closed Monday's
trading session at 8,001.47 points, up 101.95, or 1.3 percent.
	   Among Tuesday's early gainers were some banking issues, which
were bought following news that the ruling Liberal Democratic Party
and two political allies agreed on a new framework for pumping
public funds into the ailing banking system to recapitalize
debt-plagued banks.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was down 4.63, or 0.45 percent, to 1,018.71. The
TOPIX closed up 40.84 points, or 4.16 percent, the day before.
	   The yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government
bond fell to 0.865 percent from Monday's finish of 0.900 percent,
driving its price up to 108.34 yen from 108.01 yen.
 &UR; (km-may-dj)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:f; 
(REG:ASIA;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
