<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Train Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0205 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Four dead in train crash in eastern Mexico
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with more than 100 injured; crewman
missing. Details on crash. No pickup. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ A freight train collided head-on with a
passenger train Monday in eastern Mexico, killing at least four
people and injuring more than 100, the government news agency
Notimex reported.
	   The accident was caused by human error: either a dispatcher
incorrectly directed the passenger train onto the wrong track, or
the train operators misunderstood the directions, according to Luis
Ramiro Sosa Lugo, director of the government-owned National
Trainways.
	   The passenger train, traveling to Mexico City from the Gulf
coast port city of Veracruz, crashed into the eastbound freight
train near the community of Rio Blanco in Veracruz state about 210
kms east of Mexico City, Notimex said.
	   Four train crewmen were confirmed dead and one crewman was
missing, Transportation deputy secretary Aaron Dychter said.
	   More than 100 people were injured, he said. Eighteen people
remained hospitalized Monday night, including six people with
serious injuries and two others in critical condition, he said.
</TEXT>
