w2259 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Singapore-Philippines     10-12 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Philippines </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippines' Estrada to consult with other Asian leaders on APEC
</HEADLINE>
attendance
 &UR; By DAVID THURBER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Philippine President Joseph Estrada said
Tuesday he will consult with other Asian leaders before deciding
whether to attend an Asia-Pacific summit in Malaysia because of the
arrest of former Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim.
	   Estrada has expressed concern several times about Anwar, whom he
said he considers a friend.
	   ``I have not made my decision yet,'' he told a group of business
and political leaders in his first major overseas speech as
president. He said it is important to attend the November meeting
of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum in Malaysia, but
that Anwar should also receive fair treatment.
	   ``I think all of us here believe that due process and human
rights should be respected,'' he said, to loud applause from the
audience.
	   Asked afterward when he will make a decision, Estrada said he
would talk first with other Asian leaders.
	   Estrada, who has been counseled by many of his advisers to
attend the APEC summit, was to leave Singapore later Tuesday for a
hastily arranged evening meeting with Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie, who has also spoken out against Anwar's arrest.
	   Anwar was fired by Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad on
Sept. 2 after the two differed on economic policies. Anwar then
launched a nationwide campaign against Mahathir and was arrested
Sept. 20. He has appeared for court hearings with a black eye and
neck brace, and has said he was beaten by police.
	   Estrada is making is first overseas trip since taking office in
June. In his speech to the East Asia Economic Summit he said the
region's embattled economies should forge closer ties to withstand
future shocks and that they should contribute to international
efforts to forge a new world economic structure.
	   ``East Asia must be part of the effort to create a new global
financial system for the 21st century,'' he said. ``All of us, not
just a few economies, must contribute.''
	   Participants in the economic summit, sponsored by the World
Economic Forum, a private agency based in Switzerland, have
disagreed on how the region can best recover from the financial
crisis that struck 15 months ago.
	   Estrada said the world is facing uncharted territory because of
the phenomenon of massive amounts of capital moving from country to
country at electronic speed, ``bloating economies to fragile
bubbles as they rush in, and shaking economies to their foundations
as they take flight.''
</TEXT>
